<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-REPUB-FUNDS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH CRITICIZED OVER FUND-RAISING PARTY'S HOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's billed as a fun, free summer picnic, a great
chance for the regular folks to mingle with Republican
officeholders at a magnificent island estate and feast on hot dogs
and barbecue, tofu and stir-fry. The main attraction is House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, who will be trying to establish a new
category in the Guinness Book of World Records: greatest number of
individual photographs taken with people in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gingrich joins the festivities on Saturday at the local
Republican Party bash on Vashon Island, which could draw 10,000
people, he will also be stepping squarely into a controversy. It is
one that Democrats here are hoping to seize to their advantage in
this fall's Washington state elections, including several that
could be critical in the Republicans' bid to maintain their
majority in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The host of the picnic is Thomas Stewart, a wealthy Seattle
businessman who this year pleaded guilty to violating federal
campaign laws and paid nearly $5 million in fines, the
third-largest penalty in history for violation of those laws.
Stewart, chief executive of the privately held Services Group of
America, admitted that he gave employees $100,000 in bonuses and
directed them to give the money to Republican candidates. In
addition to the fines, Stewart served two months of home detention
at his estate on Vashon Island, near Seattle, and performed 160
hours of community service at a local soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats here have leaped to condemn the Republicans'
acceptance of Stewart's largesse in putting on the annual picnic,
whose cost is at least $100,000. And they say it is highly
inappropriate for Gingrich, a harsh critic of Democratic
fund-raising practices, to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely outrageous that he would go to this event,''
said Paul Berendt, the chairman of the Washington Democratic Party.
``It shows incredibly poor judgment that he would agree to appear
at the picnic of an admitted money launderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were quick to argue Friday that they saw nothing
wrong with Stewart's sponsorship of the picnic or Gingrich's
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This event is free,'' said Mark Pilla, spokesman for the state
Republican Party. ``None of this is about money. The speaker likes
contact with the grass roots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats need to concentrate on issues that are important
to the American people,'' Mike Shields, a spokesman for the
speaker's political office, said in a telephone interview from the
state fair in Iowa, which Gingrich attended Friday as part of an
18-day campaign and fund-raising tour around the country. ``I think
it's ironic that the Democratic state party is reduced to attacking
us over an event that is free and open to the public and just a fun
day out for a Saturday picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   The event is indeed free, including the wallet-sized photo that
anyone who is photographed with Gingrich may receive, though it is
to be followed by a closed-door fund-raiser for Republican
candidates, also to be attended by Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees will also be invited to throw ``a dollar or two'' into
a pot, allowing them to cast a ballot in a mock vote for U.S.
senator. And they can pay $20 for an 8-by-10-inch photograph with
the speaker or $70 for a photo plaque, though Pilla said all that
money would go to the photographer, not to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has used the term ``megastate'' to describe
Washington's importance to the Republicans in this fall's
elections. In the historic Republican takeover in 1994, the party
won seven of Washington's nine House seats, including that of the
incumbent Democratic speaker, Thomas Foley. Two years later, it
retained control of five of those seats by narrow margins, and many
races are expected to be intensely competitive this fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stewart, one of the biggest contributors to Republicans in the
state, has hosted the picnic at his 163-acre ranch for years. Last
year the guest of honor was Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader,
and in 1996 it was Jack Kemp, the Republican vice-presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The illegal contributions were part of a scheme to circumvent
the $1,000 limit on individual contributions to a campaign. Stewart
admitted to them as part of a plea bargain with federal
prosecutors. In court this March, he expressed regret and declared,
``It won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call to Stewart's office Friday was returned by
Lincoln Ferris, his company's vice president for community
relations, who provided logistical details about the picnic but
declined to comment on the Democrats' criticism of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the party's picnic,'' Ferris said, adding that
Stewart was ``just providing a venue and the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's aide, Shields, said the speaker was unlikely to break
the record listed in the Guinness book for most hands shaken by a
public figure at a public event: 8,513, by President Theodore
Roosevelt at the White House on New Year's Day 1907. But, he said,
Guinness representatives planned to be on hand for Saturday's
picture taking, which might form the basis of a new entry in the
next edition.
</P>
<P>
   At about six seconds per picture, the speaker could have his
photograph taken with 600 people per hour. He is so eager to
establish a bona fide record that he plans to be on hand for at
least five hours, and, said Shields, ``that's longer than he
usually spends in one place at one time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
