<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COL-HNS &LR;      08-22 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Waveland gang 
chasing history
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ There is a nervous tension in the air as Sammy Sosa walks
toward the plate and Rich Buhrke takes his position.
</P>
<P>
   Buhrke tugs on the bill of his cap and bounces up and down,
kicking his feet to about shoulder width apart. He smacks his hand
into his glove. He takes a few steps backward, looks into the
gleaming sun and stands just inches off the line _ the crosswalk
line.
</P>
<P>
   We are standing among the baseball legends chasing history.
Sosa, Buhrke.
</P>
<P>
   We are at the corner of Waveland and Kenmore, behind the
left-field wall of Wrigley Field, where the rumble of the El
clatters windows, the smell of bratwurst and stale Old Style is in
the air and legends roam.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hits home runs into the streets here. Buhrke and a unique
group of veteran Waveland Avenue ``ball-hawks'' chase them down.
</P>
<P>
   It is here where a group of about 10 regular ball-hawks, all of
them hardened veterans, all of them friendly, spend game days in
lawn chairs under a shade tree at Waveland and Kenmore. Near a
street light where a Dominican Republic flag hangs in reverence to
Sosa, they swig beer, trade stories and talk Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   There is no radio play-by-play action in the background, yet
with one casual glance at the Wrigley scoreboard they all seem to
know which player is up, which is on deck, lefty or righty, and
when to hop into position.
</P>
<P>
   They have become friends from their time spent chasing home runs
together on Waveland. They chip in for beer, go on road trips
together, travel to spring training and even get together every
year for what they call ``winter meetings,'' the details of which
sound an awful lot like a bachelor party.
</P>
<P>
   They respect each other's ``position.'' Buhrke stands smack in
the middle of the crosswalk on Kenmore. This is the position of
choice, and remarkable experience has earned Buhrke this place.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Vangeloff is off on Waveland, a bit back from the curb
behind the bleachers. Thick-chested Andy Mielke plays left-center.
Johnny Rosenstein inches closer to the foul pole. Dave Davison is
here, Jerry Pritikin is there.
</P>
<P>
   They have great skills and instincts, but few will admit to
being in the same class as Buhrke, 52, who has been chasing home
runs on Waveland Avenue for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   He has been to at least half of all Cubs home games since he was
12. He has flagged down balls from Mickey Mantle (in an All-Star
Game), Ernie Banks and Willie Mays. Once, then-Cub Joe Pepitone
came running out of the stadium in full uniform after Ron Santo hit
a significant home run. Pepitone ran straight toward Buhrke and
asked for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   From the dugout, Pepitone saw where the ball traveled over the
wall and figured Buhrke probably caught it. He had.
</P>
<P>
   Buhrke has covered every inch of the streets surrounding the
Wrigley outfield wall, from the flower beds lining the apartments
on Kenmore to the tables lining Murphy's Bar behind right field.
</P>
<P>
   Buhrke has caught 2,936 home runs, the majority from batting
practice. His most prized catches have been Santo's 300th homer
(the one Pepitone retrieved in exchange for other signed balls and
bats), Ryne Sandberg's 100th home run and four grand slams,
including one by Banks.
</P>
<P>
   He is the father of all ball-hawks. And this is his time to
shine.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, along with the Cardinals' Mark McGwire, is chasing Roger
Maris' record of 61.
</P>
<P>
   This week has been particularly important for Buhrke and the
ball-hawks, because McGwire was in town earlier and San Francisco's
Barry Bonds, who is one home run short of his 400th, was in town
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenalin rush is unbelievable when you get one,'' Buhrke
said. ``This is the closest I'll ever get to the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The others in the group have real-world rsums that range from
computer analysts to train conductors to ``career Bleacher Bum,''
as one put it.
</P>
<P>
   Buhrke, who heads a security staff at a Chicago department
store, rarely has seen a Cubs game from inside the stadium. He is
lanky and trim and looks much younger than his age, wearing a gray
Cubs T-shirt, a crisp hat and dark hair neatly cropped above his
ears.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly hasn't lost a step, although these are among the most
challenging days the ball-hawks have seen. The streets have been
bustling with fly-by-nighters showing up, hoping to catch history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 300 people out here when McGwire was in town,'' Mielke
said. ``That was ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ball-hawks are convinced that among the increasing
numbers roaming Waveland are hired guns brought in by professional
collectors and memorabilia dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want those 50th and 57th (NL record for home runs) home
runs from Sosa, so they can get big money,'' Buhrke said.
</P>
<P>
   But they'll need a lot of luck beating these Waveland ball-hawks
to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   They are the best of the best. During the Home Run Derby when
the Cubs hosted the 1990 All-Star Game, the ball-hawks accounted
for 24 of the 28 home runs hit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proudest moment,'' Mielke said.
</P>
<P>
   This week when McGwire hit No. 48 out of the park, it was
Vangeloff who caught the ball amid a swarm of fans, falling as he
squeezed it and then being mobbed by some who tried to pry the ball
loose. Vangeloff's ball-hawk friends came to his rescue, pulling
people off the pile and making sure Vangeloff kept the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not you that gets it, we all hope that it's one of
us,'' Rosenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as Sosa was looking for his 49th and 50th shots of the
year and Bonds for the 400th of his career, the ball-hawks were in
top form. During batting practice, Sosa hit just one ball out. But
the ball-hawks got it.
</P>
<P>
   On another shot out of the yard during batting practice,
Rosenstein made what Buhrke described as one of the best catches he
had seen in 40 years on Waveland. As the ball sailed over the wall,
Rosenstein sprinted under it, but a taxi was turning from Kenmore
onto Waveland directly in line with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstein jumped onto the moving taxi, knocked the ball off the
hood and covered it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you're out here for,'' Buhrke said. ``Most people
who try to catch one drop it, because they can't handle the
pressure. You have to know what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   When game time arrived, the mood shifted to serious every time
Sosa stepped up. Everyone got into position. When Sosa popped out
the first time up, the next sound was beer bottles popping open.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Sosa doubled. Nice, but no home run. Finally in the
bottom of the fifth, Sosa sent one deep to left-center field. The
crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   It might be. It could be.
</P>
<P>
   Ball-hawks from every direction broke into frenzied sprints
toward Mielke's position, but the ball fell into that most
frustrating of places _ over the fence but not far enough to hit
the street. The ball-hawks came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there. I had it,'' Mielke said. ``Just a little more,
and it was mine. Some fat guy in the bleachers got it. That's
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the game was just a tease. Bonds never
threatened to get his 400th. Sosa never got No. 50. The ball-hawks
went home with just a couple of batting-practice balls.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, today's another day. The Astros will be in town today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the Astros,'' Mielke said. ``They've got lots of
righthanded power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
