<HEADLINE>
FUEL TRUCK ACCIDENT SHUTS DOWN LONG ISLAND EXPRESSWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, N.Y. _ A tanker truck carrying nearly 11,000 gallons of
gasoline created a weekend motorist's nightmare Friday afternoon
when it overturned on the Long Island Expressway, halting all
traffic in the heart of Nassau County for more than eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in a car, don't come to Long Island. Every road near
the expressway is completely at a standstill. It's a horror show,''
said Officer William Bendel of the Nassau County Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Among the motorists who found themselves trapped in the middle
of the stalled traffic was Mark Sedlak, who almost made it to his
destination, Exit 43, when he was forced to jam on his brakes. ``I
have just a few more exits to go,'' he said, ``but I've heard it's
completely stopped out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare began at 1:05 p.m. when the massive truck, heading
east, swerved as it attempted to avoid a car changing lanes. The
truck shuddered, jackknifed and flipped on its side in the middle
of the eastbound lanes near Exit 41, spilling nearly 150 gallons
and causing traffic on both sides of the six-lane expressway to
begin backing up, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency vehicles and firetrucks from the Jericho Fire
Department, whose station house is located just off the expressway,
quickly arrived at the scene, halted traffic in both directions and
began pumping a white chemical foam onto the roadway, smothering
the spilled gasoline whose volatile fumes filled air. In 80-degree
temperatures, the heat from the pavement increased the possibility
of an explosion, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   As a precautionary measure, the county police department ordered
the evacuation of homes in Jericho and Hicksville within a
half-mile radius of the accident. For those having nowhere else to
go, the police said they had set up temporary shelters at the State
University of New York campus at Old Westbury, which is just north
the expressway, and at the shopping mall in Hicksville south of the
accident scene, according to Officer Adele Burke.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the truck, who was not immediately identified, was
slightly injured and was taken to the Nassau County Medical Center,
according to the police.
</P>
<P>
   The expressway was closed in both directions between Exits 40
and 43, creating, in effect, a five-mile-long vacant parking lot on
a stretch of the expressway that is normally jammed with afternoon
traffic heading east from New York City. Friday, however, there was
the added ingredient of thousands of additional motorists heading
for the beaches in the Hamptons and other summer resorts on eastern
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon wore on traffic backed up to the Queens border
and jammed the Northern State Parkway, which runs parallel to and
crosses over the Long Island Expressway just a few miles east of
the overturned tanker truck.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 4 p.m., a second tanker, operated by the same
company, Island Transportation Corp. of West Babylon, which
distributes gasoline to service stations throughout Long Island,
pulled up alongside the toppled tanker and began the tedious and
time consuming task of off-loading fuel from the disabled truck.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that the process could take at least three hours and
said that the roadway might remain closed until 10 p.m., with the
westbound lanes expected to be the first to reopen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
