<HEADLINE>
A RITUAL FOR SUMMER THEATER IN THE PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDISON, N.J. _ It is early on a sunny afternoon in the heart of
Roosevelt Park and, as usual, there are two growing lines of mostly
empty lawn chairs. A few people are actually sitting in the chairs
_ reading, sleeping, playing cards _ as if the children running
around nearby have created an imaginary bus to nowhere and
persuaded everyone else to play along.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, these are the ticket lines for Plays in the Park,
Middlesex County's open-air, bring-your-own-chair summer theater
series, now in its 36th season. Although the ticket booth does not
open until 5:30 p.m. and show time is not until 8:30, theater fans
often begin gathering shortly after noon, many with multiple chairs
to hold spaces for themselves and others.
</P>
<P>
   The performances, mostly of big-name musicals, are
sophisticated, semiprofessional productions not unlike those in
hundreds of other summer theater programs, including the New York
Shakespeare Festival's summer series, Shakespeare in the Park. What
sets Plays in the Park apart is the unspoken philosophy shared by
many of its fans: if you have to bring your own chair, you might as
well get the best seat in the house.
</P>
<P>
   The long wait in the lawn chairs has become a bizarre ritual, as
much a part of the Plays in the Park experience as seeing the
shows, and strict rules are posted on signs along the paths from
the parking area to the small brown hut that serves as a ticket
booth. The first rule is that while in line, people must remain
with their chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not with your chairs, the chairs get thrown out,''
warned Bob Kay, 58, who was first in line for the opening
performance of ``My Fair Lady'' earlier this month. Kay, who has
been attending the shows for more than 15 years, said enforcement
can be strict, particularly later in the afternoon, and added that
his chairs had been tossed from the line by the police on a
previous occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do go through the chairs, it's around 4 o'clock or a
little after, so I try to beat the system,'' said Kay, who put his
chairs in line about 1 p.m. and returned at 3:30, thereby evading
the surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   But even the pros slip up sometimes. With two hours to go before
the gates opened, Kay had forgotten his newspaper and was searching
desperately for reading material.
</P>
<P>
   Once the gates open at 5:30, audience members can pay for
admission ($3 for adults, free for children) and place their chairs
in the seating area of the Stephen J. Capestro Theater. They are
then free to leave and return for the show.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Detective William Van Doren of the Middlesex County police, who
has patrolled Plays in the Park shows for more than 20 years, said
unattended chairs pose a hazard. When the line pushes forward, they
get knocked over, he said. People trip over them, or get their feet
caught in the slats. ``As soon as everybody sees I'm here, they
start running to their chairs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the lines at Plays in the Park say that despite the
informality, etiquette generally prevails, and only the police have
been known to remove unattended chairs. Those who leave their
chairs as place holders tend to stay inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   Farther back in line were Dave and Gloria Kuchinsky, who had
driven 40 minutes from their home in Jamesburg to meet their
daughter-in-law Joy and grandchildren Michelle, 9, and Reuben, 5.
The Kuchinskys planned to buy their tickets, set up their chairs
and break for supper before returning at show time.
</P>
<P>
   Joy Kuchinsky, who lives nearby in Highland Park, had called for
a pizza to be ready at exactly 6:15. She would pick it up and take
the children home to meet her husband and eat. Her in-laws opted
for the picnic tables in the park instead. ``We have cheese
sandwiches,'' Gloria Kuchinsky said. ``And coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents drop off a child to wait in line. For example, Tom
LeCompte, 13, of Metuchen had instructions to buy tickets for his
mother, aunt and two sisters. He was in a lawn chair reading a
thick biography of Richard Nixon, required summer reading for this
fall's English class. ``I'm the oldest child,'' he said, explaining
why the place holding fell to him. ``My mom has other things to do,
like cook dinner and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tom read, the two lines behind him, one for each of the
ticket booth windows, continued to grow. Shortly before 5:30, the
producing director of Plays in the Park, Gary Cohen, announced that
ticket sales were about to begin. With a great chorus of aluminum
scraping on asphalt, the chairs were folded up and the lines
pressed ahead. ``We're a community theater, but we are a very
high-level community theater,'' Cohen said on another day this
month as he prepared for a rehearsal of ``Jerry's Girls,'' a
variety show featuring the songs of Jerry Herman that opens Tuesday
and is the last show of the season. Each April, several hundred
people audition for the four summer shows, Cohen said. ``There are
people who came to the shows as babies, who are in the shows as
teen-agers and wind up going on to careers.'' Some cast members
have gone on to Broadway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The magician David Copperfield is part of the lore. A native of
Metuchen, he performed in ``Plain and Fancy'' in 1973 in his
pre-magic days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
