<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY_TIMMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH TIME OFF   
 TIMMS HOPES TO TURN CORNER IN PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fix that Michele Timms has found herself in this season
didn't just happen. It was a well-intentioned, thought-out plan
gone awry that's had the Mercury point guard playing catch-up to
her expectations and admittedly falling short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a Monday or a Wednesday?'' said the Australian, whose
feelings about her future change daily. ``I'm just really
frustrated with myself. One day, it's like this is the end, and the
next day, I wake up and think we'll have four weeks (of preseason)
together next season and it won't be like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I'm going to throw it in before 2000 because
that's my goal, to play in the Olympics in my own back yard and
hopefully win a medal. I definitely don't want to finish my career
on this note.''
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong was that Timms had no idea how to properly go on
holiday from a job on which she worked virtually non-stop for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   In succession, she played for BTV Wuppertal of the German League
(1995-96 EuroLeague champion), the Sydney Flames of the Australian
Women's National Basketball League (spring 1996 Player of the
Year), the Australian Olympic team (summer 1996 bronze medalist),
Wuppertal again (1996-97 EuroLeague runner-up) and the Mercury
(summer 1997 playoff semifinals) in the inaugural season of the
WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced by a league-low 41 points against New York in the
playoffs, the Mercury's tank was as empty as its floor leader's.
</P>
<P>
   So for the first time in a professional career that began in
1984, Timms put basketball completely aside except for a WNBA
postseason European tour and the television analysis she did of
Arizona State and Arizona women's college games. A reprieve of more
than seven months set Timms' head straight but did nothing for her
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``She needed that mental break, but she's the first to say that
having that long (break), she lost the edge of her game shape,''
said Timms' agent, Hugh Sandie. ``And that's the basis of Michele's
game. This has been a valuable lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory that Timms could join the Goldmark Opals (Australian
National Team) in April and play herself into WNBA shape by the
completion of the World Championships only partially stood up. In
nine World games, she averaged only 25.1 minutes _ the rest going
to now Mercury teammate Kristi Harrower and Annie La Fleur _ and
returned two days before the Mercury season began with a new
offense to digest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Learning new offense &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I handled myself really well at the World Championships
_ and we did good enough and got the bronze medal (8-1 record) _
it's a little bit different here,'' Timms said. ``It was really
hard at first when I came back, point guard, not knowing the
offense, having to lead when you don't know what you're leading.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Graf, assistant coach with the Opals and the Mercury,
agreed that Timms was crying out for time off but thinks that two
months would have been sufficient, particularly for an athlete
facing the twilight of her career, when fitness retention becomes
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so, I guess, burned out and flat from Atlanta (the
Olympics) and the first season here and the hype and playing
back-to-back seasons in Australia and Germany that basically, her
body and mind shut down,'' Graf said. ``Then to start it again at
32 (Timms turned 33 in June), her body just wasn't ready. It sort
of went into shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lost a bit of speed, and with that goes a bit of
confidence, and then it becomes a battle. Battling it day in and
day out takes away from the passion.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lack of chemistry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even with Timms and five others less than a week removed from
the World Championships, the Mercury started 3-0 and was 11-3
before the lack of chemistry from missing a month of training camp
began to show. A 1-6 stretch that included five consecutive losses
ensued, and the playoff berth that seemed so secure in mid-July
became as wobbly as the year before, despite a much more talented
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Timms' scoring average dropped almost in half, from 12.1 to 6.9,
as did her steals, from 71 to 38. All her shooting percentages took
a hit. With the addition of Harrower, Timms' playing time purposely
dropped from 35.8 minutes, third in the league, to 31.1, but the
only benefit was in her turnover-to-assist ratio, which soared from
1.71 to 2.29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might not have done anything spectacular, but I feel like
I'm leading this team out on the court, which is exactly what we
needed the last six games we played in a must-win situation,''
Timms said. ``I felt like I led the team and kept my poise when I
had to and used my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Like last year, the Mercury clinched a playoff spot in the final
game of the regular season, when Timms was a season-best 5 of 6
from the free-throw line and contributed 13 points. Her match-up
with Suzie McConnell Serio will be critical to the outcome of a
best-of-three semifinal that will begin at 5 p.m. today at America
West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit I'm excited about the series,'' Timms said.
``I've been waiting all season to turn the corner, and I'm just
hoping there is still four or five games left for us. I wouldn't be
happy with anything other than being in the Grand Finals
(championship) series, because at the start of the season, I had
such high expectations.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
New vacation plans &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her new and improved vacation plans already are made. Timms will
play for the Opals in Australian tours against China and the United
States next month. Then she'll return to the WNBL for its new
October-March schedule. She already has talked with a specialist at
the Victoria Institute of Sport about how to improve her speed to
reignite the Mercury transition game in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's never been a person not to reassess and reevaluate,''
her agent said. ``She's willing to learn and extend her body life.
We haven't seen the best of Michele Timms yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's something better yet to see this season, or at
least that's how Timms is interpreting her Thursday night dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shot the rock really well,'' she recalled. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
