<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GATTI-ROBINSON-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREAKY IN AND OUT OF THE RING, GATTI PREPARES FOR A TOUGH TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arturo Gatti has a new look _ blond highlights streaked through
his brown hair _ and he claims to have a new style that he will
unveil against Ivan Robinson in a 10-round lightweight bout
Saturday at Bally's Park Place in Atlantic City as part of HBO's
``Boxing After Dark'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the barber to get a haircut and the girl said, `Why
don't you put some color in it?''' Gatti said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the colors most closely associated with Gatti the
last few years are crimson, black and blue. He is prone to
swelling, particularly around the eyes, and he gets cut.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti lost his last fight eight months ago against Angel
Manfredy when the bout was stopped in the eighth round on cuts.
Gatti has been working on new ring techniques that he hopes will
keep his face intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on not getting hit with so many right
hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The undercard should be just as exciting as the main event.
Fernando Vargas (13-0), a superb young junior middleweight who was
a member of the 1996 U.S. Olympic boxing team, meets Darren
Maciunski (16-5) in a 10-round bout, and Jose Luis Lopez, a top
welterweight title contender, will fight Ed Goins in a 10-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   The HBO broadcast is scheduled for 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti (29-2) is an exciting fighter. He can be on the verge of
being knocked out, then summon some reserve and come back to score
a knockout. He did that against Gabriel Ruelas on Oct. 4, 1997. In
that fight, Gatti looked out on his feet in the fourth round, when
Ruelas shook him with a powerful left uppercut. But Gatti rallied
and won when the fight was stopped in round 5.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why his corner and the ring doctors allowed him
to continue fighting after he sustained a deep cut that measured
about two inches in the first round of his 12-round fight against
Manfredy. The cut got worse as the fight went on. It also changed
Gatti's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan was to keep the pressure on him,'' Gatti said. ``He
talked like a warrior before the fight, but during the fight he was
looking for an exit. If that cut wasn't there, his confidence
wouldn't have been there. I knew the cut was bad, because when I
got hit on it, it hurt. But I was just determined to win the fight,
so I kept fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manfredy was one lucky opponent, because he never got hit
flush on the face. I think the referee would have let me go on if
the fight was 10 rounds. But he didn't want me in there for another
four rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatti hopes to avoid that problem with Robinson (25-2), a tough
lightweight from Philadelphia. He will need all the skills he can
muster for Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a boxer and boxers are hard to fight,'' Gatti said. ``But
Ivan's not the fighter he thinks he is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gatti and Robinson became acquainted when they trained together
with Pernell Whitaker in Virginia Beach, Va. They never sparred
against each other, but ``we ran many miles together,'' Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Robinson will be trying to stop Gatti in his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti, a former International Boxing Federation junior
lightweight champion, needs a victory against Robinson to put
himself back in contention for a lightweight title.
</P>
<P>
   He is also trying to get his personal life back together. A few
months ago he was arrested in Miami and charged with assault after
beating up a man, whom Gatti claims came after him with a knife.
Gatti said that he paid a fine and paid the man's medical bills and
that the matter is behind him.
</P>
<P>
   If Gatti can get past Robinson, things are already in place for
him to meet Cesar Bazan for the World Boxing Council lightweight
title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
