<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-ALABAMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 FILLIES TAKE AIM AT JERSEY GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jersey Girl, who has won nine of her 11 starts and seven
straight this year, will be watching from the sidelines at Saratoga
Race Course Saturday while other fillies race to overtake her on
the road to the 3-year-old championship. And two daughters of
Unbridled will be playing the lead roles: Banshee Breeze, winner of
last month's Coaching Club American Oaks, and Manistique, racing's
newest ``monster,'' who has won her three starts by a total margin
of 31 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   The scene will be the 118th running of the Alabama Stakes, the
fillies' counterpart to the Travers one week later. Six fillies are
entered in the race, which will take them a mile and a quarter
carrying 121 pounds. Jersey Girl has been sidelined with a
fractured right knee and may not race again this year. And any
filly who can win the Alabama and the Gazelle next month at Belmont
Park will be making a strong move toward catching Jersey Girl for
the title.
</P>
<P>
   Manistique is not exactly a mystery horse, although she did not
race anywhere at two because she had foot problems and also grew to
16 or 17 hands, a spectacular height for a filly. When she finally
did go to the races in May, she won at Hollywood Park by 11
lengths. One month later, again at Hollywood, she won by 10. And
one month after that, stepping up to the Hollywood Oaks at a mile
and an eighth, she won by 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question for us,'' said her trainer, John Shirreffs,
``is have we seen her best races? She's very big and very long, she
has a great head and a sharp eye. I certainly would like to have
her in a position to go for the division championship, but I think
that will be determined in the next two races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
