A7050 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BICKLEY_TOCCHET-A     08-22 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BICKLEY_TOCCHET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES' BEST MAN TURNS GROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe you can't judge a man by the company he keeps. But when
Wayne Gretzky clears out his schedule just for the pleasure of
watching you sweat in a tuxedo . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``A television crew wanted to be there,'' the Coyotes' Rick
Tocchet said. ``But I felt kind of weird about that. What if Gretz
was doing a shot and the cameras are in his face?''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, not exactly a milk mustache. But what do you expect when
an old-school throwback takes a dive for the first time in his
life?
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Tocchet will exchange vows with his fiancee, Lynne
Wilke, at a Phoenix resort. Along with Gretzky, guys like Paul
Coffey, Kevin Stevens, Rob Blake and Tony Granato have flown in for
the ceremony. It will follow a golf binge coordinated by Jeremy
Roenick, which comes in the wake of a bachelor party in Toronto
attended by 120 of his closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not nervous,'' said Tocchet, 34. ``She's been
through a lot with me the last four-five years. I've been traded so
much, she's been living with me out of a duffel bag. Besides, I've
gotten all those Philly-Pittsburgh days out of my system.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much has changed for Tocchet since arriving in Phoenix.
Plagued by back problems the previous two seasons, Tocchet
reaffirmed his spot among the league's top players in 1997-98. He
scored 26 goals before busting out in the playoffs. He brought
leadership to a team in desperate need of character. And as Keith
Tkachuk remains in Cape Cod, Mass., no closer to a new deal than he
was last summer, it's clear who is setting the tone for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody should be ticked off,'' Tocchet said. ``I
can't see anyone going into the summer feeling good about last
season. For some reason, this organization thought it was OK to
mess around for three months, then make a push in the last
two-three months. It doesn't work that way. I believe this team
really has to have a good start in October. None of this .500 at
Christmas stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   They are words that need to be heard, and if you don't believe
the ``C'' belongs on Tocchet's sweater, you haven't been paying
attention. Tocchet has already influenced the off-season habits of
his teammates, and by his suggestion, Oleg Tverdovsky, Jason Doig
and Brad Isbister spent the summer in Los Angeles working out with
Tocchet's private trainer. He has also talked to Roenick constantly
since the season ended and has lit a new fire under his teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about our young guys is they're always asking
questions,'' Tocchet said. `` `How was the Stanley Cup?' `What was
Mario Lemieux like?' `How was it when you went to the Finals?'
That's a big thrill for me, and a good sign for this
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   What this all represents is a shifting of the dressing room,
implicit acknowledgment that Tocchet is far more qualified than
Tkachuk when it comes to leadership. It is a touchy subject for
Tocchet, a guy who would never undermine a teammate and whose only
focus is winning. But he admits Tkachuk's priorities are a topic of
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of people are thinking that right now,''
Tocchet said. ``It's a bad situation for Keith because he's getting
a lot of negativity from the fans. It's too bad because if people
got to know him, he's really a good guy and he wants to win. It's
just a situation where things are real confused right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Real ridiculous, too. But if Tkachuk misses even a day of
training camp, at least the Coyotes have a window in which to shift
the captaincy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I want Keith here,'' Tocchet said. ``Will it happen? I
don't know. But either way, it has to get rectified early so we can
go into the season positively. You only have so many chances to
win, so many notches on your belt, and then you're done.''
</P>
<P>
   A feeling that will ring home in a different way on Sunday.
``I'm ready,'' he said. ``But, man, getting all the wedding plans
together? I empathize with people.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
