<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SHUT OUT RANGERS, 5-0
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
EDITORS: CORRECTS FINAL SCORE 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The New York Yankees arrived in town
yesterday in one of their worst slumps of the season. Then Chuck
Knoblauch hit the third pitch of the game over the left-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   That's all left-hander David Wells needed while pitching a
six-hit shutout in the Yankees' 5-0 victory against the Rangers
before a sellout crowd of 45,841 at The Ballpark in Arlington last
night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Yankees from matching a season-high,
three-game losing streak and was their seventh in nine games
against the Rangers this year. It also put them back on their
record-breaking victory pace after losing two games against the
Minnesota Twins. The Yankees are on pace to win 120 games, which
would shatter the 1906 Chicago Cubs' all-time record of 116
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their a good team, a complete team,'' Rangers outfielder Juan
Gonzalez said. ``They have everything, good pitching, power,
hitting, bullpen, everything. They're the best team in the majors.
Everybody is trying hard out there, but it was a good night for
Wells. He threw a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees first baseman Tino Martinez didn't do so bad either,
smashing two home runs off Rangers starter Esteban Loaiza. Derek
Jeter also hit one out against Loaiza, who dropped to 1-3 with a
4.24 earned-run average in seven starts with the Rangers since
being acquired from the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to rise to the challenge, but they're a great team,''
Loaiza said. ``I felt great, but those four home runs hurt. They
just hit good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells (16-2) has been one of the few Yankees starters who has
had trouble against the Rangers, allowing 12 runs in 82/3 innings
against them. That included five runs in six innings in a start
against them Sunday at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Yankees have proved all year that seldom do things
go bad for an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought David pitched as well as any left-hander has against
us all year,'' said Rangers manager Johnny Oates, whose team was
hitting .320 against left-handers coming into the game. ``He
spotted his fastball well, and his curve got better as the game
went on. His breaking ball was better than the last two times out
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells did walk Mark McLemore to start the first inning and gave
up a couple of singles in the second, but his defense bailed him
out with two crisply turned double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last game in New York, I was having trouble with my
mechanics,'' Wells said. ``I came out of the game tied, but I
didn't pitch very well. I wanted to redeem myself for last time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also failed to come through with rallies in the
fifth and sixth innings. Both times they had runners on first and
second with two outs, but Wells struck out Royce Clayton to end the
fifth and Ivan Rodriguez to end the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big out for me was striking out Rodriguez with two men on
base,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Wells: ``After the second or third inning, I settled down
and started pitching my game. I'm very aggressive and move my
pitches in and out. You've got to keep them on their toes. When
you've got to knock them off the plate you do it. I just tried to
battle them.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually it has been the rest of the American League trying to
battle the Yankees, and so far it's been a losing cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to play well against these guys, because it's a team
we might face when we get to the playoffs,'' outfielder Roberto
Kelly said. ``But it's a tough team to beat. You can't make many
mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
