<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS GO WITHOUT MUCH FIGHT  
 DAAL PITCHES WELL BUT STILL CAN'T NOTCH WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Diamondbacks began a new millenium here
Friday night. To their frustration, it looked a lot like the old
millenium.
</P>
<P>
   They became the first team in the major leagues to strike out
1,000 times this season in a 1-0 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies
at Veterans Stadium. They finished with eight, giving them 35 in
the three-game series and 1,003 for the season. Arizona (48-81)
lost two of the games.
</P>
<P>
   Who baffled the Diamondbacks? Right-hander Mark Portugal, 35, a
man who seemingly would look more comfortable in a recliner with a
cigarette in his mouth, a beer in one hand and a TV remote control
in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who missed most of his first season with Philadelphia
in 1997 after having elbow surgery, won his first home game for the
team by scattering five hits and striking out six in 7 innings. It
also was the 100th victory of his career and eighth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-luck loser was left-hander Omar Daal (6-8), who gave up
nine hits, walked one and struck out five in 7 innings. Daal, whose
ERA still dropped from 2.58 to 2.49, has watched his team fail to
score in his past three losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the way I pitched,'' he said. ``If I keep
throwing the ball like that, I know that sometime it (offensive
production) will turn around. It's not easy, but I have to do what
I can do. I just have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone run came in the fourth inning, when Gregg Jefferies
doubled to left field with two outs and scored on a soft single to
shallow right-center by Mark Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slider down and away,'' Daal said. ``He (Lewis)
didn't hit the ball well, but he hit it in the right spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got a pair of hits off Portugal in the first
inning (by Andy Fox and Travis Lee), but couldn't put a run on the
board. Third baseman Matt Williams hit a fly ball to right to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of a particularly frustrating night for
Williams, who was 3 for 45 against Portugal entering the game and
was hitless in three trips this time. He also struck out against
reliever Wayne Gomes to end what appeared to be a promising eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The strikeout parade began in the second inning with Jay Bell
(No. 996) and continued with Damian Miller in the second (997), Lee
in the fourth, Fox in the sixth, followed by the next batter,
Bernard Gilkey, for No. 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter gave credit to Portugal, but
said his hitters could have done a better job of recognizing
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens with a lot of young players like we have, but after
129 games, you'd think we'd do a better job of it. Some are getting
it, some aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was successful with all his pitches _ fastball,
curveball, slider and change-up _ and Showalter said he pitched
``backward'' _ throwing more off-speed pitches when he was behind
in the count instead of his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the first inning, the Diamondbacks' best chance to
score came in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal gave up a smash to Fox down the right-field line, but
the ball caromed off the stands that jut about two-thirds of the
way down the line, and went into the air, where right fielder Ruben
Amaro retrieved it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox made the wide turn, and saw Amaro fire the ball toward the
bag, where Portugal was waiting. Portugal caught the ball and made
the quick tag for the out, called by plate umpire Wally Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take an aggressive turn like that,'' Showalter
said. ``You couldn't have done better if someone in the stands had
thrown it (to Amaro).''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal walked Gilkey, and left-hander Yorkis Perez entered the
game. He walked White but struck out Lee, then giving way to the
right-handed Gomes (victim of a five-run, eighth-inning rally by
the Diamondbacks in the second game of a doubleheader Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   Gomes struck out Williams. In the ninth, he walked Bell, the
leadoff man, but Bell was quickly erased on a 4-6-3 double-play
grounder by David Dellucci. Pinch-hitter Karim Garcia flied out to
center to end the game, giving Gomes his first save. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
