<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT MARLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Adrian Beltre was on the bench for a few games this
week, but he was hardly sitting on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre knows he is the Dodgers' future at third base, but after
watching Bobby Bonilla start four consecutive games, all he could
think about was doing what is takes to play now.
</P>
<P>
   So he went to the batting cage with coach Manny Mota and to the
video room with hitting instructor Mickey Hatcher. He came out
Friday night with an RBI single and game-winning homer in a 5-1
victory over the Florida Marlins in front of 19,857 at Pro Player
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi hit a three-run homer in the ninth and Chan Ho Park
went eight strong innings for his 11th victory and the Dodgers
second straight win.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Beltre's night for many reasons. His promotion from
Double-A two months ago has been questioned. He was playing and
flailing as the team dropped further behind the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But his talent was never an issue. Friday, he showed why.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is Raul Mondesi at a third base,'' Eric Karros said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, to be 20 with those kinds of skills,'' said Bonilla, who
will have his tender left wrist examined today. ``Adrian Beltre is
something to behold.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla has asked the Dodgers for an anti-inflammatory shot,
which means Beltre should be back in the lineup today against the
Braves in Atlanta. Bonilla played well during his time in the
lineup, but nobody forgot about Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the extra work showed how much he wants this,''
Mota said of Beltre. ``I also told him to just be in the dugout and
watch how the pitchers set up hitters. We also threw him 75
breaking balls a day and tonight he hit a breaking ball for a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   It came in the sixth with the scored tied 1-1 against
right-hander Livan Hernandez (10-9), who lost but threw 144 pitches
for a club-high eighth complete game. Hernandez retired the first
two batters in the inning, but Beltre worked the count to 3-2.
Hernandez threw a curve and Beltre drove it over the 20-foot fence
in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre is batting just .224. Thursday he went 0 for 4 and Friday
he had a throwing error. But his offense lifted the spirits of a
team desperately trying to put together a winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and Detroit Tigers are the only major-league teams
not to win four consecutive games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Dodgers back to .500 (64-64) and drew them
within seven games of the New York Mets and Chicago Cubs in the
wild-card race with 34 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Park played a big role in the victory, limiting the Marlins to
four hits and one run. He was best in the third inning when he
struck out the side after left fielder Matt Luke misplayed Gregg
Zaun's fly ball into a triple.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Park should have been out of the inning, but
second baseman Eric Young booted Cliff Floyd's two-out grounder.
Park got out of it when Beltre grabbed Kevin Orie's sharp
one-hopper and threw to second for the force out. Antonio Osuna
pitched a scoreless ninth, striking out two.
</P>
<P>
   If Bonilla's wrist is sound, he is going to play as long as the
Dodgers believe they are in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to show some improvements when Bobby moved into
third base,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``That is no reflection
on Adrian. He's here because we want him to play and to succeed.
But these are big games for this organization. He can learn even if
he's not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre said that part of his education has come from listening
to players whose job he is trying to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Bo has been through a lot and he is showing me how to
handle myself,'' Beltre said. ``When he was playing and I was
watching he would take me aside and told me why he did things a
certain way. He doesn't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bonilla sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is part of the beauty of the game,'' he said. ``When I
was coming up in the Pirates organization, that guy for me was
Willie Stargell. This is a hard game and you need people to help
you along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
