<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA BOOED AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the fans at Shea Stadium want Mike Piazza back
next season, they continue to have a strange way of showing it.
While the St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire's every move was
cheered during Thursday night's doubleheader, Piazza was once again
the target of boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just more of the same,'' Mets General Manager Steve Phillips
said of the booing of Piazza, who had a tough time at the plate and
in the field in the doubleheader until he pounded a towering home
run in Game 2 that helped spark the Mets' 5-4 comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   After the home run, the fans did a 180-degree reversal and
demanded a curtain call from Piazza. Piazza obliged, even though
one of his teammates, Turk Wendell, said Friday that he would not
have done so if he were Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised they actually asked me to do it,'' Piazza
said. ``I didn't put us ahead or tie it. But it was flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza heard resounding cheers on Tuesday night, when his
dramatic pinch-hit three-run double gave the Mets a doubleheader
sweep of Colorado. The good feelings carried over to Wednesday
night, when he got an ovation as he strode to the plate against the
Rockies with the bases loaded. The roar got even louder when he
lined a run-scoring single, a big hit in a game the Mets won by
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But 24 hours later, the booing was back.
</P>
<P>
   As for the renewed jeers, Piazza said: ``What's the big deal?
They've booed everyone here. They booed Reggie Jackson. It's part
of the territory about playing here. You have to block everything
out. I try to. And I think I do a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Piazza knows what goes through his mind when he hears the
boos, which began earlier in the season when he repeatedly failed
in clutch situations for the Mets. In recent weeks, the booing
seemed to bother him, but Friday he appeared to shrug it off. He
smiled, joked and at times seemed downright jovial.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been because he had the first game of Friday night's
doubleheader off after playing all 18 innings on Thursday. Or, as
he insisted, it may have been mind over reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm really not spending a significant
amount of time pondering the situation,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Others do, as anyone who has listened to sports-talk radio shows
would attest. As Phillips admitted, when asked if the booing would
have a negative effect on any contract negotiations Piazza might
have with the Mets: ``I think it's safe to say it will make it more
difficult. In any negotiation, a player has to be motivated to
stay. I mostly feel bad for Mike. It's not an easy thing to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday if he might not want to return because of the
booing, Piazza said: ``I can't answer that. But I don't see the big
debate. I consider it the way this town has always been. And not
only this one.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's Nemesis
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell has struck out Mark McGwire three times in the last
week, twice with games on the line. So Wendell could afford to joke
a little about his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Lankford bothers me more than McGwire,'' Wendell said
Friday. ``Lankford hits me better.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody lately has been hitting Wendell, who picked up
the save in the second game of Wednesday's doubleheader with two
scoreless innings. The quirky reliever, who had been buried in the
Mets' bullpen the first four months of the season, had not allowed
a run in his last 10 appearances _ a span of 11 innings _ coming
into last night's doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell is now entrenched as the right-handed set-up man for
closer John Franco. And the crowd at Shea appeared to be rooting
for Wendell when he struck out McGwire in the top of the eighth on
Wednesday night. On all his other at-bats, the crowd was rooting
for McGwire, who belted his 50th and 51st homers during the
doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Volunteers
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones will start for the Mets Saturday afternoon on three
days' rest. ``It wasn't my idea, it was his,'' Manager Bobby
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had been leaning toward recalling right-hander Octavio
Dotel from Class AAA Norfolk for a spot start. But the game would
have been Dotel's major-league debut, and the Mets are in the
middle of a wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'd rather not bring in an unknown,'' Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he told Valentine, `` `I don't know what your options
are for Saturday, but if you need somebody, I'd be willing to
pitch.''' Which means that Jones' back does not seem to be
bothering him that much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought it would bother me by pitching on three days'
rest, there is no way I'd even be thinking about it,'' Jones said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
