<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX POUND TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The votes have been counted in all precincts, from
Barnstable County on the Cape to Cumberland County in Maine, and
it's unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   As far as New England is concerned, Nomar Garciaparra gets no
more days off from now until as deep into autumn as the Red Sox
play this season.
</P>
<P>
   A day after being given a rare breather by manager Jimy
Williams, Garciaparra hit a three-run home run Friday night that
threatened to scrape some Teflon off the roof of the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   With that fourth-inning blast, which came two innings after
Damon Buford's three-run homer started Boston toward a 9-2 win over
the Minnesota Twins, Garciaparra became just the fifth shortstop in
Red Sox history to drive in 100 or more runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who added his 101st RBI with an eighth-inning
single, is no threat this season to break the big league record for
RBIs by a shortstop, 159 by Vern Stephens of the Sox in 1949. But
he joined Stephens, John Valentin, Joe Cronin, and Rico Petrocelli
as 100-RBI Sox shortstops, and he did it in just his 108th game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice group to be in; to be mentioned with those guys is
definitely an honor,'' Garciaparra said. ``But I'd like my name
next to the 1918 Red Sox, too. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox still have a long way to go before they can join the
company of the '18 World Series ringbearers, but with Friday
night's win, they drew a significant step closer toward playing in
October. The win, coupled with the Orioles' 6-3 loss to the Indians
Friday night, gave the Red Sox an eight-game edge in the American
League wild-card race with 36 games left.
</P>
<P>
   The win went to pitcher Steve Avery, who, if it had been put to
the vox populi last Sunday, probably would have faced impeachment
proceedings. Instead, the lefthander, who openly questioned how
long he could hold on to his spot in the rotation, pitched seven
innings in which he allowed three singles and Matt Lawton's
bases-empty homer, the only run he permitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you don't always like to be under the gun,'' said
Avery, now 9-5 just five days after the Twins bombed him for nine
hits and six runs in Fenway Park, ``but I told you I'm not going to
let it affect me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the same desire to win. It's not always going to
happen, but you still go out with everything you have. I use my
heart, my mind. Even tonight, my stuff wasn't that good.''
</P>
<P>
   But his defense was, especially in the fourth inning when second
baseman Mike Benjamin and first baseman Mo Vaughn both made leaping
grabs of line drives, sandwiched around one of Garciaparra's
trademark across-the-body throws from deep in the hole to nab Marty
Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reverse slam dunk,'' Benjamin said of his full extension to
catch Brent Gates's liner. ``I stuck the landing, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Twins reliever Todd Ritchie had a right to be shocked when
Garciaparra stuck it to him by launching his 3-and-0 pitch into the
outer reaches of the Metrodome in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time this season Garciaparra had swung at a
3-and-0 pitch. On 23 previous occasions, he'd passed up the chance.
Last season, in the same number of chances, he swung just three
times and put two balls in play, once for a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it depends on whether you get the green light,''
said Garciaparra, who normally is given the go-ahead to swing away
by manager Jimy Williams. ``Sometimes you don't feel good.
Sometimes you don't want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I was thinking, `Is he going to give it to me? I hope
he does,' because I had a feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling translated into Garciaparra's 26th home run of the
season. It followed an RBI ground single by Vaughn under the glove
of first baseman Ron Coomer, who would have rescued Ritchie from
further damage had he made what would have been an inning-ending
play.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Vaughn's ball eluded Coomer's backhand attempt,
Benjamin scored on the play to make it 4-0, and Garciaparra
followed with a 394-foot drive into the left-center-field seats,
the ninth time this season he has hit a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, whose eighth-inning single scored Valentin after a
walk and wild pitch, now has three more RBIs than he did as Rookie
of the Year in 1997. Sports Illustrated, for one, already has
declared that he should be the AL Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about things like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the time has come for opposing pitchers to start
worrying about Buford, whose home run came off rookie lefthander
Eric Milton, who had held the Red Sox hitless for five innings last
weekend in Boston but was lifted after walking five of the 11
batters he faced Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Buford followed two of those walks, to Mike Stanley and Troy
O'Leary starting the second, with his ninth home run, giving the
Sox a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of Buford's home runs have come with men on base: a grand
slam, two three-runners, and four with a man aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even thought about that,'' Buford said. ``I don't
want to think about there being men on base, because I might try to
do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's done, as the Sox' leading hitter against lefthanded
pitchers, has been more than his share. Like a certain shortstop
who may soon be adding three initials to his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
