<HEADLINE>
MARIJUANA USE RISING ACROSS NATION, GOVERNMENT STUDY FINDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BROOKE OLSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A just-released study shows that teen-age drug
use is rising, particularly marijuana use, and experts and teens
alike blame society's glamorization of the illegal weed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in 10 youths between 12 and 17 reported having smoked
marijuana at least once in the previous month, according to the
survey, released Friday by the U.S. Health and Human Services
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The 9.4 percent rate of marijuana use among U.S. teen-agers --
an estimated 2.1 million youths &UR;  &LR; -- rose from 7.1 percent in 1996,
the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana leaf insignias on shirts and hats and hemp products
such as clothing, paper and even shampoo have created the
perception among teens that marijuana is ``cool'' and relatively
harmless, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done pot, but I don't think anything would happen
to me if I did do it,'' said Karen Duffy, 17, a senior at suburban
Chatsworth High School. Duffy said most of her friends have tried
marijuana and nothing harmful has ever come from their use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad drug; I don't know why everyone makes such a
stink out of it,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   It's precisely that kind of accepting attitude that makes the
glamorization of marijuana all the more dangerous, said Mary
Kauffman, an adviser for Drug Abuse and Resistance Education, a
national program that teaches students about the dangers of drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the kids perceive the drugs as not dangerous, or even
beneficial to them, the number of them using the drugs will be on
the rise,'' Kauffman said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, one of two states for which the survey provided
separate data, 6.6 percent of young people reported having used
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Of the youths surveyed nationwide, 11.4 percent used illicit
drugs in 1997, up from 9 percent the previous year. The survey
questioned 24,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Valley teen-agers said marijuana was easier to obtain than any
other substance illegal to teens -- including alcohol and
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of people selling it. It's not too hard to
find,'' said Michael Kennington, 16, of suburban Northridge. ``With
cigarettes or alcohol, you always have to find someone older to buy
it for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, everyone is doing it or endorsing it -- you see it on
TV or in the movies, or there's songs about it. It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lions Lair, a novelty and apparel store in suburban Canoga
Park, Mark Herer ticked off the benefits of hemp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marijuana has many different uses -- it actually produces
really good clothing and paper,'' said Herer, assistant manager of
the store and son of Jack Herer, who wrote the pro-hemp book ``The
Emperor Wears No Clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts believe kids' perceptions are being tainted by hemp
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating. We're up against a very powerful medium
that affects kids every day,'' Kauffman said. ``There's not a
moment that goes by where kids aren't being inundated with the
effects of advertising, movies or even fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The side effects of marijuana use are wide-ranging, and include
everything from medical problems to social stigma, said David
Feinberg, a child analyst and psychologist who specializes in teen
drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chronic marijuana use leads to a motivational syndrome --
what's known as `burnout' -- and that's where you just don't want
to do anything except smoke pot,'' Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   In high dosages, marijuana can lead to breast enlargement in
males and decreasing fertility among both sexes, he said. It has
also been linked to lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging aspect of marijuana is that when bought on the
street, it can contain traces of other drugs, such as PCP or LSD,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marijuana does get laced with stuff, and it can have
devastating consequences,'' Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But teens, especially in California, remain adamant that
marijuana is a low-risk drug. According to the national survey,
Californians were less likely to perceive great risk in using
marijuana than residents in the remainder of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings from the annual federally funded survey:
</P>
<P>
   --Between 1996 and 1997, illicit drug use increased from 2
percent to 4 percent among 12- and 13-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1997, 9.1 percent of youths in California and 11.9 percent
of youths in the U.S. were illicit drug users.
</P>
<P>
   --The number of cocaine users did not change significantly in
1997, but there has been an increasing trend in heroin use since
1993. In 1997, 325,000 used it in the past month, approximately 0.2
percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Why do more kids seem to be turning to drugs? L.A.-area teens
listed several reasons, including boredom and eagerness to ``fit
in'' with certain crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just cool to do,'' Kennington said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
