<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS HALT `LOSING STREAK' AT TWO GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ In describing his pitcher's personality, Joe
Torre would refer to David Wells by his nickname this spring and
say, ``The Boomer is the Boomer.'' Wells was not exactly sure what
the New York Yankees manager meant by this, but he guessed it was
not a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   They existed within this spiral of misunderstanding, pitcher and
manager, until Wells nearly blew a 9-0 lead against the Rangers
here on May 6 and Torre suggested Wells might be out of shape. That
led to a meeting two days later, in which they came to know each
other a little better, and the end result has been an era of good
feeling. Wells shut out the Rangers Friday night, 5-0, bringing his
season's performance and his relationship with his manager full
circle.
</P>
<P>
   The victory enabled the Yankees (93-32) to end their losing
streak at two games. They have not lost three consecutive games
since opening the season with three defeats. Tino Martinez hit two
home runs and collected his 100th and 101st runs batted in,
becoming the first Yankee since Don Mattingly to drive in 100 or
more runs in three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Following the near-disaster against Texas in May, Torre barely
contained his frustration with Wells, questioning his conditioning.
Torre's remarks were relayed to the pitcher. In Minnesota two days
later, Wells initiated a meeting, telling his manager that he felt
Torre and the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre did not believe in him
or his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the conversation Friday night, Torre said that he
started to understand how sensitive Wells can be, despite his loud,
direct and in-your-face personality.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, too, seems to have gleaned the knowledge that, above all,
Torre wants to win. ``We're going to butt heads sometimes,'' Wells
said. ``But I respect him tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells smiled. ``Joe is Joe,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   When Wells departed Texas that night in May, he was 3-1 with a
5.77 earned run average. In the months since, he has pitched a
perfect game, started for the American League in the All-Star Game
and has become a strong candidate for the league's Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Rangers Friday night, Wells allowed six hits and a
walk and struck out seven. He is 16-2, matching his career high for
victories, with a 3.26 ERA. He leads the league in shutouts with
four, and Torre on Friday night talked about how Wells has been the
pitcher ``you hang your hat on.'' David Cone started slowly and
improved gradually, Andy Pettitte has struggled intermittently,
Hideki Irabu swooned in midseason. But Wells has been constant most
of the season, with Torre coming to respect his competitiveness.
When Wells battled and scratched to throw six innings Sunday,
despite having poor stuff, Torre made sure to compliment him.
</P>
<P>
   With Wells, everything starts with strike one. He can throw his
92 mile-per-hour fastball for a strike just about every time he
wants, Minnesota Manager Tom Kelly recently told a friend; he can
throw his curve for strikes, he's improving his changeup, and he
challenges everybody. Before Friday night's game, Wells had allowed
only 1.02 runners per inning, the lowest in the AL.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wells threw a first-pitch strike to each of the first five
batters he faced Friday night, and threw first-pitch strikes to 10
of the first 12 hitters. Only in the fifth inning did he appear in
trouble, and that had more to do with the weather than the Rangers.
Heavy winds began to blow and a storm seemed imminent. Despite that
threat, Wells slowed his pace, rather than speed it up.
</P>
<P>
   The rains came and went, and Wells kept on dominating the
Rangers, retiring the last 10 batters he faced. Torre looked down
at the end of the Yankees' bench when his team was batting to see
Wells sitting alone, staring out on the field, his concentration
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him throw a lot of good games,'' said Mark McLemore,
the Rangers second baseman who faced Wells when both were growing
up in San Diego. ``But that's the best I've seen him since I faced
him in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Texas Manager Johnny Oates: ``It was one of the best
performances by a left-hander we've seen all season. He spotted his
fastball well, and his curveball and changeup got better as the
game went on.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Wells paused for a moment when he shook hands
with Torre, and the manager tapped him on the chest. The Boomer is
the Boomer.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, who hit a first-inning home run, his 17th, was
hit by a pitch in the lower back in the seventh inning and was
replaced in the bottom of the inning by Luis Sojo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
