<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFFS BEGIN, AND HOUSTON IS THE TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MELANIE HAUSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will the Women's National Basketball Association playoffs be a
one-team race? Or will this be a down-to-the-wire postseason?
</P>
<P>
   It depends on whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four coaches involved see this as a wide-open race.
And the fourth? Phoenix Coach Cheryl Miller put the pressure
squarely on the favored Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their championship to lose,'' she said in a conference
call on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Rockers may be the hottest team coming in and the
Charlotte Sting may be the luckiest, having slipped in when the
lost to Detroit Wednesday night, but the Comets are the defending
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's Houston and then there's the rest of us,''
said Miller, who predicted a Houston-Phoenix final last month.
``I've felt like that all season long.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston rolls into Saturday's opening semifinal game in
Charlotte (18-12) with the best record (27-3) and three of the
league's best offensive players.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's Mercury (19-11) travels to Cleveland (20-10) for the
beginning of the other two-of-three-game semifinal round Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Perrot, Houston's point guard, suffered a severely sprained
right ankle in Wednesday night's season finale against Los Angeles.
Coach Van Chancellor said Perrot, who broke the same ankle two
years ago, will probably play in Game 1, but that Janeth Arcain
will start at the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her if she thought she could play 15 minutes
Saturday,'' Chancellor said of Perrot. ``She acted like she was
insulted. But it's all going to come down to whether she can cut
out there on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot has been the glue for the Comets this season, but the
spotlight has been on Cynthia Cooper, the league's leading scorer
and last year's most valuable player; Sheryl Swoopes (sixth in
scoring) and Tina Thompson. It was Cooper who took over and almost
single-handedly beat the Liberty in the second half of last year's
WNBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been some internal friction on the Comets _ a
few weeks ago, Cooper said that some teammates were too concerned
with individual statistics _ Chancellor said reports about it have
been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer to that is 27 wins,'' he said. ``You can't win 27
basketball games with all the problems that have been reported.
It's not all peaches and cream, but when we step on the court,
we're a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston is 3-0 against Charlotte this season and beat the Sting,
70-54, in last year's semifinals, while New York beat Phoenix,
59-41. Last season, all playoffs were one game each.
</P>
<P>
   The Sting slipped into the playoffs late Wednesday night after
the Liberty was eliminated by its loss to Detroit coupled with
Phoenix's victory over Sacramento. ``We listened to the last three
minutes of the game in the locker room on a cell phone,'' Coach
Marynell Meadors said of the Phoenix-Sacramento game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sting had a 14-4 start, but stumbled down the stretch. Then,
through a scheduling quirk, Charlotte had five days off and could
do nothing but watch other teams play their way into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, which nailed down the top of the Eastern Conference
standing Monday night when it defeated the Liberty in New York, now
faces Phoenix and Jennifer Gillom, the second-leading scorer in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of respect for Phoenix,'' Coach Linda
Hill-McDonald said. ``We've struggled against them all three times
we've played them. They've got speed and size and Jennifer
Gillom.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
