<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-22 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Powell, defense 
keep Brewers 
under control
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MILWAUKEE _ If the Astros don't know already, Milwaukee isn't the
most charitable locale in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   That would explain the uneasy feeling manager Larry Dierker
began to feel in the seventh inning Friday night when the Astros
watched a two-run lead dwindle to one. Only 24 hours earlier, the
Astros twice blew three-run leads in a 10-inning loss to the
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the most confident manager in the major leagues at
that moment,'' Dierker admitted after the Astros pulled away on
Richard Hidalgo's two-run homer in the ninth for a 5-2 victory over
Milwaukee at County Stadium. ``This was a very scary game.
Practically every time, they either beat you or make you sweat it
out because they don't mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, neither did the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   For a club that relies on big sticks, it was the gloves _ and
some solid pitching _ that came in handy as the Astros earned a
split of a two-game series with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   By winning, the Astros maintained a 7{-game lead over the
Chicago Cubs in the National League Central heading into a crucial
three-game series beginning today at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's case for the defense:
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, who went 3-for-5, chased down a deep fly ball by Geoff
Jenkins at the warning track in the fifth inning. On Thursday,
Hidalgo threw out a runner at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning Friday, shortstop Tim Bogar stabbed a line
drive and flipped the ball to second baseman Craig Biggio for an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers, who entered the game as a pinch hitter in the
eighth, went airborne for a high chopper along the third-base line
in the ninth inning for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in a solid pitching effort by righthander Sean Bergman and
2 innings of scoreless relief from Jay Powell, and the Astros had
the ingredients for their seventh win in nine meetings with the
Brewers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to win a pennant if you can't catch the ball,
no matter how many runs you score,'' said third baseman Sean Berry,
who went 2-for-2 and batted .450 against the Brewers this season.
``We've done a pretty good job this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can attack you a bunch of different ways _ steal bases, hit
home runs and make the great play to stop the runs from scoring.
The pitching is keeping us in the game. All you have to do is keep
us close; we'll find a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman (11-6) pitched 4 scoreless innings before Milwaukee
broke through. He allowed two runs and seven hits for his first
victory since July 28.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander, coming off a strong eight-inning outing five
days earlier against the Cubs, didn't allow a run until Marquis
Grissom's single scored Bill Pulsipher in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't nearly as fast or dominating as his last start, but
he was tenacious and kept the ball down pretty well,'' Dierker
said. ``He's been very steady. Obviously, when you pitch almost
seven innings, give up two runs, on the road and at a good hitter's
park, it looks like a great outing, but I think he would tell you
it wasn't his best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I pitched well,'' said Bergman. ``I have to give a
lot of credit to the defense. They gave me the opportunities to
win. I feel comfortable, even in the games I've struggled a little
bit. Tonight I wasn't as sharp, but they made some great plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee made it interesting in the seventh when Jenkins led
off with a home run to center on a 2-2 changeup from Bergman,
slicing the Astros' lead to 3-2. After a walk to Fernando Via,
Dierker went to his overused bullpen and inserted Powell, who
allowed only one hit over the final 2 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen had struggled one day earlier in a 6-5 loss to the
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just try to go out there and get us into the ninth with
the lead _ that's my job,'' Powell said. ``Our goal is to get the
ball to Billy (Wagner) with the lead in the ninth. If we do that,
we'll win a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner wasn't available after pitching Thursday, so Powell was
asked to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo put the game out of reach with a two-run shot off
Brewers reliever Bronswell Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   However, runs were in short supply as Bergman and Pulsipher
(1-1) staged a pitching duel early.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Astros didn't understand the math: 17 hits, two
of them home runs, and only five runs in a 10-inning loss. On
Friday, Pulsipher had a one-hitter through four innings _ and the
Astros led 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher didn't do himself any favors with five walks, which
led to two of the Astros' runs.
</P>
<P>
   Berry provided two runs with a sacrifice fly in the second
inning and an RBI single in the fourth. Berry went 9-for-20 with
two home runs and six RBIs against the Brewers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really hot when I got hurt,'' Berry said. ``That
first-at-bat home run (Thursday) was a big lift. It's tough coming
off an injury like that. It kind of slows you down. I wouldn't say
I'm quite 100 percent, but I'm getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros made it 3-1 in the sixth inning. Jeff Bagwell, who
walked twice and scored three times, singled to lead off the
inning. Berry singled with one out, and Tony Eusebio followed with
an RBI single to right. That proved to be just enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
