<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' GENERAL MANAGER WANTS END TO LONG SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By VINCENT M. MALLOZZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ Speaking in a low but firm voice over lunch,
General Manager Lou Lamoriello of the New Jersey Devils said Friday
that the memory of last season's stunning first-round playoff loss
to Ottawa was still hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, quite frankly in my mind, a disaster,'' said
Lamoriello, who watched the Devils skate to the best regular-season
record in the Eastern Conference last season only to be eliminated
in six games by the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could have gone wrong last season, went wrong, and it's
been a long summer for everyone,'' Lamoriello said. ``We had a
player getting cut with a skate, another getting food-poisoned, but
there are no excuses, because we did not compete the way we should
have.''
</P>
<P>
   With training camp set to open Sept. 12, the Devils are ready to
atone for last season's playoff debacle, which led to the
resignation of the head coach Jacques Lemaire, who brought a
Stanley Cup to New Jersey in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Lemaire, replaced by the assistant Robbie Ftorek, is still with
the Devils' organization in a role that Lamoriello described as a
``special assignment scout.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the conversations I've had with our players in the
postseason, I have no problem in my mind today knowing what their
attitude is,'' Lamoriello said. ``Character is not something we
lack, and I think this is going to be a very competitive training
camp, because when you have character, you have pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Since drinking from the Stanley Cup, the Devils have strung
together three hard-luck seasons: failing to make the playoffs in
1996, losing to the rival New York Rangers in the second round of
the 1997 playoffs, and losing last season to Ottawa without the
services in Game 6 of center Jason Arnott, whose wrist was cut by a
skate in Game 5, and center Bobby Holik, who had food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello said Friday that Arnott had another setback three
weeks ago, injuring the middle finger on his left hand in a fishing
accident in Sudbury, Ontario. While Arnott's injury required
surgery, Lamoriello said he should be out of a cast and ready to
play by the start of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is acquiring a quality backup for goaltender
Martin Brodeur. Although the Devils have several solid young
goalies in the minors, Lamoriello said he wants a veteran ``who is
capable of playing 15-20 games and is willing to accept that
role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
