   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLL _ President Clinton continues to draw high ratings
from the American public for his job performance, but his admission
of a relationship with a White House intern has produced signs of a
darkening public view of both the president's moral character and
his overall personal image, the latest New York Times/CBS News poll
shows. By Adam Nagourney. (With graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   MISS-KLAN-TRIAL (Hattiesburg, Miss.) _ Vernon Dahmer Jr. covered
his face and wept into his hands. His brother, Dennis, gently
pounded a railing in the old courthouse balcony. And their mother,
the elderly Ellie Dahmer, shut her eyes and steepled her fingers,
thanking God for the jury's Friday verdict that, almost 33 years
after the crime, found an old, stooped Klansman guilty of ordering
her husband killed. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CT-NUKE-PILLS (Hartford, Conn.) _ After years of resistance, the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission is preparing to distribute to states
with nuclear power plants a drug that blocks a type of radiation
that causes thyroid cancer, and already, people in Connecticut and
other states are clamoring for the medicine. By Jonathan
Rabinovitz.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEGHENY-COLLAPSE (Philadelphia) _ This venerable city is
reeling from the collapse of an institution that swooped into town
a decade ago and shook up every aspect of health care. That
institution, the Allegheny Health, Education and Research
Foundation, is the largest health-care provider in Pennsylvania and
one of the largest nonprofit providers in the country. By Peter T.
Kilborn. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LIBRARY (New York) _ New York's main library adapts for
computer age. By David W. Dunlap. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-DAMAGE (Washington) _ The administration made measured
claims of success for the cruise-missile attacks in Sudan and
Afghanistan on Thursday, saying the attack on a mountain redoubt in
Afghanistan would disrupt training and, possibly, future attacks by
terrorists sponsored by Osama bin Laden. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Khartoum, Sudan) _ Not quite 24 hours after U.S.
missiles hit a factory in a decrepit industrial area of this
capital, clouds of white smoke and acrid smells still hovered over
the site Friday night. The Islamic government, accused by the
Clinton administration of assisting in the terrorist activities of
Osama Bin Laden, used the fiery remnants of the factory as a
backdrop for an anti-American demonstration that featured placards
showing President Clinton's face and that of Monica Lewinsky. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ President Clinton's top national
security advisers began on Friday to show a small group of
lawmakers the evidence they had to justify the missile attacks on
terrorist targets. Although they would not reveal details, the
lawmakers said they agreed that the case against Osama bin Laden is
as compelling as the administration contends. By Eric Schmitt.
(With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RECAP (Washington) _ A recap of the process leading up to
the decision to attack: Clinton had cut short a political trip to
California to attend a military strategy meeting. For the next
eight days, he and the White House were consumed with planning on
two tracks for two events: his grand jury testimony and the
attacks. By James Bennet. (With timeline graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ The man who climbed atop a tank and
led Russia out of communism in 1991 has scarcely been seen in
public since his country's financial markets and its currency fell
off a cliff last week. The big question _ for him and for the
reforms he champions _ is whether Russians any longer care.
President Boris Yeltsin, already deeply unpopular, now seems to
have sunk even lower in political and public esteem than his
country's ruble. By Michael Wines.
