</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY MAC HAS BASEBALL WORLD ON EDGE OF SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Some of us are still waiting for the home run Mark
McGwire blasted at the Kingdome last season to touch down.
</P>
<P>
   Earth to McGwire's prodigious longball: Please phone home.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those of us lucky enough to see McGwire's epic moon
launch a year ago June 24, before he was traded to that other
league, were glad the Kingdome ceiling tiles already had fallen
down and been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Surely McGwire's nuclear tater would have set off another epic
roof disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ex-Mariner Randy Johnson, the pitcher who was tagged
for McGwire's last Kingdome homer (OK, it did land and the
eye-popping tale of the tape read 538 feet), jokingly wonders if
that home run ball isn't still orbiting somewhere in space.
</P>
<P>
   You get the point.
</P>
<P>
   Big Mac does not hit home runs. He ignites them.
</P>
<P>
   There's ``Rocket'' Roger Clemens and then there's ``Rocket
Fuel'' McGwire, which means that for the first time since George
Herman Ruth, there is a home run hitter who is unafraid to call
himself a home run hitter and unabashed about making a national
headline circus of his longball feats.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is Sammy Sosa, who tagged No. 49 Friday to help the
Cubs beat the Giants. Sosa has done the right things to amend his
mechanics, curb his impulsiveness at the plate. He has turned his
talent into big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there was Ken Griffey Jr., who leads the American
League with 42 homers but who has all but defected from the Maris
chase. We dearly miss Griffey's participation in this
great-for-baseball home run drama, but the show must go on,
especially since Griffey will define himself as he sees fit _ which
means as one of the best, if not the best, all-around baseball
players ever to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   As for the New Age Sultan of Swat?
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has earned himself the title, and he's not even done
yet.
</P>
<P>
   While the world talks about how the chase is on to break Roger
Maris' single-season home run record of 61 in '61, it is McGwire
(and his Popeye-armed physique) who makes us crack open Baseball
Encyclopedias and click on baseball history web sites to help us
better compare him to the real Bronx Bomber _ Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   It is the affable, generous and focused McGwire who makes us
yearn to get a historic handle on why it is we have come to accept
_ or rather, why we have come to relish _ the idea that he can
break this most hallowed sports record.
</P>
<P>
   That's because McGwire is assaulting the home run record in a
fashion befitting the Babe.
</P>
<P>
   That became especially true after McGwire hit No. 50 Thursday at
Shea Stadium to become the only player to have 50 or more homers in
three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   To get some perspective on this feat, figure that even Hank
Aaron, who owns the career home run record, never hit more than 47
in a single season. Harmon Killebrew and Frank Robinson each got to
49.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with No. 51 in the second game of Thursday's doubleheader
against the Mets, McGwire tied Ruth's mark of 161 homers over a
three-year period, which Ruth did from 1926-28, including his
60-homer season in '27.
</P>
<P>
   Taking nothing away from Maris, whose record 61 homers is
magnificent if only because he achieved it under such agonizing
conditions in '61 _ with his hair falling out and the media
scrutiny intense _ the reason McGwire is readily able to win over
well-wishers is because the drama of his ear-splitting homers is
eclipsed as much by the pace at which he amassing them.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone yet doubt that McGwire is heading as much for 70
homers this season as he is chasing Maris and 61?
</P>
<P>
   McGwire may hardly be ``Ruthian'' in regard to his place in
baseball history _ so far as we can now tell. No one compares to
Ruth, who started off as an overwhelming pitcher for the Red Sox
and ended his sport-defining career as a outfielder, just because
the Yankees knew they must take advantage of his awesome and
unfailingly consistent production and power at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   However, McGwire does produce his home runs in a fashion so
monstrous, so compelling and under circumstances no less difficult
than Ruth, there is now a new term in baseball:
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire-esque.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Associated Press reports out of New York
described McGwire's gravity-resistant home runs with this term.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you cannot look up ``McGwire-esque'' in the dictionary. But
if you could, the definition most likely would be ``to crush'' or
``to captivate an entire ballyard, city, state and nation during
each drippingly anticipated at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has been ``McGwire-esque'' at the very least since last
June, when he showed the Griffey-watchers in the Kingdome the
difference between a perfect swing (Griffey's) and the epic swing
of a launcher of longballs.
</P>
<P>
   The race for 61 is not on, it's a done deal. And the man leading
the way has the colossus of clout-type of size and power to force a
nation to turn its eyes to him.
</P>
<P>
   To be ``Ruthian'' may be eternal, but we'll take
``McGwire-esque.'' Every day from now until October, with delight.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
