<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOON, SEAHAWKS OUT TO IMPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ All eyes will be on Warren Moon Saturday night
when the Seahawks take what could be the final giant step toward
their Sept. 6 regular-season opener in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' starting quarterback will make his summer debut
against the Arizona Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium in Tempe. Moon
missed basically all of training camp and the first three preseason
games because of his 25-day holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren has picked up right where he left off at our minicamps
this spring. There aren't many quarterbacks playing right now who
can throw it better than he can,'' coach Dennis Erickson said
Friday after the team did a 30-minute walk-through before their
flight to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he needs to do it in a game situation,'' Erickson said.``
It's important that he plays quite a bit in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon is scheduled to play most of the first half against the
Cardinals. His efforts, as well as those of the other starters,
will determine how much the No. 1 offense and defense play in next
week's rematch against the San Francisco 49ers in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson would like to go with his starters for only a few
series in that game, but if they do not show a marked improvement
from last week's flat effort against the 49ers in Vancouver, B.C.,
they will play longer. Erickson has told the players what is riding
on Saturday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to sit down and look at where we're at
after this game,'' Erickson said. ``If we're not where we need to
be, we've going to have to do something about it against San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   So more than Moon playing like the quarterback who set club
records for completions and passing yards last year, the coaches
need to see improvement from all the starters.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the runs Ricky Watters has come close to breaking in
the first three games need to go for double-digit yardage; the
early inclusion of Joey Galloway in the passing game that finally
happened last week must continue, but not at the exclusion of
getting the ball into the hands of Mike Pritchard, James McKnight
and Brian Blades; and the line must dominate as it did two weeks
ago against Indianapolis, rather than be pushed around as it was
against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see a little better consistency, the type of
consistency we're going to need opening day,'' offensive
coordinator Bob Bratkowski said. ``That's consistency in the
running game, pass protection and everything else. We've done some
good things. Now we have to do them consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   While this is a time for the starters to show that last week was
a one-game letdown, look for a couple of rookies to get some time
with the No. 1 unit _ third-round draft choice Ahman Green spelling
Watters, sooner; and second-round pick Todd Weiner replacing Howard
Ballard at right tackle, later.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, consistency also has been the buzz word this week.
In the first two preseason games, the Seahawks started slowly, then
put the clamps on Dallas and Indianapolis. Last week, the defense
produced its first three-and-out series to start a game, but then
yielded 70- and 62-yard scoring drives to the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to let it loose, play together and minimize the
mental mistakes,'' defensive coordinator Greg McMackin said.
``We're looking to do the little things that will allow us to play
with more consistency. That's what it all comes down to _
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   As on offense, key backups like middle linebacker DeShone Myles,
this year's fourth-round draft choice, and cornerback Fred Thomas
will be worked into the mix with the No. 1 defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game as far as evaluating where we're at _
individually and as units,'' Erickson said. ``That overrides the
winning and losing of this preseason game.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: DE Phillip Daniels and DT Dan Saleauma will start
despite being slowed by injuries this week, Erickson said. . . . SS
Mark Collins is questionable with a sore hamstring, and whether
Blades' sprained ankle will allow him to play won't be determined
until the pre-game warmups. . . . DT Cortez Kennedy, who sprained
his right ankle last week, did not make the trip. He remained
behind to rehab his ankle. . . . For the fourth straight week, the
Seahawks are playing an opponent they will face later. They opened
at Dallas, and will play the Cowboys again Nov. 22. Next was
Indianapolis, and the Colts return to the Kingdome on Dec. 20. Last
week, the Seahawks played the 49ers and the teams meet again next
week. As for the Cardinals, they play at the Kingdome on Sept. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
