A7093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MCWILLIAMS-NYT &LR;      08-22 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MCWILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM K. MCWILLIAMS JR., 75, LEADER IN GAS AND OIL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (lh) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William K. McWilliams Jr., a geologist and leader in the oil and
gas industry, died of kidney failure at St. Tammany Hospital in
Covington, La., July 17, said William Collier, a spokesman for
Freeport-McMoran Inc. He was 75 and lived in Covington.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams was an independent oil and gas producer, co-founder
and chairman-emeritus of the McMoran Oil and Gas Company and
director emeritus of Freeport-McMoran Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, James R. Moffett, chairman and chief executive
of Freeport-McMoran Copper and Gold Inc., renamed from
Freeport-McMoran Inc., said: ``Ken McWilliams was one of the
foremost visionary geologists in the world. His geological
philosophy set the pattern that led to the company's ability to
find many world-class natural resource deposits.''
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams attended Tulane University on the first basketball
scholarship ever awarded by the school, and graduated with a
Bachelor of Science degree in geology.
</P>
<P>
   He maintained a lifelong interest in athletics. From 1982 until
1984 he served as chairman of the Louisiana Superdome Commission.
And in 1982, he served as chairman of the National Collegiate
Athletic Association basketball finals, bringing that event to New
Orleans for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, McWilliams was appointed by President Jimmy Carter to
be a member of the National Petroleum Council. He was reappointed
three years later by President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Elleonora Perrilliat McWilliams, of
Covington; three sons, David K. of Covington and Paul C. and
Patrick T. of Metairie, La.; three daughters, Penny M. Doster of
Madisonville, La., and Jennifer M. Cantrelle and Rebecca M. Giveans
of Mandeville, La.; 11 grandchildren, and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 0219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7095 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     08-22 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
adds quotes, details 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It went 9-1-5-4 in the scorebook, a double
play that was as costly to the Angels as it was strange.
</P>
<P>
   After the play, it took five minutes for the umpires to come up
with a ruling. And when they did, they took a run away from the
Angels. The Angels played the rest of the game under protest. But
by the time it was over, it might not have mattered.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays scored two runs in the eighth inning and
two more in the ninth to open up a tight game on their way to a 9-4
victory Friday night before 36,052 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Because Texas also lost, the Angels still have a 1{-game lead in
the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays' Carlos Delgado hit two home runs and Jose Canseco
one off Angels starter Jeff Juden, making his home debut with the
Angels since being acquired in an Aug. 7 trade with the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Juden, however, had nothing to do with the play that had
everybody scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels lost at least one run and the chance for more in the
second inning on a play resulting from Garret Anderson's
base-running blunder.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied 1-1 when, with the bases loaded and one out,
Gary DiSarcina hit a sinking liner to right field. It fell in front
of right fielder Shawn Green, and Jim Edmonds scored from third to
give the Angels a 2-1 lead. Or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was on second to begin the play and apparently thought
Green caught the ball on the fly. He didn't look at third base
coach Larry Bowa waving him over and stayed at second. Meanwhile,
Matt Walbeck went from first to second. But when he saw Anderson
standing there, he also assumed the ball was caught and ran back
toward first.
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels were confused on the base paths, Green got the
ball in to pitcher Chris Carpenter, who threw to Tony Fernandez for
the force on Anderson at third. Fernandez then threw to second
baseman Craig Grebeck to force Walbeck, who by this time was nearly
back at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Because the double play started with a force out, Edmonds' run
did not count. The Angels played the rest of the game under
protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take was that Walbeck touched second, so I think that takes
the force off,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``(Crew chief
Larry Barnett) said it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he doesn't think the chances are good the league
will rule in favor of the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably zero,'' Collins said. ``Anybody ever won one? I've
never heard of one being won.''
</P>
<P>
   While Collins said he'd never seen a play like that before,
Anderson said: ``It wasn't strange, I just messed it up. No
excuses, no reason to speculate. I take responsibility for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Juden looked overpowering at times, yet he got bombed enough to
put the Angels in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   He ended each of the first six innings with a strikeout, and had
nine in all. Three times he set down the Blue Jays in order.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second inning, Delgado hit a rocket over the
center-field fence. Then in the third, after an RBI single by
Green, Canseco hit a 422-foot homer to left-center for a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good,'' said Juden, 0-2 with the Angels and 7-13
overall. ``But I made a couple mistakes, left a couple pitches to
Delgado out over the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde's two-run homer in the third cut the Angels'
deficit to 4-3, but Delgado hit his second homer of the game in the
sixth for a 5-3 Toronto lead.
</P>
<P>
   Juden left after seven innings, having allowed five runs but
only five hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays added two runs in the eighth inning on an RBI
single by Delgado and an RBI double by Jose Cruz Jr. In the ninth,
Green had an RBI triple and scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter (9-6) went seven innings to get the win, the second
over Juden and the Angels in less than a week. He beat Juden 6-4 on
Aug. 16 in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, buoyed by the double play in the second inning, held
the Angels to three runs (two earned) and five hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
