MARINERS WIN ONE-RUN GAME FOR A CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It took them nearly two months, but the Mariners won
another one-run game Friday night. They would have accepted any
margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Mike Timlin battled through the most dangerous part of
the Chicago White Sox lineup to secure his 11th save in the
Mariners' 5-4 victory before 34,421 fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Joey Cora collected his 1,000th major-league hit,
Jay Buhner and Edgar Martinez hit home runs and Russ Davis excelled
in the field and at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The M's hadn't won a one-run game since June 24 and are still a
major-league worst 5-20 in games decided by the slimmest margin.
They also had lost seven of their past nine games to fall 12 games
behind the American League West-leading Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to win a one-run game, but any kind of win is
nice,'' shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``You can't go out and score
seven or eight runs every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to right-handed relievers Jose Paniagua and Timlin, five
were enough in the four-game series opener. But it wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, promoted from Class AAA Tacoma on Wednesday, replaced
starter Jeff Fassero in the eighth inning. He ran into trouble but
escaped by striking out Ray Durham with two runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   He became the pitcher of record in the bottom of the inning when
Buhner worked losing pitcher Keith Foulke for a full-count walk.
Davis also went to a full count before slapping an opposite-field
fly ball to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Sox right fielder Magglio Ordonez, not nearly as familiar with
the wall as Buhner, positioned himself at the base of the barrier.
Bad move.
</P>
<P>
   The ball caromed toward the infield, giving Buhner time to score
the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good at-bat,'' said manager Lou Piniella of Davis,
who fouled off two full-count pitches before driving in his 72nd
run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella then turned over the game to Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox rookie shortstop Mike Caruso greeted Timlin with a
single, sending up Frank Thomas, Albert Belle and Robin Ventura, a
productive threesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no fun facing those guys,'' Timlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas lined out to left fielder Rich Amaral. Belle, 3-for-3 at
the time with a home run and double, lined out even harder to
Amaral, who snagged the sinking liner at his shoe tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw both of them (Thomas and Belle) sinkers,'' Timlin
said. ``With the ball going down, and them trying to lift it, you
get a lot of top spin on the ball and that's what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richie made a nice play (on Belle) and I asked him if his hand
hurt. He said it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Still one out away, Timlin said he worked Ventura on the outside
and ``then tried to trick him by coming inside. I was trying to get
a slider down and in and he raked it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball glanced off first baseman David Segui's glove, putting
the tying run on third base. But the game ended when Ordonez popped
out to Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Davis saved a run with a diving catch and throw to nail Durham
at first base and end the sixth inning. Amaral robbed Thomas of a
hit in the third with a lunging catch while running to the
left-field line and Cora snagged a Robert Machado line drive in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, who hasn't won since July 25 and remains stuck on 10
wins, yielded two runs in the first inning. Belle drove in one with
a single and Ventura doubled home the other.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner pulled the Mariners even in the fourth with his 13th
homer of the season. Cora capped the three-run inning with a
bases-loaded infield single for hit No. 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Fassero couldn't hold that lead, or the one-run cushion
Martinez provided in the fifth with his 23rd homer.
</P>
<P>
   It came down to the bullpens and Seattle's won for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, working for the third straight game, has been
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see is a good, live arm,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with him in Montreal and he throws strikes,'' added
Segui.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, claimed on waivers from the expansion Tampa Bay Devil
Rays during spring training, won his first major-league game since
Sept. 12, 1997 when he was pitching for the Expos and defeated the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you we were going to pitch him to see what he can do
and we have,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Durham, who went 9-for-13 during a three-game series against the
Mariners last weekend at Comiskey Park, greeted Fassero with a
game-opening single to trigger the two-run Chicago first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Mariner third baseman, lent a helping hand, bobbling
Caruso's grounder, putting runners on first and second with none
out. After Thomas flied to left field, Belle smacked a drive off
the wall in left, scoring Durham. Belle, attempting to stretch a
single into a double, was thrown out at second.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura delivered a run-scoring double to left before Fassero
wiggled out of trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
