<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. ATTACK ON TERRORIST SITES &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans the following package of stories for
Sunday AMs covering the aftermath of attacks Thursday against
suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-TERROR-WAR (Washington) _ The barrage of missiles that
fell on Afghanistan and Sudan last week was a small battle in a war
without a foreseeable end, American leaders are warning _ not the
moral equivalent of war, but war itself, similar in some ways to
the long twilight struggle against the Soviet Union. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RDP (Washington) _ President Clinton vowed Saturday that
the United States would use ``all the tools at our disposal'' to
fight the terrorist network of Osama bin Laden, as the
administration outlined efforts to squeeze him financially
following Thursday's cruise-missiles strikes in Afghanistan and the
Sudan. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S.-DIPLOMACY (Washington) _ American and Western
officials describe the Clinton administration's decision to use
missile strikes to respond to the embassy bombings in East Africa
as a significant departure from its past practice of seeking
international support and U.N. authorization for American military
action. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN _ Developments in Sudan, as the government there
continues to say that the building struck by U.S. missiles was a
drug-making factory. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   We will update this advisory as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   And be sure to check the Graphics and Photo budgets for more
detailed information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
