<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. BOMBING ATTACK STORIES:
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-TERROR-WAR (Washington) _ The barrage of missiles that
fell on Afghanistan and Sudan last week was a small battle in a war
without a foreseeable end, American leaders are warning _ not the
moral equivalent of war, but war itself, similar in some ways to
the long twilight struggle against the Soviet Union. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-RDP (Washington) _ President Clinton vowed Saturday that
the United States would use ``all the tools at our disposal'' to
fight the terrorist network of Osama bin Laden, as the
administration outlined efforts to squeeze him financially
following Thursday's cruise-missiles strikes in Afghanistan and the
Sudan. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S.-DIPLOMACY (Washington) _ American and Western
officials describe the Clinton administration's decision to use
missile strikes to respond to the embassy bombings in East Africa
as a significant departure from its past practice of seeking
international support and U.N. authorization for American military
action. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN _ Developments in Sudan, as the government there
continues to say that the building struck by U.S. missiles was a
drug-making factory. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-BREAKDOWN (Lagos, Nigeria) _ Nigeria, Africa's most
populous nation, is rich. It has vast reserves of oil and minerals,
fertile land, more than 30 universities and many talented, highly
educated people. But after decades of gross mismanagement under
military rulers, it is also marked by sweeping poverty and ethnic
tensions. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Kaluga, Russia) _ For most people in Kaluga, last
week was just another chapter in a crisis that dates from 1991, to
the collapse of communism and of a way of life that was, if nothing
else, secure. Since then, they have lived through worse: the
soaring inflation of the early 1990s utterly wiped out people's
Soviet-era savings. This time, their savings accounts have remained
secure _ at least for now. What has made the week's events so
painful, and so bitter, was the reminder that the seven-year crisis
is not over, not by a long shot. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN-PALME (Stockholm, Sweden) _ The site is so modestly
marked that it is easy to miss. Perhaps appropriately, one must bow
one's head to see it. The simple brass plaque in the pavement at
the Tunnelgatan entrance to the Hotorget subway station reads, ``On
this spot Sweden's Prime Minister Olof Palme was killed.'' People
by the scores find it daily, though, drawn to the site where many
Swedes think their country began to lose its way. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-DRUG-KINGPIN (Basseterre, St. Kitts and Nevis) _
American law-enforcement officials regard Charles Miller as one of
the most dangerous and powerful drug traffickers in the Caribbean
and have been seeking his extradition for two years. Now the stakes
are higher than ever: the State Department says he has threatened
to kill American college students enrolled here if the local
government hands him over to the United States. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-CONGO (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ A last-ditch effort
by South Africa to negotiate a peace settlement for the Democratic
Republic of Congo appeared to get off to a poor start, when two of
the key players failed to show up for a scheduled meeting, though
one sent a representative. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N.-BUTLER (United Nations) _ The chief U.N. arms
inspector for Iraq, Richard Butler, warned Friday that he might
soon test Baghdad's resolve to block further weapons inspections by
sending his team to examine a new site. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-POLYGAMY (Salt Lake City) _ As this state rebuilds highways
and hotels to play host to the 2002 Winter Olympics, modern Utah is
wrestling with a social institution inherited from its 19th-century
Mormon pioneers _ polygamy. By James brooke.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-WELFARE-GARDEN (Ethete, Wyo.) _ In the face of cutbacks
brought about by the overhaul of welfare programs, members of the
Northern Arapaho Tribe here on the Wind River Reservation have
started a seven-acre community garden with donated land, seeds and
equipment to grow vegetables for themselves and for the elderly and
disabled who cannot work.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ICEHOUSE (Houston) _ A paean to the Texas icehouse or
open-air beer joint, a cross between a saloon and a convenience
store. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-AUTO-SETTLE (Los Angeles) _ California motorists who
obtain restitution from automakers for defective vehicles may no
longer have to promise they will stay quiet as part of their
settlements. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BADDREAM-HOUSE (Sagaponack, N.Y.) _ Ira Rennert's dream house
in the Hamptons will have 29 bedrooms, 39 bathrooms, a 164-seat
theater and a restaurant-sized kitchen with five refrigerators, six
sinks and a 1,500-gallon grease trap. The 63-acre, five-building
spread, at the rim of the Atlantic Ocean here, will dwarf the White
House, San Simeon and Bill Gates' mega-mansion. Can a complex of
such staggering dimensions be considered a single-family home? This
is the question being asked by the Sagaponack Homeowners'
Association, an ad hoc group of wealthy residents who are
challenging Rennert's building permits, granted in the dead of
winter when his prospective neighbors were 100 miles away in
Manhattan. By Jane Gross.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEGACY (Washington) _ President Clinton has spent his
whole life devouring biographies of his predecessors, and he now
has more yesterdays behind him in office than he does tomorrows.
After the most tumultuous week of his presidency, capped by a
dramatic strike on terrorist outposts abroad, the question that
haunts Clinton is how he will be judged in light of the Monica
Lewinsky matter. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIVILEGE (Washington) _ President Clinton's defense of
his private conduct this year has endangered more than his
reputation and credibility. The legal battles he has fought to
avoid acknowledging that his behavior with Monica Lewinsky was
inappropriate may have eroded presidential power and prerogatives
for future presidents, legal experts, constitutional scholars and
political scientists say. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NOTEBOOK _ A digest of items from the Clinton vacation.
By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (Moving in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-WOHLERS-PROFILE _ Mark Wohlers, 28, has been a major league
star since 1991 _ a relief pitcher for the Atlanta Braves, and
among the hardest throwers in the history of the game. Capable of
overpowering hitters with a 100-mph fastball, he saved 97 games for
Atlanta spanning 1995 and 1997. But earlier this year, Wohlers
suddenly lost his ability to throw strikes. By Bruce Weber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ It's not easy being in love with a president. Just
ask Monica. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK TIMES PARTNERS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Please note that your New York Times News Service report
includes news and features from The Arizona Republic, Bloomberg
News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Kansas
City Star, The Los Angeles Daily News, The San Francisco Chronicle,
The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New
