<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-REVIEW-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SAVE THE RUBLE, RUSSIA DANCES WITH THE WOLVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, armchair diplomats took comfort in their
mastery of heady terms like ``throw-weight'' and ``detente,'' and
tested their mettle parsing the differences between SALT talks and
START talks.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of the Cold War and the swift, furious opening of
financial markets in far-flung locales like Malaysia, Brazil and
the Czech Republic have changed all that. Now anyone interested in
world affairs has to contend with a new vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia's woes of the past week have illustrated, the new
buzzwords of international diplomacy are ``devaluation,''
``currency speculation'' and ``debt moratorium'' _ terminology just
as opaque and loaded with free-floating dread as anything in the
Cold War lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, not only were Russian lawmakers calling for the
resignation of President Boris Yeltsin, but the world's financial
markets were being pummeled, largely because of fears set in motion
by the decision of Yeltsin's government to devalue the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   A devaluation typically occurs when a country suffering through
an economic downturn decides it's time to lower the value of its
currency in relation to another _ usually the dollar _ to give its
exporters more muscle in international trade. A country's exports
suddenly become cheaper overseas and, ideally, local cash registers
start ringing.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, Russia decided to do just that, announcing that
it would let the value of its currency fall as low as 9.5 rubles to
the dollar from 6.5 rubles, effectively devaluing its currency by
34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Russia is not likely to get much of a boost from the
devaluation because the price of its most important export, oil,
has already plunged this year, as have prices for other basic
commodities the country exports.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia exported cars, CD players or personal computers,
devaluation might have helped undercut the prices of other
international competitors. But as any shopper knows, Russia makes
nothing that competes with brand names like Toyota, Sony and
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of devaluation is that it makes imports more
expensive. Since Russia imports quite a bit of food and other
staples, the average Russian is going to find it even harder to
make ends meet. And Russian financial institutions that owe
dollar-denominated loans are discovering that the cost of paying
off their debts will rise in direct proportion to the drop in the
ruble's value.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news all around. So, why did Russia devalue?
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no choice,'' said Nancy Kimelman, chief economist for
Thomson Financial Services in Boston. ``You have everyone and their
mother trading against the ruble, and if you don't want it to fall
below a certain level the government has to go in there and defend
it. And the government didn't have the cash to do that, because
Russia is basically bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   What Russia has learned, as have several Asian countries that
are now economic basket cases, is that inviting market forces into
your economy also invites the wolves. Traders who make their living
betting on the direction of currency prices smell blood when a
strong currency masks a weak economy. Russia, which had already
squandered International Monetary Fund aid bolstering the ruble,
opted out of the blood bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians know that if they defend the currency's value,
it's just going into the pocket of some currency trader,'' Ms.
Kimelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also declared a debt moratorium last week, which amounts
to a 90-day breather on the repayment of $40 billion in foreign
loans and perhaps as much as $100 billion in ``hedges'' _ insurance
that traders and banks use to protect themselves from sudden
currency swings.
</P>
<P>
   Moratoriums typically give battered economies some wiggle room
by allowing lenders and borrowers to renegotiate loans. But the
tactic, which has had mixed results in countries like South Korea
and Indonesia over the last several months, does nothing to address
underlying economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Russia's moratorium was lauded by some analysts.
``I wouldn't have advised them to devalue,'' said Morris Goldstein,
a former IMF official and a senior fellow at the Institute for
International Economics in Washington. ``I think it would have been
smarter to restructure the debt first.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But everyone has to be treated fairly for such a restructuring
to work, and foreign investors, who have grown used to reaping fat
profits in Russia, went into a tizzy last week when they learned
that some of the debt would be repriced more favorably for domestic
investors than for foreign investors, according to Credit Suisse
First Boston. Foreign investors, threatening never to open their
wallets in Russia again, quickly slapped down that proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Private jets are now ferrying foreign lenders into Russia to
repackage the debt in a way that all sides can agree on, and a new
proposal is expected by Monday. But while the debt restructuring
may calm Russian markets, the devaluation genie that has been let
out of the bottle may produce even more turmoil in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Russia carried more weight on the international
stage in the old world of detente than in the new world of
devaluation. It still sits atop a formidable nuclear stockpile, but
for all its military might the nation of 147 million people
currently lacks the economic heft of the temporarily declawed Asian
tigers. And in a world where vast sums of money zip across borders
with a few taps on a computer keyboard, the ruble is just a blip on
traders' screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Ms. Kimelman said. ``If Russia had the
wealth to support its geopolitical might, it would be a different
story. But they don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
