<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZARRE-BURB-3Takes-L     08-22 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZARRE-BURB-3Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY COMMUNITY COMBINES SUBLIME WITH SURREAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- Somewhere between the postcard ideal
of small-town America and a weirder, more disturbing reality lies
this quiet Antelope Valley community.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty miles north of its metropolitan namesake and 25 miles
from the nearest post office, this high-desert bedroom town of
14,000 is a place of extreme, even surreal contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   Of friendly greetings and simmering resentments. Of tidy ranch
houses and ghostly rows of abandoned homes. Of majestic buttes and
hazy mountains offset by animal pens scarred with graffiti and
front lawns littered with trash.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it's a place divided between those who stay because they
love it and those who stay simply because they are stuck. With the
collapse of the aerospace and defense industries in the early
1990s, Lake Los Angeles has suffered from many of the same problems
that afflict neighboring Palmdale and Lancaster, including a rash
of drug-related crime and a surge in low-income transients lured
here by plunging rents and high vacancy rates.
</P>
<P>
   Even the community's name hints at a contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say, I like Lake Los Angeles, but there ain't no lake
and it ain't near Los Angeles,'' said Barbara Crane, 70, a retiree
who moved here in 1958 to teach school and now says she can't
imagine living anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Since its first scattered housing tracts rose from the desert
floor in the late 1960s -- around an artificial pond that dried up
years ago -- Lake Los Angeles has struggled to construct an
identity. Few Angelenos know it exists, much less where to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the community got on the map -- though not for
reasons anyone liked. On July 23, Mike and Kathleen ``Katrina''
Gentry were charged with murder and child abuse in the starvation
death of their severely disabled teen-age daughter. When she died
Feb. 6, 1996, Lindsay Gentry, 15, was 4 feet 8 inches tall and
weighed less than 50 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors have rallied around the popular, churchgoing couple,
raising money for their legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us are in the courtroom, so unless you have evidence
yourself, it's all B.S., know what I mean?'' said Jenny Keys, 34,
echoing a prevailing feeling among locals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the incident seems to underscore the ambivalent nature of a
community that still likes to think of itself as a peaceful country
village, but in some ways has begun to act like a troubled inner
city.
</P>
<P>
   Glimpsed from a passing car along dusty Palmdale Boulevard, Lake
Los Angeles appears to be a picturesque oasis in a singularly
unforgiving environment.
</P>
<P>
   Residents love to talk about the area's soul-stirring solitude
and natural splendor. Indeed, the dramatic backdrop of the Angeles
National Forest and the miles of gnarly Joshua trees stretching
across the horizon speak eloquently enough for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people who pass through the desert see nothing but
brown,'' said John Donovan, pastor of Spirit of Christ Lutheran
Church, a bustling storefront operation in a strip mall off the
main drag of 170th Street East. ``There's a lot of beautiful things
in the desert, but if you drive right through, you won't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   To Keys, 34, and her husband Robert, 41, refugees from L.A.'s
San Fernando Valley, Lake Los Angeles is the best of all possible
worlds. Where else can you find cheap housing, solid schools,
mind-blowing scenery and small-town ambience an hour's drive from
the city?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can live here and be wonderful, little happy Okies, and
still go down to the theater, to the beach. I can see `Phantom (of
the Opera),' '' said Jenny Keys, who runs Swift Digits, a
data-entry firm.
</P>
<P>
   The couple left L.A.'s Chatsworth suburb nine years ago after
some grammar-school children there were found snorting cocaine. Now
they and their four children spend summer nights scanning meteor
showers in the velvet desert sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lay out on our picnic table and watch 'em,'' Jenny Keys
said.
</P>
<P>
   This splendid isolation comes at a price.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a supermarket in sight, not a medical clinic,
pharmacy or movie theater. Rite Aid's recent announcement that it
plans to open a store in town was greeted with hosannas.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the U.S. Postal Service is concerned, there
(ITAL)is(END ITAL) no Lake Los Angeles. The area is split between
Lancaster and Palmdale ZIP codes, and it's a 25-mile drive for mail
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the bastard child,'' said one resident.
</P>
<P>
   Locals speak of ``down there'' -- referring to Los Angeles --
with a mixture of envy and disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Many give high marks to the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department, whose Lancaster office recently added a second patrol
car to cover the region. And they have mostly good things to say
about county Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich and his efforts to
upgrade the area's outdated infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are longtime complaints about ``second-class
citizenship,'' plus a general perception that the community has
been neglected for 30 years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's not real hard to find people who want to have it both
ways,'' Robert Keys said. ``They want to keep the county rural, but
they're sick and tired of not having any services.''
</P>
<P>
   The first major wave of urban immigrants -- many from the San
Fernando Valley -- began arriving in the early 1980s, driven by
smog, congestion and inflated real estate prices. Spacious,
three-bedroom houses on 1{-acre lots cost $60,000 or less in Lake
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The area then was populated with alfalfa farmers and aerospace
workers from Lockheed and Edwards Air Force Base, whose independent
mind-set set the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved out here because we wanted to be left alone. Just to
be ourselves,'' Crane said.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia for a vanishing frontier is reflected in the rustic
street names: High Chaparral Avenue, Frontier Circus, Mackenna's
Gold Avenue, Rawhide Avenue, Jubilee Trail. Several houses sport a
pioneer look, with cacti, imitation wagon wheels and bleached
ornamental steer skulls poking up from their front lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Other homes flaunt the inalienable right to keep anything you
like in your back yard: lumber, llamas, goats, chickens,
above-ground pools, Rottweilers, lowrider cars, archery targets,
rusting hot-water tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Like the monumental landscape around it, life here can be
freakish. A year ago, an 11-year-old boy had to be rescued after
slipping into a crevice in a giant boulder. Warning signs along
Palmdale Boulevard note the stiff fines imposed for abandoning
animals (thousands are left in the desert every year).
</P>
<P>
   Recently, county officials launched a campaign to evict hundreds
of families who have been living in illegal travel trailers, often
without proper toilet facilities or sanitary water.
</P>
<P>
   The incongruities fascinate Heinz Legler, owner of Club Ed, a
movie-location scouting company just outside town, housed in the
set he originally built for ``Eye of the Storm,'' a 1991 desert
gothic thriller starring Dennis Hopper.
</P>
<P>
   The set -- a reproduction of a vintage diner, motel and a
24-hour truck stop -- now is used for TV shoots, commercials and
music videos, as well as feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain romance and a certain nostalgia to the
desert and to Route 66,'' said Legler, 46, a native of Stuttgart,
Germany. ``It's that independence, that freedom, which you never
get in Europe. If you come to the United States, you're on your
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Culturally speaking, Lake Los Angeles occupies a buffer zone
between the wild, ornery Old West and the sanitized, subdivided New
West. Wary of ``desert rat'' stereotypes, residents revel in their
isolation and eccentricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, a bunch of crazies come out here,'' Crane said,
laughing. ``We're all a little bit nuts. But there are nuts all
over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   According to real estate agent Maurice Kunkel, inbound migration
peaked between 1983 and 1989. Latecomers found something other than
a desert Eden: a sagging economy, few jobs and growing frustration.
As the recession bottomed out in the early 1990s and property
values sagged, many homeowners walked away from houses that had
lost half their value.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up with a lot of HUD repos and bank repos. We're
still dealing with that,'' said Kunkel, who estimates that almost
10 percent of Lake Los Angeles' 3,550 homes are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Empty houses invite teen-age vandals. Scavengers roll up in
their trucks at night and haul away appliances, chandeliers and
whatever else they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take everything but the foundation,'' said sheriff's
Deputy Christopher Keeling.
</P>
<P>
   An unwelcome cottage industry also has developed. Three weeks
ago, sheriff's deputies arrested a Lake Los Angeles man on charges
of possessing chemicals used to make methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 16th meth lab found in the Antelope Valley this year,
and it came four weeks after city, sheriff's and state officials
established a task force to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future out here is very bad,'' said Ken Groden, 65, a
semiretired machinist who moved from L.A.'s Van Nuys suburb 14
years ago, as he busied himself tending a neighbor's garden one
recent morning. Groden said the house he bought then for $62,000 is
now worth only $64,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some long-term residents attribute community problems to recent
arrivals from Los Angeles, some of them on public assistance. But
they empathize with the newcomers' reasons for fleeing Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're leaving (Los Angeles) for the right reasons. They're
getting their kids out of the inner city, but they bring a whole
lot of baggage with them,'' said Dorothea Pickhinke, who with her
husband, Tony, runs the popular Pizza Factory (``We toss 'em,
they're awesome!'').
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 3RD TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Finnigan is a man with a dream. The gadfly from
Massachusetts was here in the early 1980s, when the lake was
allowed to dry up because of rising maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, it broke our hearts. It was like the end of the
world,'' the 21-year resident said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Finnigan is helping lead a drive to restore the lake at an
estimated cost of $700,000. So far, a committee has rounded up
1,600 signatures supporting the plan, but the county has demanded
an engineering study first. A new lake would have to meet
flood-control standards and likely would need to be sealed with
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Whether residents will want to pick up the tab is uncertain. But
some hopeful residents predict their property values could double
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lake means so much out here; it'll give the people a
lift,'' Finnigan said. ``It'll make life a little bit easier
instead of going down to Santa Monica, know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Looking across this spare, deceptive landscape, you seem to be
looking back across time, thousands of years ago, when American
Indians lived on what was then a verdant plain. When the water
supply dwindled, the Antelope Valley changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   Now water has become a symbol of renewal for a community in
flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people thrown together so quickly, I can't
even predict what Lake Los Angeles will be like in five years, let
alone 10 or 15 years,'' Robert Keys said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
