<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-SUDAN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY AS `PARIAH,' A NATION RESPONDS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ATTACK-RDP, ATTACK-U.S.-DIPLOMACY and
ATTACK-TERROR-WAR)  
(ak) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, Sudan _ Abdel Rahman Ibrahim el-Khalifa is a
Western-trained lawyer, a member of the governing Islamic party and
until recently Sudan's attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a perfectly pressed safari suit and seated in front
of windows that allowed a breeze into the stifling heat of his law
offices Saturday, he expressed some commonly held views here about
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the good books of the Americans, you are an
angel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are not a friend, you are a pariah,'' he added with
disgust. ``They set the standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, he asked, did the United States strike at a Sudanese plant
that Washington contends was financed by the Islamic militant Osama
bin Laden, when bin Laden has many investments in Saudi Arabia that
remain unscathed?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you say everything he invested in in Saudi Arabia
should be bombarded?'' Khalifa said, rejecting Washington's
argument that the pharmaceutical plant was a cover for the
production of a precursor to nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, two days after the plant on the outskirts of the
capital was destroyed by American cruise missiles, the venting of
fury at the United States proceeded in full force. In the dusty
street below Khalifa's office, young anti-American demonstrators,
let out of school early, marched by. Khalifa, who attended McGill
University in Montreal, gave them a clenched-fist salute and a
thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   And in the heart of the city, thousands more answered the call
of the government and marched, carrying banners and shouting
slogans like: ``Down, down with the U.S.A.! We won't be ruled by
the CIA!''
</P>
<P>
   One banner read, in English, ``No War for Monica,'' a reference
to suggestions that the attacks were meant to deflect American
public attention from the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the demonstrators were teen-age students, dressed in the
guerrilla-style camouflage uniforms that are the standard school
garb for girls and boys here. There was little of the steely
defiance that is common in some mass demonstrations elsewhere. Many
laughed and giggled as they sauntered along, shouting the lines.
Older people watched from the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   But at Khartoum University, where the government is generally
viewed with skepticism, most students ignored the rallies and
attended classes. ``Don't believe anything this government says _
anything,'' said one student, a linguist, who would not give his
name.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic authorities, who have held power since a 1989 coup,
have not won over the general population either, but manage to
remain in charge with the help of an efficient network of
informers. They also rely on what seems to be a high tolerance here
for ever-declining living standards.
</P>
<P>
   The government has seized on the American attack to try to
energize sliding support. More street demonstrations against the
United States are expected in the coming days, with some likely to
be led by President Omar Hassan el-Bashir dressed in traditional
white flowing robes and a turban.
</P>
<P>
   Khalifa said it was easy to mobilize anti-American feelings, in
part because the Clinton administration had rejected openings in
the last several years to repair its hostile relationship with
Sudan. The United States has labeled the country a sponsor of
terrorism.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bin Laden, whom Washington accuses of masterminding the
terrorist bombings of two American embassies in East Africa, lived
in Sudan for two years ``as an investor'' but was asked to leave in
1996, Khalifa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you are part of a family but someone is causing
trouble you ask him to leave,'' Khalifa said of bin Laden's
departure.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer declined to be specific about bin Laden's reasons for
leaving but said there had been ``a lot of fuss'' about him being
in Sudan. Washington had accused the country of harboring bin
Laden, who is accused of being a wealthy terrorist, and had said he
was running training camps for his followers here.
</P>
<P>
   After 1996, Khalifa said, Sudan suggested a dialogue with the
United States, but the Clinton administration rebuffed the
overture.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think this is an Islamic regime that has to be opposed,''
he said. ``We will not be a puppet for another country like the
United States, and if you are not in their pocket they give you a
hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   What he is most bitter about, Khalifa said, is that Washington
has cynically used Sudan as a ``scapegoat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bombard two countries for the sake of one single person?''
he asked, referring to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after hearing the head of state telling lies to his own
people and having a filthy affair with Monica Lewinsky, I can
understand why Americans act in a vulgar way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
