u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARIBBEAN-DRUG-KINGPI     08-22 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-DRUG-KINGPIN-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TURNCOAT NOW TURNING ON AMERICANS IN CARIBBEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By LARRY ROHTER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASSETERRE, St. Kitts and Nevis _ U.S. law-enforcement officials
regard Charles Miller as one of the most dangerous and powerful
drug traffickers in the Caribbean and have been seeking his
extradition for two years. Now the stakes are higher than ever: the
State Department says he has threatened to kill U.S. college
students enrolled here if the local government hands him over to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Having furnished Miller with his freedom and the identity he now
uses, U.S. authorities have every reason to take that warning
seriously. Less than a decade ago, when he was a police informer
called Cecil Connor, Miller was granted full immunity to testify in
a case against Jamaican drug gangs operating in Florida and New
York. He acknowledged involvement in nine drug-related slayings and
was placed in the federal witness-protection program.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning, with a U.S. passport, to this country, which he
left as a teen-ager, Miller has been linked by law-enforcement
officials to a series of drug-related cases, among them the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Along with two associates, Miller, who gives his age as 38, is
now wanted in Miami on charges of smuggling nearly a ton of cocaine
to Florida. In 1996, a magistrate here refused to allow Miller to
be extradited to the United States, but his decision was overturned
by a higher court earlier this year, and new hearings on the
petition are scheduled for October.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely violent and unstable individual who has
acquired a great deal of wealth and exercises a great deal of
power,'' said a foreign official with long experience in the
region. ``He will stop at nothing to keep from falling into
American hands.'' And since St. Kitts and Nevis is the smallest
nation in the Western Hemisphere, the official noted, with only
46,000 people, ``Just a little bit of effort goes a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's case is emblematic of the difficulties that the
mini-states of the Caribbean face in their efforts to combat drug
trafficking. More than one-third of the cocaine now consumed in the
United States is believed to be shipped through the region, and
traffickers are increasingly blatant in their efforts to corrupt
governments and encourage local consumption of their product.
</P>
<P>
   At Ross University and in neighborhoods where the school's 280
veterinary students live, protection has been noticeably beefed up,
with agents of the U.S. and local governments as well as private
security. University officials said they hoped the 54 students who
have withdrawn from classes and gone back to the United States will
return when the fall term begins.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and the government of St. Kitts and Nevis,
which depends heavily on tourism, have emphasized that no blanket
warning to Americans to stay away has been issued.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here, Prime Minister Denzil Douglas said his
government was cooperating fully with the United States and other
nations to ``increase and improve security,'' adding that local
police ``continue to keep the suspect under surveillance.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller did not respond to telephone messages left for him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But in a long interview last year, he dismissed the accusations
against him as politically motivated and said he had worked for
U.S. and British intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government, the British and the Americans, they all wish
Charles Miller would be run over or drop dead,'' he said, because
of his knowledge of ``all the Machiavellian moves that have been
happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   As Miller tells it, he moved to Jamaica in the mid-1970s and was
recruited as a political enforcer by the Jamaica Labor Party. He
says that the CIA trained him and later helped him flee the
Jamaican prison where he was serving a 75-year sentence for armed
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such allegations are utter nonsense,'' Mark Mansfield, a
spokesman for the CIA, said in a telephone interview from the
agency's headquarters in Virginia. ``This individual has never been
employed by or affiliated with the CIA.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the United States, court records indicate, Miller linked
up with a Jamaica-based gang to sell cocaine and marijuana in Miami
and Rochester, N.Y. But after being arrested, he turned on the gang
to cooperate with prosecutors, giving testimony that led to the
conviction of top leaders of the group, and abandoned his identity
as Cecil Connor.
</P>
<P>
   St. Kitts and Nevis has signed a new treaty, awaiting approval
by the U.S. Congress, that would considerably simplify any future
extradition proceedings. But the measure is not retroactive, and
government officials here say that any attempt to move against
Miller for the threats made here would only further complicate the
existing extradition proceedings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
