<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The sluggish remnants of Tropical Storm Charley will drift
westward in the vicinity of the Big Bend of Texas Sunday. Though
the winds of Charley will be diminished, the system will still
harbor an impressive reservoir of tropical moisture. Thus, heavy
rains from showers and thunderstorms will threaten south-central
and southwest Texas. Flash flooding is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hurricane Bonnie will strengthen as it churns
relatively slowly northwest near the Bahamas. Though isolated,
routine thunderstorms will develop over eastern Florida. A
compensating area of sinking air preceding the rising air
associated with Hurricane Bonnie will limit storms near Florida's
east coast.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to lethargic tropical systems, a current of
fast-moving air will flow over the northern tier states at
altitudes near 30,000 feet. A series of disturbances will move
eastward with this current, generating clusters of showers and
thunderstorms. One disturbance will spark showers and storms early
Sunday in eastern Michigan and then forge into New York and New
England along and ahead of a warm front.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop over the
upper Great Lakes and northern Minnesota Sunday afternoon in
response to another disturbance. A few of these storms will
approach severe levels, with strong winds and hail posing a threat.
Clusters of potent storms will also erupt farther southwest into
parts of Iowa and eastern Nebraska along a cool front associated
with the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Probing Storms
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane hunters continued to relay crucial information about
Bonnie to forecasters at the National Hurricane Center Saturday.
Though aircraft probing the stormy ring of thunderstorms that
surround the eye of hurricanes have experienced serious turbulence
on occasion, such flights are generally much smoother than flying
into severe thunderstorms over land. The updrafts of air that
sustain ferocious continental storms can reach speeds of 60 miles
an hour or more and can cause severe turbulence. By contrast, the
updrafts in thunderstorms in the eye wall of hurricanes are much
slower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
