<HEADER>
A7285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ICEHOUSE-640&AMP;AD     08-22 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ICEHOUSE-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICEHOUSES ARE SLOWLY MELTING INTO THE SOUTH TEXAS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ More often than not, midday finds Clynn Cox sitting on
one of the chipped swivel chairs at the West Alabama Ice House,
nursing a long-neck bottle of iced beer wrapped in a sopping paper
napkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming for 18 years, which isn't so long,'' said
Cox, 66, a retired ironworker. ``Some of the guys have been coming
for 30 years or more. I guess you could say it's kind of a family
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox, the beer and even a stray dog called Stray, stretched out
on the cool concrete, its fur blown to attention by an
industrial-strength floor fan, are all part of a classic and slowly
disappearing South Texas tableau, the neighborhood icehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that there may be a handful elsewhere, but you
tend to find the real, classic icehouses in a line from Houston to
San Antonio and then south to the border,'' said Char Miller, a
professor of American history at Trinity University in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   An icehouse is an open-air beer joint, a cross between a saloon
and a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   One University of Texas historian traced the icehouse as far
back as 1840, when ships in Maine would load their holds with ice,
head down the coast and into the Gulf of Mexico and sell whatever
had not melted when they docked in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, they sold ice,'' said Jerry Markantonis,
whose family owns and runs the West Alabama Ice House. ``Then in
the 1920s, they began to add some items, like bread or milk or
beer. They became like neighborhood groceries or convenience
stores. But after a while, a lot of them realized that the most
popular item was beer so they did away with everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be difficult to get people in South Texas to agree on
what constitutes an icehouse. ``We don't have a real definition for
an icehouse,'' said Julie Utsey, a spokeswoman for the Texas
Alcoholic Beverage Commission. A lot of places call themselves
icehouses _ there are more than 50 listed under ``tavern'' in the
Houston yellow pages _ that aficionados will tell you are not
actually icehouses, in the classic sense.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Munoz and Geoff Edwards, curators for a traveling exhibit
on ``The South Texas Ice House'' that is scheduled to come to El
Museo del Barrio in New York City in the fall of 1999, describe an
icehouse as ``originally a rural grocery store and cantina which
eventually transformed into a spontaneous form of community
center.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say that the only authentic icehouses have inadequate
parking, because they were built to cater to the neighborhood.
Others say that a true icehouse has no air-conditioning, or will
cool its beer only under mountains of ice. One professor described
it as a drinking establishment where it is difficult to tell
``where the inside ends and the outside begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Markantonis, disdainful of what he sees as a growing number of
beer joints that misuse the name icehouse, has his own definition.
``It must be a place that, at one time, actually sold blocks of
ice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never really been properly defined,'' said Jesse Hall,
a graduate student at the University of the Incarnate Word in San
Antonio who is making a film about an icehouse for his thesis.
``The few real icehouses, the ones that are still around, are to
their neighborhood what a town center was to a small village.''
</P>
<P>
   The heyday of the icehouse was between the end of World War II
and the late 1960s. It was illegal to sell hard liquor by the drink
in Texas until 1969, which helped sustain the icehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Many icehouses closed in the '70s and '80s, when their
neighborhoods disappeared in the rush of suburbanization. But now,
as Houston and San Antonio join many cities in seeing a fresh wave
of suburbanites moving back into the city centers, icehouses are
endangered by rising real-estate prices and suburban sensibilities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The values those returning suburbanites have and the values of
the local communities are quite different,'' Miller said. ``What
you see is this culture clash. It's classic. In the end, though, as
these longstanding communities fade, so will the institutions
associated with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people agree that an icehouse is open to the air, usually
with outside tables and overhangs, though it often has garage-like
doors that can be closed during the coldest winter evenings when
the temperatures can dip into the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really emerged out of mom-and-pop operations very closely
tied to discrete neighborhoods, serving largely working-class
populations,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, icehouses tend to draw Hispanic customers. In
Houston and East Texas, more customers tend to be white tradesmen
and oil workers. Some, like the West Alabama Ice House, draw a
diverse group from construction workers to downtown office workers
with cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very plastic forms, that's what they are,'' said Tom
Denyer, a former professor of political science at Texas A &AMP; M who
has written academic articles on the icehouse phenomenon. ``They're
folk venues. They're collaborations between the owner and the
regulars. They're ongoing performance art.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Markantonis, 30, the son of Jerry Markantonis and the
manager of the West Alabama Ice House, dumped a bucket of ice cubes
into stainless steel tubs filled with long-neck beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you of two icehouses that were put out of business
in recent years by neighborhoods who thought they were too loud or
rowdy,'' he said. ``There's no doubt the neighborhood is changing,
but we've been lucky to have support from our community. A real
icehouse is a family place, and that's what we try to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, several young children, including his own, were
running around nearby.
</P>
<P>
   He reached in and pulled out a cold bottle and wrapped it in a
paper napkin, which instantly clung to the wet sides. There is a
deeply held belief among icehouse aficionados that, just as beer in
a bottle tastes better than beer in a can, so does beer kept in ice
taste better than refrigerated beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's true,'' Cox said. ``I think maybe it's
psychological. Though there's just something about it when you pick
up a beer that's been in ice, the way it feels in your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox tries to remember back to his first visit, when he had just
moved to the neighborhood and thought the icehouse looked like a
nice place. Had it changed much?
</P>
<P>
   ``Change?'' he said, momentarily puzzled. ``It doesn't change
much around here. That's why we come.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-AUTO-SETTLE(500     08-22 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-AUTO-SETTLE(500&AMP;ADD)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA ACTS TO BAR GAG ORDERS IN AUTO DEFECT CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ak) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California motorists who obtain restitution from
automakers for defective vehicles may no longer have to promise
they will stay quiet as part of their settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation approved by California lawmakers would bar
automakers from imposing gag rules in agreements to repurchase cars
or trucks that are deemed defective under the state's lemon law.
The bill, the first of its kind in the nation, awaits the signature
of Gov. Pete Wilson; an aide said Wilson was likely to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Demands for silence on the settlement terms of a court case, or
on details of a matter resolved privately, are common in disputes
involving medical malpractice, product liability and corporate
malfeasance. Increasingly, consumer advocates say, these secrecy
clauses are being written into automakers' agreements to buy back
badly flawed vehicles. Some regulators say the gags erode their
oversight by making it hard for them to track vehicles that have
been branded as lemons.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp.'s reselling of 116 such defective vehicles is
central to a two-year legal fight between the company and
California's Department of Motor Vehicles. In June, a Superior
Court judge ordered the dispute to be reconsidered, and, in effect,
reinstated the proposed penalty _ the harshest by any state for
violations of lemon laws. The penalty, which has yet to take
effect, would bar Chrysler from shipping cars or trucks to the
state for 45 days. Chrysler has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Annually, about 100,000 vehicles are repurchased by automakers
because of defects, including 5,000 to 10,000 in California, said
Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety in
Washington. He said consumer complaints often prompted
investigations by Federal safety officials. ``If the gags are
widespread, you're going to dry up the source of complaints,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Charles M. Calderon, a Democrat who co-sponsored the
bill with Democratic Assemblyman Kevin Shelley, said he expected
Wilson to approve the legislation. ``Where the state has a
responsibility to monitor safe products, then secrecy makes no
sense,'' Calderon said.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate hearing in June, Mark Krause, a lobbyist for defense
lawyers, testified that the legislation would generate more
litigation and work against consumers, making automakers less
likely to negotiate. ``By having a gag clause, it sweetens the
pot,'' he said. ``It makes it easier for manufacturers to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rosemary Shahan, president of Consumers for Auto Reliability
and Safety, an advocacy group in Sacramento that asked lawmakers to
introduce the bill, argued that ``gag clauses interfere with
agencies that are supposed to protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the state Senate voted 21-12 to approve the
legislation, adding an amendment that permits secrecy on a
settlement's financial terms. On Tuesday, the state Assembly, which
had endorsed the bill, approved the amendment 42-28.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to the Association for California Tort Reform,
several automakers opposed the legislation. Ray Buttacavoli,
regional manager for General Motors Corp. in Sacramento, said most
lemon-law repurchases were voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we ought to be able to impose conditions on those
buybacks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Gomez, 48, a Moorpark, Calif., avocado grower, felt
vindicated when arbitrators deemed her 1996 Jeep Cherokee a lemon.
In its first year on the road, the car's drive shaft fell out
twice, once when Ms. Gomez's teen-age son was driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we returned the car, the very first thing they did was
shove a gag order in our face,'' Ms. Gomez said. ``It was
intimidation without legal representation; it was a threat to drag
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A Chrysler representative eventually released a check to Ms.
Gomez, but only after she declared her intention to seek the help
of a consumer advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gomez's experience is typical, said Steven Solomon, a
Burlingame, Calif., lawyer who specializes in vehicle fraud. Most
consumers see a gag provision only in the final flurry of paper
signing, not in negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say they hope that California's ban on gag
clauses will be copied in other states. Yet the bill does not
establish a broader precedent that could be used to argue against
gag clauses in other consumer product settlements, said Judge
Thomas J. Whelan, presiding judge of San Diego Superior Court.
``The statute is limited in its application,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
