<P>
   JAMAICA-WHIZKID _ KINGSTON, Jamaica _ He swoons over the Spice
Girls. He mouths off to his mother. He even signs his name with a
smiley face. Yet the dreadlocked Makonnen David Blake is a
13-year-old who holds a powerful position: he's the youngest-ever
adviser to the Jamaican government. The fidgety whiz kid was
recently appointed by the government to advise the Ministry of
Technology on computer technology and new trends in the Internet.
He'll hold the position for at least one year. Thrown out of school
at age 7 for questioning whether Jesus was really white, Blake was
home-schooled in a country where public education is poor. Today,
he reads science textbooks for fun and designs Web sites for his
friends. Wearing Adidas jogging pants and a T-shirt, he has a
direct line to government officials, many of whom just started
using computers over the past year. Government officials say
they're relying on Makonnen to take them into the next century of
computer technology. They say they want to put a computer in every
public school by the year 2000. But many of the 967 schools don't
even have a phone line. Meanwhile, the new government adviser has
an interesting family history. His grandfather, Evan Blake, broke
the color barrier in Jamaica in the 1950s by jumping into a
whites-only swimming pool. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
