<P>
   DDN-COX-BIKER _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Once the No. 2 man in the Outlaws
motorcycle gang, David Spurgeon knows the inside of a jail cell.
But Spurgeon now has a new title: reverand. Spurgeon has a bit of a
footnote in judicial law. When he was sentenced to mandatory five
years in prison on a weapons charge in connection with a drug case
seven years ago, U.S. District Court Judge Walter Rice postponed
imposing the sentence _ indefinitely. The Supreme Court eventually
reversed the case in which Spurgeon was convicted, and now he
counsels inmates as part of a prison ministry program. (Hills,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-HOMICIDE _ Kill someone, that's homicide. Kill someone
without a good reason, and that's murder. It's up to Sgt. Mitch
Woodruff's squad to sort it out, and it's up to Woodruff to answer
the first question, the one that makes homicide detective a wearing
and sometimes revolting job: Who will walk into that stinking,
stifling room to look over the body? ``Murders are solved in 48
hours,'' says Woodruff, whose homicide squad is one of two that
trade shifts in a second-floor bureau of the Palm Beach County
Sheriff's Office. ``After that, the chances go way down.''
(Kalajian.
</P>
<P>
   ROBESON _ ROBESON COUNTY, N.C., has emerged from the governance
of white politicians despite a nearly even split of blacks, whites
and Lumbee Indians. Community leaders point to the re-election of
the first Native American to become sheriff as proof of bonafide
change, and the county school board recently ended a tradition of
rotating its leadership among the races by electing its first woman
_ a white _ instead installing a black. The changes aren't without
growing pains, however. A Superior Court judge recently issued a
gag order in the impending trial of a school superintendent
indicted for embezzlement. The judge is Native American as is the
defendent, raising the question whether political favoritism is at
hand. (Manuel , Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ANTIGAM _ Eupora, Miss._She's from a two-stoplight town west of
Starkville and east of nowhere. She wears demure church dresses,
plays the piano, and works for a state legislator when she's not
taking care of her two children. And this summer, Elizabeth Stoner
has become a household name in Mississippi. She filed an initiative
in June that would put the issue of riverboat casinos to a
statewide vote, giving Mississippians a chance to kick the casinos
out. If they vote to ban gambling, the 30 riverboats docked in
eight counties along the Mississippi River and the Gulf Coast would
have two years to shut down. (Anne Rochell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   with/BINGO _ ROCK HILL, S.C._ The Indian tribe that didn't
really want to open a bingo parlor because of religious beliefs is
now raking in about $2 million a month at the largest bingo
operation on the Eastern Seaboard. Located in a former Sears
Roebuck store on the edge of this college town, Catawba Bingo
offers games every day except Sunday, luring thousands of folks
from all over the Southeast. On Big Games days, twice each month,
the payout is $200,000 with one game worth $50,000. Folks arrive as
early as 10 a.m. for the start of the 1 p.m. games. ``We're doing
quite well,'' said Wanda George Warren, the Catawba Indian Nation's
executive director. (Riddle, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
