<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-CONGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS ON CONGO GET OFF TO A ROUGH START IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa _ A last-ditch effort by South Africa to
negotiate a peace settlement for Congo appeared to get off to a
poor start Saturday, when two of the key players failed to show up
for a scheduled meeting, though one sent a representative.
</P>
<P>
   President Nelson Mandela had called two meetings of African
leaders in Pretoria for this weekend, fearing that the rebellion
and turmoil in the Congo could turn into a regional war. Saturday's
meeting was to gather the leaders of Congo, Rwanda, Uganda and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda's president, Pasteur Bizimungu, and Uganda's president,
Yoweri Museveni, who are widely believed to be supporting the
rebels, arrived in Pretoria as planned.
</P>
<P>
   But the Congo's president, Laurent Kabila, and his ally,
President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, said they were too ill to
attend, South African officials said. Kabila sent his justice
minister as a representative.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela had planned to negotiate a cease-fire in the Congo and
then map out a strategy for a long-term peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sunday, he had hoped to present that plan to all 14
countries that are members of the South African Development
Community, hoping they would support it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absences, South African officials continued to say
they were optimistic about the meetings, which were not expected to
start before mid-afternoon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we will cover a lot of ground today and tomorrow,''
said Parks Mankahlana, Mandela's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Mankahlana said that efforts were still under way to persuade
Mugabe to come to Pretoria. He said Mandela had asked Mozambique's
president, Joaquim Chissano, to see what he could do to get him to
the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe and Mandela, who have clashed in the past over a range of
issues, have been at odds over how to deal with the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has been calling for regional military action to prevent
another upheaval in the former Zaire, whose longstanding dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko fell only 15 months ago. Mugabe is reported to
have already sent troops to help prop up Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   But Mandela, currently the chair of SADC, has urged restraint.
Only last week, Mugabe appeared to rebuke Mandela when he said
Mandela could do as he liked, but he shouldn't tell anyone else in
SADC what to do.
</P>
<P>
   South African officials indicated that Kabila's absence came as
no surprise. He has said that he would be reluctant to take part in
any negotiations until a cease-fire had been agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   South African television broadcast a telephone interview with a
Congolese spokesman, Pierre Victor Mpoyo, who said Kabila would
never negotiate with rebels and did not trust Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Mpoyo said South Africa had sold arms to Rwanda in the past and
was biased in favor of the rebels. Rwanda and Uganda were once
allies of Kabila's, but have since lost patience with him.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is hoping to map out a framework for a new
government for Congo, which would include a power-sharing scheme
that might address some of Uganda's and Rwanda's concerns. Kabila
has been widely criticized for his lack of leadership and
diplomatic skills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1526EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METAL-BATS-ART-(2TAKE     08-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METAL-BATS-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMATEUR BASEBALL CONFRONTS EVER MORE POWERFUL BATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic showing how a fast pitch comes off of a metal bat
is being modified is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
(ak) 
 By ED GUZMAN and KIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In baseball, researchers say that a pitcher standing 60 feet
from home plate needs at least four-tenths of a second to raise his
glove in defense of a hard line drive hit at him.
</P>
<P>
   But on the afternoon of March 23, 1996, Danny Crawford of the
University of Houston was not allowed even that narrow margin. A
Texas A&AMP;M batter hit Crawford with a ball that screamed back in
only 0.29 seconds. Five of his teeth were shattered. Sixty-two
stitches were needed to mend his face.
</P>
<P>
   The bat used that day was an aluminum alloy, space-age
technology that has come to dominate and alter the nature of
amateur baseball in the United States by being simply too good.
</P>
<P>
   The bats are far lighter to swing than wood and the ball flies
off faster. Earlier this month, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association said the newest generation of these bats had become
dangerous to players and harmful to the game because so many
hitting records are being broken.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA ordered bat manufacturers to modify their designs to
meet a new lower-performance standard: bats that are heavier, with
a smaller barrel. The group that regulates high school sports said
it was considering a similar move.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule change, which will take effect next August, has
also brought to the surface an issue that has been churning
bitterly for years within the NCAA and the sports equipment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although injuries like Crawford's are still the exception rather
than the rule, officials of the NCAA expressed safety concerns
about the nonwooden bats as early as 1985, and twice, in 1988 and
1995, issued industry guidelines and tests to try to put limits on
bat performance, according to NCAA documents.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelming those worries, however, were entrenched forces as
old as sports and capitalism: players and teams who were competing
for victories wanted the hitting power afforded by more advanced
alloy bats. Companies, competing with one another for sales, wanted
to supply what the market demanded. A former bat designer who
voiced fears about bat safety with his employer said he was ignored
as the business boomed.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an arms race, with the NCAA, because of its own
flawed science and limited efforts at oversight, ultimately
rendered not much more than a bystander. No team or player or
company wanted to give up any possible advantage, and no one wanted
to be the first to apply the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Even as officials within the NCAA and within the industry began
to worry, bats evolved to include things that would have made Babe
Ruth's eyes glaze over: hollow air chambers, cryogenic freezing
techniques and rare metal compounds like scandium, which is mined
only in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Prices soared to $300 a bat. Three companies came to dominate
sales: Easton Sports of Van Nuys, Calif., Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby Co.,
and Worth Inc. of Tullahoma, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is free enterprise and the consumer tells you what he
wants,'' said Bill Williams, the vice president of Hillerich &AMP;
Bradsby, based in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum bats started out as substitutes, not stars. Their
appeal when they were introduced in the mid-1970s was their lower
cost and greater durability. They were cheaper than the white ash
for wood bats, and for amateur teams and recreational players, that
filled a need.
</P>
<P>
   But as their appeal grew _ aluminum now accounts for roughly 90
percent of the $115 million bat market, according to the Sporting
Goods Manufacturing Association _ performance began to improve as
well. Major League and Minor League baseball are about the last
leagues left, industry officials say, that allow only wood bats.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, NCAA officials, meeting with manufacturers, made the
first attempt to set limits on the technology. The NCAA ruled then
that Easton's B-9 Black Magic aluminum bat _ then the
highest-performance end of the alloy spectrum _ would be the
benchmark. Future bat models would have to fall within or below the
performance range of the B-9.
</P>
<P>
   But the race to build a better bat continued and batting records
toppled. In 1995, bat manufacturers introduced bats made with yet
another new aluminum alloy, called C405. Strong sales of the new
bats, coupled with a record number of home runs in the 1995 College
World Series, prompted the NCAA to demand yet another meeting with
the bat companies.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings led to the adoption of the so-called bat
performance factor test, aimed at limiting bats to 1994 performance
levels. Created by Richard Brandt, a physics professor at New York
University, the test consisted of firing pitches at 60 mph at a
stationary bat, and concluded that the newer models were not
dramatically more powerful than their predecessors, and not all
that much better than wood.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the legitimacy of the Brandt test began to
accumulate, though, and with them more worries about safety and the
integrity of the game. In a letter last year to Bill Rowe, the
chairman of the NCAA baseball rules committee, Brandt conceded that
his test was more accurate at the lower ball speeds of softball
than at collegiate-level baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the NCAA said they trusted bat manufacturers to
abide by the rules and trusted the standards and tests that
measured bat performance. Now there is a quiet rumbling within
collegiate baseball _ from coaches and officials speaking on
condition of anonymity _ that they feel the rules were bent. On the
record, NCAA spokesmen say simply that neither the NCAA nor the
manufacturers had enough information about what the new
technologies could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we knew then what we know now, we would not have moved
ahead,'' said Ted Breidenthal, staff liaison to the baseball rules
committee at the NCAA, referring to the now discredited tests
adopted by the NCAA in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Sports Equipment Manufacturers Association, a
trade group, said they believed that alloy bats are safe and that
other changes in the game _ a spongier ball and more powerful,
better-conditioned athletes _ helped explain harder-hit balls and
scoring records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA's own statistics show that baseball is the safest
sport they have,'' said John Riddle, the group's president. ``I
don't think there is a legitimate safety concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers say that the rules, necessary or not, will result
in warehouses full of unsellable bats. Easton, the largest
manufacturer of nonwooden bats, filed a federal lawsuit against the
NCAA even before the rules were voted on, saying that the
organization, which had planned to implement the new rules next
January, was acting precipitously and restraining trade.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA admits that it cannot directly blame alloy bats for
specific injuries because with all the variables involved in a
pitch and a swing, the ball's speed off the bat is only part of the
story. Higher scoring records, however, and studies testing human
reaction time, NCAA officials said, all point to the need for new
limits.
</P>
<P>
   The new specifications require, in particular, that the exit
velocity of a ball leaving a bat be reduced by more than 10
percent, to a maximum of only 93 mph _ comparable to a wood bat _
from the now-common speeds of more than 104 mph. To reach that
threshold, the maximum diameter of the barrel of aluminum bats must
be reduced by one-eighth of an inch and the weight increased.
</P>
<P>
   One bat design expert, Jack MacKay, said the changes were long
overdue. MacKay said he had raised safety concerns to his employer,
Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby, in company memos as far back as 1994 as the
bat wars raged on.
</P>
<P>
   He said flatly in an interview that the NCAA was duped by
companies that knew their bats were more powerful than the tests
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who resigned last year when he said he was being
ignored, is being sued by his former employer for misappropriation
of proprietary information and breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA did nothing wrong except trust the wrong people,''
MacKay said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the vice president at Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby, said he was
never made aware of MacKay's concerns, and that the company did
nothing improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware that if we produced anything illegal, it would
not be good for two reasons,'' he said. ``No. 1, it would produce
liability. No. 2, we'd get caught and pay the price. Why would we
hang ourselves like that?''
</P>
<P>
   The debate continues on whether high-performance bats are
hurting the integrity of the game. In NCAA Division I competition,
teams hit an average of 1.06 home runs a game last season, up from
0.70 in 1995. This year's College World Series championship between
the University of Southern California and Arizona State yielded a
21-14 game, a record for runs scored. The record for home runs in a
College World Series was broken in 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against aluminum mainly because I think it's hurting
baseball,'' said Bob Seddon, the baseball coach at the University
of Pennsylvania. ``It's gotten ridiculous. I was at the College
World Series this year and I got up and left. I mean, what is
this?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all coaches share that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is in good balance and the competition level is
fine,'' said Skip Bertman, head coach at Louisiana State
University, which has won four national titles in the last seven
years. ``The game is more popular today than at any point in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   And some scientists say they think the NCAA has perhaps still
not found a reliable solution to its bat problems. One scientist,
Trey Crisco, the director of Rhode Island Hospital's bioengineering
laboratory, who has been commissioned by the NCAA and the National
Federation of State High School Associations to test bats, said
that because the bat makers, most of them privately owned
companies, are so reluctant to share information about their own
tests or specifications, he thinks the NCAA was forced to form its
new policy without enough information.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you set a philosophy, you have to base it on science, not
on emotion,'' Crisco said.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers and distributors who sell sporting goods also say they
expect the pressures to produce a top-selling bat will simply mean
new technological innovations to fit the new standard.
</P>
<P>
   Worth makes a bat, for example, that includes what it calls an
``electronic vibration control module,'' intended to reduce the
so-called ``bee-sting'' on a batter's hands when a ball strikes the
bat and allow a more solid follow-through of the swing.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Rawlings, has also recently introduced a bat
that features a bigger barrel and a skinny handle that allows a
greater flex and snap of the bat, and thus more power. A spokesman
for Rawlings said the company planned to have a modified version of
that bat _ conforming to the new NCAA standards _ on the market by
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of possibilities,'' said Jeff Burton, director
of sales at Baseball Express, a San Antonio sports equipment
distributor. ``It will be interesting to see where this leads bat
manufacturing in the future.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
