<HEADLINE>
GROUP CLAIMS TOLL IN ATTACKS WAS HIGHER THAN FIRST THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ak) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ The number of people killed by American
missiles fired into eastern Afghanistan appears to be higher than
first thought, with one estimate putting the death toll at 50 or
higher.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here Saturday, the leader of one of the
groups apparently targeted in the attack said ``about 50 of our
people were killed and there is still more counting to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader, Fazal ur-Rehman Khalil, said he is the central emir
of the Harkat-ul-Mujahedeen, one of three militant Islamic groups
that appears to have been targeted.
</P>
<P>
   The official radio of the Taliban, the militant Islamic group
that controls most of Afghanistan, said 21 people died in the
attacks, although it was not clear if that total covered more than
one camp. The United States says it does not yet have an accurate
assessment of the number of people who were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Two other encampments that were hit belonged to the
Jamiat-ul-Mujahedeen and the Harkat-ul-Jihad al-Islami.
</P>
<P>
   The latter encampment was said to be the home base for Osama bin
Laden, the Saudi businessman U.S. officials say was behind the
bombings of the American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the Pakistani press said bin Laden's camp had been
leveled, though, because of either a fortuitous change in dinner
plans or the use of extra caution, he was not present when the
missiles struck.
</P>
<P>
   There was little information about casualties among bin Laden's
followers. The dead and wounded would likely have been taken to
Taliban-run hospitals in Kabul, 90 miles away, or to nearby Khost.
</P>
<P>
   A Pakistani newspaper reported Saturday that bin Laden had
issued a threatening response to the attack that was conveyed by
one of his close associates. The associate, Ayman al-Zawahri,
phoned a Pakistani reporter and said: ``The war has just started.
The Americans should wait for the answer!''
</P>
<P>
   The other two groups hit by the missiles were primarily
Pakistani, and, according to reports here attributed to government
officials, both were active in sending Islamic militants into the
Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil denied any involvement in terrorism.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are ready to provide all details about the victims, and if
anyone can prove they were terrorists, we will withdraw our
objections and support the American attack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his camp and others go back to the war fought in the
1980s against Soviet troops in Afghanistan and the Afghan
government they backed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans themselves built the camps for the purpose of war,
and now we use the buildings as education and welfare centers,''
Khalil said.
</P>
<P>
   Many wounded Pakistanis were being treated at hospitals in their
own country. The dead were taken to their home towns. Survivors
told of their horror as the missiles rained from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were blasts as the bombs fell to the ground,'' said
Mohammed Arsalan, 20, a member of the Harkat-ul-Mujahedeen. ``We
ran to save ourselves, trying to hide in mountains and caves.''
</P>
<P>
   At a religious school of the Harkat-ul-Mujahedeen in the old
city of Rawalpindi, the mood was mournful and deeply anti-American.
Arsalan's elders stopped him from providing a more detailed account
of the missile barrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have nothing to do with humanity,'' one of the
elders said, shooing Arsalan away. ``The American people have
awakened the Islamic world from slumber because America has
attacked Islam and Islam will have its revenge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
