<HEADER>
A7313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-DONATIONS     08-22 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CAMPAIGN-DONATIONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES BANKROLL DEMOCRATIC ORGANIZATIONS, RIVALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic chieftains in the Buffalo, N.Y., area have a new
patron this year, a well-to-do Manhattan resident named Eliot
Spitzer who has ladled more than $50,000 of his personal wealth
into the local party machine, paying for rent and salaries and
assorted political sundries.
</P>
<P>
   While such largess from an outsider might seem odd, Spitzer is
getting something as well: grass-roots support in his bid for the
Democratic nomination for attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer is a former state prosecutor and real estate heir who
has spent more than $2.5 million of his fortune on his campaign,
and plans to lay out another $1 million before the primary on Sept.
15. But not all of that money has gone to finance cannonades of
television commercials. Spitzer, who has never held elective
office, has also quietly sought to bolster his candidacy by giving
heavily to Democratic organizations and candidates across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   His donations have helped garner him the kind of fealty from
party cadres that more seasoned politicians secure by rising
through the ranks. Often, he has opened his checkbook in the weeks
after local leaders agreed to back him.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the only one to adopt such tactics. Lt. Gov. Betsy
McCaughey Ross, who is seeking the Democratic gubernatorial
nomination and similarly lacks roots in the party, has also done
so. Her campaign and her husband gave a total of $87,000 to the
Democrats in Nassau County in June, less than two months after the
county leader switched his support to Ms. McCaughey Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Their rivals call this spending a cynical and possibly illegal
scheme to buy allegiance, but Spitzer and Ms. McCaughey Ross
strongly deny that they donated in exchange for support.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the arguments about potential improprieties, such
giving demonstrates how affluent candidates benefit from their
bankrolls. They are not only freed from time-consuming fund-raising
and able to spend handsomely on advertising, but can also court
local party organizations that are forever seeking money.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the loyalty of these committees and clubs could be
significant in the primary next month, when turnout will probably
be low, handing an edge to those candidates who can get their
partisans to the polls. Buffalo and surrounding Erie County, as
well as Nassau County, are important battlegrounds in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross, a former Republican who abandoned her party
last year to try to oust her former running mate, Gov. George
Pataki, is using money from her husband, Wilbur Ross Jr., for her
campaign. He has filled her bank account with more than $3 million,
though questions remain about how much of that he will allow to be
spent. Only one of her three rivals, Peter Vallone, the City
Council speaker, has a similar amount on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's money comes from his father, Bernard, a real estate
magnate in New York City. He has raised and spent far more than the
three other contenders _ State Sen. Catherine Abate, Evan Davis, a
counsel to former Gov. Mario Cuomo, and G. Oliver Koppell, who was
attorney general in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Spitzer, his parents and his campaign have made well
over 100 payments in the last two years to Democratic groups and
candidates, according to disclosure records, interviews and a
summary that Spitzer was asked to provide. They range from $25 to
$20,000 and are expected to total more than $300,000 by primary
day.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer adopted the Democratic organization in Brooklyn earlier
this year soon after it lined up behind his candidacy, and he plans
to funnel it more than $60,000. The organization in Nassau has
received more than $15,000 from Spitzer and his father, most of it
around the time that it decided to back him. And Spitzer gave
$15,000 to the Democratic organization in the Rochester area in
January, just as its leader supported him, records show.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her support for the Nassau organization, Ms.
McCaughey Ross has also channeled several thousand dollars to the
one in the Buffalo area.
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews, Spitzer and Ms. McCaughey Ross defended
their donations, saying they were intended to bolster local
Democratic apparatuses that have withered since Pataki won in 1994.
Both said some of the money was being used for get-out-the-vote
drives and other efforts that would assist their candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said that after he came in fourth in the primary for
attorney general in 1994, he realized that his campaign had
suffered because he had neglected local Democratic groups, so he
embarked on a strenuous effort to travel around the state and make
his face and platform known.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he attended the typical regimen of fund-raisers and
party dinners, where he gave money, he said. He noted that in
several instances, he had given large contributions _ $5,000, for
example, to the organization in Schenectady County _ to groups that
were not supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contributing money is not a way of generating support or
endearing myself,'' he said. ``I will walk away from anybody who
says a contribution will help get support. I have a very strong
sense of what is ethically correct. I am of the view that after
somebody has supported me, if we are working together, and I am
trying to build a field organization, then I will build that
organization. But I will never contribute money in return for
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross said there was nothing unusual about the
donations her campaign and her husband made to the Nassau
Democrats. ``Virtually every statewide candidate has made
contributions to county committees,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Told that her three opponents had not given contributions
anywhere near in size to the Nassau ones, she said she and her
husband were doing their part for the Democrats. ``Wilbur and I are
committed to helping rebuild the Democratic Party in New York
state,'' she said. ``It has no money and it has lacked the kind of
leadership that will make it a financially strong party.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have come under intense attacks over their
finances. In the attorney general race, Davis angrily withdrew from
the Democratic State Convention in May after contending that
Spitzer's money was turning the process into a sham. Koppell has
filed a lawsuit against Spitzer, asserting that he has violated
state law by receiving financial assistance from his father that is
greater than the legal limit. Spitzer called Koppell's charges
``completely meritless.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abate said she was considering filing a complaint with the
state Board of Elections that would contend, among other things,
that Spitzer should not be allowed to donate money to local
Democratic groups from his personal funds, as he has done, because
such giving is essentially a campaign expenditure that should come
from his campaign. She noted that donations from his personal funds
are much harder to track, because he does not have to detail them
in disclosure forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unseemly to give money at the same time that you are
asking for support,'' Ms. Abate said. ``I believe that credible
candidates who have a record built on the experience of serving the
people shouldn't have to resort to giving money away in the fashion
that he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abate's aides have also maintained that under state law,
county political committees are not allowed to help candidates in
primaries, questioning whether Spitzer's donations are being used
specifically for that purpose. It often appears, though, that the
county leaders who are backing Spitzer are using other groups,
rather than the formal county committees themselves, to handle his
donations.
</P>
<P>
   In the gubernatorial primary, one of the contenders, James
Larocca, has filed a complaint with the Board of Elections over the
payments to the Nassau County organizations by the McCaughey Ross
campaign and Ross. The Nassau leader, Stephen Sabbeth, had been
supporting Larocca, a former state transportation commissioner,
until he shifted to Ms. McCaughey Ross shortly before the state
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this is a direct violation of the law, and
certainly the spirit of the law, which is that our elections should
not be for sale,'' Larocca said. Larocca quoted Sabbeth as telling
him that the switch stemmed from ```one thing, and one thing only:
money.
</P>
<P>
   ```She has it, and you don't.'''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Sabbeth, who is also allied with Spitzer, said
neither candidate gave donations in return for support.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Larocca's recollection of their conversation,
Sabbeth said: ``It wasn't a quid pro quo. If someone has the
ability after the fact to help us, they are really helping
themselves. That is a responsibility that candidates should have,
if only for the fact that we have an organization in November to
pull out the vote for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader in the Buffalo area, G. Steven Pigeon, said he liked
Spitzer in part because the candidate was committed to having a
strong field operation in place for the primary and general
election. Pigeon said the donations were not a decisive factor in
winning support, but he acknowledged that Spitzer's candidacy was
attractive because he has enough money to take on the Republicans,
who have been far more successful at fund-raising than the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to apologize that we have a candidate who can
compete with them,'' Pigeon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
