<SLUG> BC-NY-CLOTHING-TAX-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 ANOTHER WEEK WITHOUT TAX ON CLOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pressing a political point and catering to
back-to-school shoppers, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced Saturday
that most clothing or shoes sold in New York City would be free of
sales tax during the first week of September.
</P>
<P>
   The tax, including the state and city levies, totals 8\ percent,
so the weeklong break will mean a savings of $7.42 on a $90 pair of
Nike Air Max running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth such week in the city in two years, as the
mayor continues to push state legislators to do away with the tax.
In the session that ended in June, the state Legislature went part
way, eliminating the tax on clothes and shoes that sell for less
than $110, beginning Dec. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The week to splurge will be Sept. 1 to 7, when the city's
exemption will cover goods costing less than $500 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best job-creation program that New York has come
up with in probably 50 years,'' Giuliani said. ``The purpose of
encouraging people to shop for clothes during the tax-free week is
to create an example, really, of what can happen if you eliminate
the sales tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani praised legislators for meeting him part way, but urged
them to go further. ``When we started three years ago, the cynics
said this couldn't be done in Albany, and we fought and we
scratched and we pushed very hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers said their sales had tripled during past tax-free
weeks. City officials contend that they more than make up for the
tax money they lose, since more people are hired and shoppers stay
in the city instead of heading for the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   A leading retail analyst, Kurt Barnard, cautioned that part of
the sales increase during tax-free weeks consists of sales that
would have occurred anyway, but are shifted to the taxless periods
because people time their purchases to save money.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report, based
in Upper Montclair, N.J., said tax-free weeks clearly increased
sales over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings sales to the city of New York that normally would go
to other areas, and makes it possible for a lot of people on tight
budgets to buy a few more things,'' he said. ``You go in to buy a
suit, and maybe you pick up a tie.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mayor made the announcement at Moe Ginsburg Men's Better
Clothing, on Fifth Avenue, where he tried on a double-breasted
Italian suit for the benefit of 10 television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's exactly a suit I could get away with,''
Giuliani said, patting his midriff. Surprise: The suit, carefully
chosen by store executives and the mayor's aides, fit flatteringly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty nice, huh?'' the mayor said. ``I don't think
I've ever had a suit like this.'' Then he touched the breast pocket
of the $680 suit and said, ``Could you put a little `N.Y.' here, or
something?''
</P>
<P>
   The city, which is promoting the tax break with posters showing
a shiny apple and other classroom cliches, has produced a long list
of items that are eligible for the tax break, and those that are
not.
</P>
<P>
   The exempt items include aerobic clothing, bathing caps, corset
laces, lab coats, riding pants, shoelaces, socks, tights, tuxedos
(unless rented) and underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Taxable items include bobby pins, goggles (unless prescription),
helmets, ice skates, party costumes, roller skates, shin guards,
sunglasses, wallets and wigs.
</P>
<P>
   The store the mayor visited, Moe Ginsburg, has been among the
most aggressive promoters of the city's tax-free weeks, and got a
jump on this fall's campaign by declaring all of August tax free,
with the tax coming out of the store's profit.
</P>
<P>
   The store's president, Paul Ginsburg, said his sales tripled or
quadrupled during past tax-free weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And Arifur Khan, 24, manager of Wheels of London, a shoe store
in Greenwich Village, said his sales increased 10 percent to 20
percent during tax-free weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids browse before tax-free week,'' he said, then come back
and buy.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, several shoppers said they would put off purchases
to take advantage of the tax-free week.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Samuels, 38, who was stocking up on bras for her daughter
at Conway, on 34th Street, said, ``If you really know how to shop,
you don't have to wait around for a no-sales-tax week.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said she would wait until the first week of September
for more expensive items, including gym shoes and blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Fanuele, who lives in Greenwich Village and was on her way
out of Gap Kids on Sixth Avenue, said that she would wait to
stretch the $200 she planned to spend on her 7-year-old daughter,
Angeline.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fanuele said she would love to see the sales tax eliminated,
``but I'll take what we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Gleckman, 46, who has a daughter, Mimi, headed for
nursery school, was suspicious. ``Are they going to mark up the
price?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   During the city's tax-free week last September, shoes were not
covered, which the mayor said ``created mass confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's sales tax includes 4 percent for the city, 4 percent
for the state and one-quarter percent for the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   According to estimates by the city's Economic Development
Corporation, the plan passed by the Legislature will mean an
increase of 13,200 retail jobs, while total elimination of the tax
on clothing and shoes would produce 19,600 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales are often perceived as just marketing, but this is a
genuine discount off the price, and consumers realize that,'' said
Charles Millard, president of the economic development agency.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said eliminating the tax was ``the best way to create
jobs _ not for government to subsidize jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   As the mayor headed out of the fifth floor (``Contemporary
European Collections'') of Moe Ginsburg's on Saturday, he handed
the suit to Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on to this,'' Giuliani instructed. ``I'll come back at a
quieter time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
