<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-VIGIL-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH, NORTH AND SOUTH, MARK WEEK SINCE TERROR BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ Tens of thousands of people in
Northern Ireland and in the Irish Republic observed a painful
minute of silence at 3:10 Saturday afternoon, the exact time a week
ago that a terrorist bomb killed 28 people in the center of this
small market town.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb, which left 220 injured, 75 of whom are still
hospitalized, was the deadliest terrorist atrocity in 19 years of
sectarian violence in this mostly Protestant British province.
</P>
<P>
   A Catholic splinter guerrilla group, the Real IRA, which wants
the Republic to take over the North, claimed responsibility for the
attack. The police are questioning two men, but no one has been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted a united Ireland,'' said Amanda Heffernan, a
clerk. ``Now we're united in grief.''
</P>
<P>
   The blast was commemorated in public assemblies in dozens of
cities and towns here and in the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish
Republic. Irish President Mary McAleese spoke briefly. Her father's
pub near the border with the Irish Republic was blown up by
Protestant terrorists 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, who has advanced harsh legal
measures to combat terrorism, attended the ceremony at the
courthouse in Omagh, a few hundred yards from where the bomb went
off. Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott represented the British
government.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA, which split from the Irish Republican Army this
year, announced a cease-fire last week. And Saturday, another
Republican splinter group, the Irish National Liberation Army,
followed suit, a development officials say should enhance the peace
agreement approved in referendums here and in the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern called the latest cease-fire pledge ``good news at the end
of a bleak and tragic week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish National Liberation Army's last admitted violent act
was on June 25 when a car bomb destroyed part of the border town of
Newtownhamilton, wounding 11 people.
</P>
<P>
   The statement _ announced at the west Belfast headquarters of
the group's political representatives, the Irish Republican
Socialist Party _ means that only one anti-British organization in
Northern Ireland, the Continuity IRA, has yet to call a truce. All
major Protestant paramilitary groups have already called
cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that the political situation has changed since
the formation of INLA,'' the statement said. ``We recognize that
armed struggle can never be the only option for revolutionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the people of the whole island of Ireland ``have
spoken clearly as to their wishes,'' it acknowledged ``faults and
grievous errors in our prosecution of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Innocent people were killed and injured and at times our
actions as a liberation army fell far short of what they should
have been,'' it said. ``For this we as republicans, as socialists
and as revolutionaries offer a sincere and heartfelt apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday in Omagh, a mostly Catholic city of 20,000 set in the
cow-studded hills of bucolic central Ulster, the people in the town
center and in nearby parking lots with loudspeakers listened to the
prayers of Protestant and Catholic clergymen. Many wept and many
more seemed to be fighting back tears.
</P>
<P>
   A few directed some of their anger at the Real IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Cunliffe, 68, a retired truck driver and a native
Englishman, said: ``It is disgusting to see what one human being
can do to another. If it was mad dogs, you would put them down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the minute of silence began, Kathleen Heffernan picked up
her granddaughter, Tara, 4, hugging and nuzzling her. Half of the
dead in the blast were children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Heffernan talked about her niece, Stephanie Colton, 16, who
was seriously wounded in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a piece of the car, the car-bomb car, stuck on her
chest,'' she said. ``She nearly lost a foot. On Tuesday they are
going to try to take the stones out from around her eyes, the
gravel that the bomb blew at her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Heffernan said her niece recalled that, seconds before the
blast, as police officers alerted to a bomb mistakenly led crowds
toward the explosion, not away from it, an older woman had turned
to her and her friends and said, ``This is the real thing, this
time, girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls began to laugh at the woman,'' Ms. Heffernan said.
``Then the blast hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   All around her, people were teary-eyed and spoke in low voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this means the end of the war,'' said Joseph Harley,
owner of a construction equipment company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said his wife, Veronica. ``But too late for Omagh.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
