<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BIKER-MOVIESTAR-AR     08-22 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BIKER-MOVIESTAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIKER-BODYGUARD AIMS TO BE A MOVIE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo of Chuck Zito is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ In his 45 years, Chuck Zito has been many
things: outlaw biker, convict, bodyguard to the stars and stunt
man.
</P>
<P>
   Now Zito, president of the New York Nomads chapter of the Hell's
Angels motorcycle club, is trying to engineer a leap from macho man
to movie star.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a bodyguard, I met the celebrities and progressed from
there into stunt work,'' he said. ``Now I'm ready to progress into
bigger and better parts. I'm just waiting for that leading role, to
become the next Rocky or Rambo.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito had his first taste of the movies in 1979, when he appeared
on screen with his custom-painted Harley-Davidson. The following
year, he used his Hollywood connections to start a bodyguard
service that attracted celebrity clients like Sylvester Stallone,
Mickey Rourke and Sean Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has worked on more than 50 films, mostly as a
stunt man. But last winter, Zito won his best role yet, a part in
``Oz,'' a prison drama series on HBO in which he plays Chuckie
Pancamo, the enforcer for a group of Italian inmates.
</P>
<P>
   His desire to act, he said, arose in part from the frustration
of watching movie stars do imitations of the man he is in daily
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch a lot of these actors and say to myself, `I could do
it better,''' he said. ``They're trying to look like what I really
am, but they're not living it day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 to 1991, Zito was in prison serving a sentence for
drug conspiracy, an experience that informs his work on ``Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings so much authority and credibility to the role,''
said Tom Fontana, the show's executive producer. ``But I really
think that comes from his whole life as opposed to just his time in
prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to people like Fontana, Zito's life, which once revolved
around parole boards, motorcycles and trips to the gym, has
broadened to include screen tests and casting calls. He is also
trying to sell a movie treatment he has written, titled ``The
American Way,'' which documents his progress from the Hell's Angels
to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hollywood, of all things, that first drew him to the
motorcycle club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch their movies like `Hell's Angels On Wheels'
and `Hell's Angels '69' as a kid,'' he said. ``They were the elite
of the elite, the No. 1. They were the ones who actually inspired
me to ride a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   In his early 20s, Zito bought a 1969 Harley-Davidson Sportster,
which he rode to boxing practice at the former Gramercy Gym on East
14th Street in New York. It was there, he said, that he met Sandy
Alexander, a professional boxer, who was president of the Hell's
Angels' New York City chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I introduced myself and told him I'd built and hand-painted my
own bike,'' he said. ``Soon enough, I was painting all the Angels'
bikes. And after doing the `hang-around' process for a while, they
took a vote, and I was in.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the city chapter, which has a clubhouse in the East
Village, Zito's Nomads group roams the open highway from Syracuse
to the northern border of the five boroughs. While he refused to
disclose the number of members in the group (``That's for the cops
to figure out,'' he says), he said he has led the chapter almost
from the day he helped found it in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Though he became a Hell's Angel nearly 20 years ago, boxed as an
amateur for several years and caused a stir in February by knocking
out Jean-Claude Van Damme, the martial artist turned movie star, in
a fracas in the East Side strip club Scores, Zito has a remarkably
strong domestic side. Although he is divorced, he said he sees his
former wife, Kathy, frequently as well as his daughter, Lisa, a
Manhattan entertainment lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his family and the movies, his true love is his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a movie, get the money, and put it right into my house,''
he said. In the last six years, he has stripped the house in New
Rochelle of wooden shingles, re-faced it with brick and stone, and
wants to install a swimming pool and a miniature waterfall in the
back yard. The only thing that stops him now is money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to myself, with the people I know, the people I've
bodyguarded for, I should be retired today,'' he said. ``Done.
Rich. Over with. But I've never taken anything from anybody. So I
just plug along.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a lunch of tuna salad and potato chips, he spoke about
turning 50 in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started late in the acting business,'' he said. ``The
Leonardo DiCaprios and Brad Pitts, they're young guys. That's why I
always say I've got to make it now, because I'm not getting any
younger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
