<SLUG> BC-GLF-GARY-PLAYER(450&AMP;ADD)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 62, GARY PLAYER IS STILL GOING STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ak) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, N.Y. _ Approaching his 63rd birthday, Gary Player is
one of the best-conditioned athletes in the world, and no doubt one
of the the most-traveled ones, too. But Player, in his 45th year as
a professional golfer, shows no signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be still playing at 70,'' Player said here Friday
after shooting a 4-under-par 68 to tie for second place in the
Northville Long Island Classic Senior PGA tournament. ``And I see
no reason why I shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the first golfer to practice physical fitness vigorously
on a regular basis, Player still works out daily, either at home in
South Africa, in a hotel room or in the physical fitness van that
accompanies golfers on the Senior PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure because of that regimen, which mainly includes
calisthenics and lifting weights, Player looks, and apparently is,
as fit and trim at 62 as he was in his prime. That's saying
something, because he won 21 titles on the PGA Tour and became the
third of only four golfers to win all four Grand Slam tournaments
(the others are Gene Sarazen, Ben Hogan and Jack Nicklaus). He has
won 18 times on the Senior Tour for players 50 and over, and three
senior events overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For a while last year, though, it looked as if time might
finally have caught up with Player. He had not won on the PGA
Senior Tour since 1995, and after missing two months of play early
last year following surgery for a double hernia, Player managed
only one top-10 finish in the 22 tournaments in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But in 12 tournaments this year, he has rebounded with three
finishes in the top 10. And his 68 on Friday at the Meadow Brook
Club here, which tied him with Lee Trevino and four others, three
strokes behind Walter Hall, put him in contention to win the
54-hole tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Player still finds victory exulting, even after winning 162
tournaments worldwide, including three Masters, three British
Opens, two P.G.A. Championships and one U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won the British Senior Open last year, it was one of
the most cherished moments of my career,'' he said, ``because to
win a major at 62 is very special.''
</P>
<P>
   A devoted family man with six children and six grandchildren,
with four more expected by Christmas, Player concedes that all of
the travel is one of the drawbacks of a charmed existence. ``It's
lonely being away from my family,'' said Player, who, while still
playing a relatively full golf schedule, designs golf courses, owns
a stable of race horses and operates a ranch in his native South
Africa. ``But I love golf _ although I love ranching as much _ and
want to continue playing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Player estimates that he travels about 300,000 miles a year _
``about as much as I did when I played the regular tour, because of
my golf-course design and playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Candor has always been as much a part of Player's makeup as the
black outfits he used to wear on the golf course. And that has not
changed. He once said golfers were the world's worst-conditioned
athletes and that he, himself, had to look to other athletic
pursuits, such as tennis, for aerobic activity. On Friday, he was
critical of some of the new courses that pros find themselves
playing on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the modern-day courses are terrible,'' he said. ``They
put in deep bunkers in front of the greens, which, in many cases,
are too severe and undulating. They seem to forget that golf
courses should be built for the members, not for the professionals.
That's why I love an old course like the one we're playing on here,
where you can run the ball up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
