<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-TECH-SEATS-KAN &LR;      08-22 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-SEATS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY BRINGS COMPUTERS TO FANS AT THE BALLPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ The roaring crowd confirms the pickoff move at
second base was close. Too bad you missed it because the fan in
front of you was getting up.
</P>
<P>
   Tap on the computer screen and _ problem solved _ you get a
replay from any camera angle in the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   After booing the umpire, you can tap in a food order, check the
progress of other games in the league, see whether Mark McGwire has
homered again, even find out that the other team's shortstop is
hitting below .200, the infamous Mendoza line.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't the Internet. It's not virtual baseball either.
It's called ChoiceSeat.
</P>
<P>
   There are 100 ChoiceSeats in Tropicana Field, the home of the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays, where the Royals opened a three-game series
Friday night. Each seat has a computer screen attached to the arm
rest. Fans can tap different points on the screen to use any of the
features ChoiceSeat offers.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm Stadium, where the National League's San Diego Padres
play, has 400 ChoiceSeats that were installed for Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa-based Williams Cos. Inc. tested its ChoiceSeats in the two
stadiums. Barry Goldberg, who is general manager with Williams'
ChoiceSeat business unit, said fans can expect to see ChoiceSeats
in three or four more baseball stadiums next season, and all
ballparks eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to see them at Kauffman Stadium soon.
</P>
<P>
   Art Chaudry, senior vice president of operations for the Kansas
City Royals, said the idea sounds fascinating, but the Royals
aren't shopping yet. He said ``necessities,'' such as new seats
with cupholders, are on the priority list for Kauffman Stadium, not
``luxuries'' like computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning how to crawl before we run,'' Chaudry said of
the Royals' stadium upgrade plans.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, some fans wonder whether the ChoiceSeat features would
be worth the extra price. Nor are they sure who'd want to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Oppitz and David Sexton sat only a few seats from each
other at last Sunday's game between the Royals and Devil Rays at
Kauffman Stadium. But they were on opposite sides of the
fan-interest issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton said he thought casual baseball fans would be wooed by a
ChoiceSeat screen. True fans wouldn't want the distraction, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you mess around with the computer a lot, you're going to
miss the game,'' said Sexton, a Parkville, Mo., resident who splits
season tickets with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Oppitz from Overland Park, Kan. She said the
die-hard baseball fan would love to pore over statistics, see
replays from several camera angles and such. It's a great idea but
it's not for the sometimes fan, she said.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed, however, about how often they'd be willing to pay
extra for a ChoiceSeat _ occasionally. Sexton said he wouldn't want
the added cost for his season tickets, and Oppitz said she'd only
want to pay extra for a ChoiceSeat a few times to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   That's not really a choice for season ticket holders because the
ChoiceSeat addition is stationary. Fans gain access to the machine
for the price of their game ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And it's difficult to say how much more that ChoiceSeat ticket
would cost.
</P>
<P>
   At Tropicana Field, a seat with the ChoiceSeat screens costs
$195 _ per game. But that's not because they're ChoiceSeats, said
John Higgins, senior vice president with the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   The team installed its 100 ChoiceSeat screens in a section
directly behind home plate. Fans in these seats are closer to home
plate than the pitcher is. Waiters jot down their orders and
deliver the food and beverages. These would be choice seats even
without the ChoiceSeats.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said Williams Cos. isn't aiming for that small,
expensive section of seats. Tropicana Field's exclusive section was
just a test area; Williams Cos. wants to see ChoiceSeats spread
much more broadly in a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't go into Kansas City, for example, and want those
seats to be $200 seats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg wants ChoiceSeats in typical seats, say, $15 seats. The
added cost might push the ticket to $20 or $22.50, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If it were up to Goldberg, fans might not have to pay extra for
the fancy computer features. They could sneak down to an empty
ChoiceSeat during the game.
</P>
<P>
   That's not possible at Tropicana Field, Higgins said. Ushers
limit access to the high-price section where the ChoiceSeats were
installed. But access would be limited to ticket holders even
without the computers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in how widely ChoiceSeats spread is their cost to
install, run and maintain. Goldberg said the only maintenance
problem Williams Cos. has encountered is with the screen surface.
It scratches too easily. But, he said, this can be fixed by using a
different screen in future models.
</P>
<P>
   Football fans, however, may not see ChoiceSeats at all. Goldberg
said at current costs for the computer screens and data, stadiums
couldn't charge enough for the few football games to make
ChoiceSeats profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball and hockey, which have more games than football,
might work. Williams Cos. is studying the possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
