<SLUG> BC-BOATS-MOATS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOATS-IN-MOATS ISSUE WILL APPEAR ON MISSOURI BALLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM and WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ The boats-in-moats casino issue and another to ban
cockfighting and other animal cruelty will appear on Missouri's
November ballot, Secretary of State Rebecca Cook announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The gambling measure, to be listed on the ballot as
Constitutional Amendment 9, asks Missouri voters to decide whether
games of chance should be allowed on riverboats that float in
artificial basins fed by river water.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-cockfighting measure will be known as Proposition A and
would make animal fighting a felony punishable by up to five years
in prison. It would also make attending an animal fight a
misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the petition drives to place the measures on the
ballot, Cook also said a criminal investigation was continuing into
allegations of fraud in the gathering of signatures for the
riverboat measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we are at the very beginning of a very large
investigation,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had no reason to believe that the suspected
fraudulent activity was linked to any organized effort by
pro-gambling forces.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said most of the alleged fraud was linked to a petition
circulator identified as David D. Jackson, who she said worked for
Petition Management Inc., a California firm that paid workers to
gather Missouri voters' signatures on petitions.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of fraud were so obvious that the circulator ``must
have thought we were idiots,'' said Cook. Dead people, ministers
known to oppose casinos and relatives of county officials who said
they had not signed also showed up on petitions, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 7,078 signatures gathered by Jackson was counted,
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson apparently used a Springfield motel as his home address.
State officials believe Jackson, who may be an Oklahoma resident,
has left the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fraud uncovered here is absolutely incredible and
despicable,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the seriousness of the allegations, Cook said, the final
tally of names on the gambling petitions was not affected. Gambling
supporters gathered about 30,000 signatures more than the 114,000
needed to place the measure on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Don Poston, a spokesman for the casino-sponsored group
Missourians For Fairness and Jobs in St. Louis, said his group will
cooperate with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Poston said passage of the measure will
preserve thousands of jobs and millions of tax dollars now going to
Missouri schools. ``There is a fundamental question of fairness,''
he added, in that state gaming authorities approved the off-river
operations years ago, triggering more than $1 billion worth of
casino construction in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Supreme Court last year outlawed games of chance at
off-river boats in response to a lawsuit by St. Louis area gambling
foes.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the state's 15 riverboat casinos are threatened by the
action. In the Kansas City area that includes two vessels each
operated by Harrah's and Station Casino, and the Flamingo Hilton
Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Andrews, chairman of the St. Louis-based anti-gambling
group Show Me the River, predicted that Missouri voters would
reject the measure, which would retroactively legalize games of
chance like slot machines aboard off-river gambling boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the casinos succeed at scorning our laws, there will be a
next time and a next,'' Andrews said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
