<SLUG> BC-TWA-PILOTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA PILOTS COMPLETE VOTING ON PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Trans World Airlines' pilots completed voting Friday
on a tentative contract agreement between their union and the
company, but nobody is making predictions about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The ballots will be tabulated at the Air Line Pilots
Association's office in Washington. The results are expected to be
announced Aug. 31, said Gina Butikofer, a spokeswoman for TWA's
pilots union.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Chronic, master chairman of TWA's unit of the pilots union,
said a polling of the pilots three weeks ago showed then that the
vote was too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a large number of pilots who don't care for the
tentative agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic said Air Line Pilots Association, which represents more
than 2,500 TWA pilots, also was upset last week when the company
announced that all airline employees working under their old
contracts would receive a 4.8 percent raise on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think management was trying to tell our pilots that they're
not going to lose anything significant by voting against the new
contract offer,'' he said. ``At least they would get a minimal
raise while holding out for a better offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots union has responded by telling its members that TWA
would save $20 million over six months if the tentative agreement
is rejected. The average pilot would make $1,000 a month more in
salary for the rest of the year under the new contract compared to
the 4.8 percent raise if the offer is rejected, Chronic said.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic said TWA seems to be meddling with the ratification
process of the pilots' new contract. ``We don't know why they
couldn't have waited till next week to make that announcement,
after all the votes are in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TWA declined to comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken the position to not get involved in the matter,''
said Jim Brown, a TWA spokesman in St. Louis. ``I can say we signed
the (tentative) contract because we believed in it and think it's a
good one.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all pilots do. Some of TWA's pilots union members have
created a vocal opposition group called the ``Contract Awareness
Committee.'' The group's main complaint is that the agreement gives
too much to the younger pilots at the expense of the senior pilots
who have taken the biggest concessions over the past 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the four-year contract will bring pilots' pay to 90
percent of the industry standard by the year 2002, which the
opponents say is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots union wants to eliminate the two-tier wage system
that was in place for the younger pilots. The lower wages for newer
hires has created a high turnover rate among the younger pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new contract gives the union 1 million shares
of TWA stock. Union leaders have said the veteran pilots would
receive a greater proportion of the stock to make up for the
smaller percentage raises they would receive than the younger
pilots at the beginning of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Machinists union, which represents about 75
percent of TWA employees, has continued negotiating and has stated
that it would be satisfied with pay increases that would bring
wages within 90 percent of the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of speculation about whether the pilots'
contract will pass or not,'' said Keith Nelson, president of
Machinists Local 1650 in Kansas City. About 2,500 union machinists
work at TWA's jet overhaul base at Kansas City International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also said the 4.8 percent raise in September for all
employees is a previous commitment TWA made when the company sought
concessions from its workers three years ago. Employees should not
consider the pay increase as being part of a new contract the
Machinists are trying to negotiate with management, Nelson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1630EDT &QL; 
