<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS BOARD SHOULD HAVE SPELLED IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. - The big news Thursday was expected to be a
major revelation about the Royals' search for a new owner.
</P>
<P>
   While that news did indeed top the agenda, the more significant
disclosure was that the Royals directors had muddied the process by
their apparent failure to be perfectly clear when articulating the
rules of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The story's lead, of course, was the anointing of New Yorker
Miles Prentice as owner apparent. The significance of the
development was confounded, however, by the board's caveat that
Prentice's success depended on raising half the purchase price from
local backers. The precise amount of additional local money needed
to meet that mandate is a matter of speculation.
</P>
<P>
   All this came as a surprise to many who have followed the
process closely. Prentice said he first became aware of the
requirement earlier this month, but learned only Thursday that it
was included in the Royals articles of incorporation. Not to worry,
though, Prentice said, because if that's what's required, it will
be done. Meanwhile, Royals president Michael Herman challenged
Kansas Citians of means to kick into the kitty to support
Prentice's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Herman's exhortation might have carried more potency, though, if
the Royals board hadn't created the perception of not being as
forthright as it should have been when initially articulating the
terms of the sale. Royals executives seem to think its mere
inclusion in the articles of incorporation speaks for itself and is
thus sufficient, but that's debatable. So is the claim that
documents made available in May included the stipulation.
</P>
<P>
   When the team went up for sale, a table of explicit commandments
should have been prominently displayed for all interested parties _
including the tire kickers _ to see:
</P>
<P>
   1. Thou shalt pay $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. Thou shalt not move the team out of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   3. Thou shalt raise half the purchase money from local sources.
</P>
<P>
   The first two commandments were always unmistakeably
articulated. The third wasn't. Charlie Crumpley, who has been a
lead reporter on the story, reviewed related coverage, but failed
to turn up any specific mention by Royals executives or document
references concerning the 50 percent local ownership requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective local bidders might also wonder why a New York
lawyer and his expert advisers weren't more careful during their
due diligence when reading the fine print of all the pertinent
documents. Prentice has a law degree and experience with buying
sports franchises, and shouldn't have been blind-sided this late in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   That said, however, it doesn't excuse the failure of the Royals
directors to be as up front as circumstances now reveal they should
have been. Some observers of the skeptical persuasion smell a game
of hide-the-cookie and fume that the rules are being changed in the
middle of the game.
</P>
<P>
   While such suspicions may be understandable, the board must be
taken at its word. It's a dedicated group of upstanding citizens
doing a thankless job. Its members deserve a world of credit for
their labors in Kansas City's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   And while the board bears blame for any confusion, Prentice
exacerbated things by his failure to follow what should have been
his lawyerly instincts.
</P>
<P>
   How all this is going to affect the community's ability to
retain its big-league baseball team is now up to its deep-pocketed
civic leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1631EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
