<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following lifestyle
features for publication Sunday, August 23, 1998. If there are any
questions, please call the Star's news desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS (undated) _ Jackie White, fashion editor
for the Kansas City Star, writes a column each week looking at
those ever-changing style trends. Story will move in the ``l''
category.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-TEACHERS-KANSAS (undated) _ Oh, what should parents do
when their child just can't stand a teacher? What course does one
take once the school year starts and complaints from a child begin
mounting like galoshes in the cloakroom? Sidebar attached. By ERIC
ADLER. Story will move in the ``l'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7335 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-TEACHERS-KANSA     08-22 1664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-TEACHERS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADING THE GRADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Yippee, a new school year.
</P>
<P>
   But what's this? Your teacher is ... Mrs. Grundle!
</P>
<P>
   Nooooo!
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the horror.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the inhumanity.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, what should parents do when their child just can't stand a
teacher? What course does one take once the school year starts and
complaints from a child begin mounting like galoshes in the
cloakroom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, Mrs. Grundle yells.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, Mr. Blather's boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, Ms. Miff doesn't like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Students, of course, complain constantly. To many, any teacher
with expectations of work beyond coloring pumpkins is an unpitying
martinet. Moreover, teachers are frequently denounced based not on
any real knowledge, but on years of mythology: ``Dad, everyone says
Mr. Hoggosian is the devil!''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, said Carolyn Callahan, a professor at the
University of Virginia in Charlottesville and immediate past
president of the National Association for Gifted Children, while
most teachers are committed to truly enlightening students, crummy
teachers do exist.
</P>
<P>
   Some _ not most, mind you _ are bad. Unimaginative. Boring.
Burned out. So ill-informed they'd fail their own subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Still others, Callahan said, don't like children. ``Not everyone
is Mr. Rogers. And we can't expect that to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   But parents should expect their children to be well educated.
The difficulty is sorting out if a child's complaints have merit,
and how to proceed without jeopardizing the essential relationship
shared between child and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The first step? The National Education Association, the American
Federation of Teachers, the National Parent Teacher Association and
the National Association of Gifted Children all agree:
</P>
<P>
   Search for the truth. Before yanking your child from class,
storming the principal's office or confronting your child's
teacher, do your best to discern the real issue or problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children,'' Callahan said, ``may not always tell you what the
real problem is.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade expectations
</P>
<P>
   A child may complain about a teacher, while the actual problem
is unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   Some students, for example, may bad-mouth a teacher when the
real problem is the changing expectations of higher grades, such as
the call for additional homework and more independent and critical
thinking. Perhaps the student is having difficulty making the
transition from the relaxed atmosphere of early grades _ naps,
beanbag chairs and relative freedom _ to the more structured higher
grades, sitting at desks in rows.
</P>
<P>
   Social changes also may be a factor. One year a child may be the
most popular student in class; the next, she's not. Suddenly she's
stomping home, hurling her books across the room, yelling, ``I hate
Mrs. Frattlethrap!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the teacher is a bad teacher, or it may be as simple
as a problem on the bus on the way to school,'' Callahan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A common complaint you hear from kids is that my teacher yells
at me,'' said Caroline Butler, a member of the board of directors
of the National Parent Teachers Association and principal at Maple
Wood Elementary School in Somersworth, N.H. ``But a child's
definition of yell is often different from what an adult says is
yell. What a child may mean is, `My teacher corrected me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But if, after some Holmesian sleuthing _ ``It's elementary
school, my dear Watson'' _ parents are convinced that a
teacher-student problem really exists, they should act.
</P>
<P>
   Creative listening
</P>
<P>
   First, parents may observe one or more classes to see if their
child's complaints are borne out. For instance, parents may find a
``strict'' teacher is simply demanding intellectual rigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a child may perceive as mean or tough may actually be a
teacher who, in retrospect, they think, `You know, she really
taught me something. She had a disciplined class, held us to the
curriculum, held us to high standards and it paid off in the end,'
'' said Janet Bass, spokeswoman for the American Federation of
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Next, parents might set up a parent-teacher conference. ``And,
for at least part of that,'' Butler recommended, ``include the
child. Have a three-way conversation, or four-way, if both parents
are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an incident in the middle of the year,'' she recalled,
``where we all sat down together in an environment that was not
threatening. We soon figured out the problem _ the child and
teacher were not understanding what each other was saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is real important for the parent to go in and say,
`This is what my child is saying, and how can we work together to
make my child feel more comfortable in school.' If parents and
teachers can really listen to each other and not threaten each
other, things can be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan concurred. If there's one thing parents don't want to
do it's stampede into a teacher's room with accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never go to school saying to a teacher, `You're wrong,' or,
`You're doing something inappropriate,' '' she said. ``Put the
teacher on the defensive and all you'll get is a defensive
response.''
</P>
<P>
   The best course, Callahan said, is to be honest and reasonable.
Express your child's feelings, misgivings or the situation as best
you know them, then ask how you and the teacher can work together
to solve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing to do,'' Callahan added, ``is to say, `These are the
things that are making my child uncomfortable. She really likes
school. She loves to learn. But she doesn't learn well when she
doesn't have the opportunity to talk to other people. How can we
make it more comfortable for her to learn here? We have the same
goals. How can I help support you in what you do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Often, that should be enough. ``I think in 97 percent of cases,
opening the lines of communication _ when everybody is listening to
each other _ truly takes care of the problem,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   But not always.
</P>
<P>
   To the top
</P>
<P>
   ``If the teacher says, `These are my rules. This is the way I
run my classroom. And that's that,' '' Callahan said, ``then you go
to the principal's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, rather than arriving armed with anger and accusations _
``I'd be very careful not to say, `This is a bad teacher,' ''
Callahan advised _ come prepared with solid examples documenting
your child's concerns and what's keeping her from learning in this
classroom. Examples:
</P>
<P>
   - For two months the teacher has given only workbook
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   - Your child needs more structure; the class is very free.
</P>
<P>
   - Your child thrives with freedom; the teacher is very
regimented.
</P>
<P>
   - You've spoken to parents A, B and C and students X, Y and Z,
who all have concerns about the teacher's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   - You've spoken with the teacher, who seems unwilling to work
with you.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Butler said, parents should expect most principals to
act conservatively. It's the rare administrator who will
immediately switch a student from one classroom to another. And the
reason may have little to do withthe teacher.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no room in other classes. The principal may be
concerned about taking a student out of class where he or she has
good friends; such a switch may do more harm than good. Sometimes
the principal is in a sensitive situation because nobody wants
their child in that classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say you can't get your child moved. You've gone up and
down the line and this is where your child is,'' Callahan said.
``You can do two things.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you tell your child that life isn't always fair.
Sometimes it is grossly unfair. I have bosses I don't like. But as
long as your child is not in any physical or mental danger, he'll
probably be OK. Kids adapt and they're resilient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second: You, at home, begin to intervene in the learning
process. `Tell me what you've learned in school today. Tell me what
you did in math today.' You say, `I can help you make school fun,
even if this is not the best teacher you have ever had.' Then you
make it interesting by the things you do at home.''
</P>
<P>
   If the child's studying the Civil War, for example, take her to
a local battle re-enactment. Go to the library. Get books, videos,
educational computer games.
</P>
<P>
   After school, help the student concentrate on the positive
aspects of class, with questions such as, ``What was the best thing
your teacher did today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea,'' Callahan said, ``is to turn the attention from the
negatives to the positives in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no law that a child has to remain with any
one teacher. Parents pay for schools with either taxes or tuition
and, if they choose, can insist their child be moved from a
classroom. Although it may require going from teacher to principal
to school superintendent, in the end school officials will comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can insist,'' Butler said. ``But you really need to look
at the child and you need to go in and observe. If every other
child in a classroom is happy and smiling and seems to be having a
wonderful time, and your child is not, then what is the situation?
It's knowing the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidebar What mean really means
</P>
<P>
   If a child is having problems with a teacher, educators say,
parents must dig for the facts by asking the child specific
questions, such as:
</P>
<P>
   - Exactly what about your teacher is ``mean''?
</P>
<P>
   - When does she yell at you?
</P>
<P>
   - Why don't you think your teacher likes you? What gives you
that feeling?
</P>
<P>
   - Did she say she doesn't like you?
</P>
<P>
   - Does your teacher yell at you every day?
</P>
<P>
   - Does she yell at other kids?
</P>
<P>
   After sifting through sundry monosyllabic answers or floods of
emotional verbiage, parents should be able to uncover some truths.
Maybe the teacher was in a bad mood. Maybe she was dealing with an
unruly class.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe _ gasp! _ your child actually did something to merit
the teacher's reaction. _ Eric Adler, staff writer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
