<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ A new shop op ...
</P>
<P>
   Posing before a full-length mirror in a comfortable dressing
room trying on clothes in an adult, slightly narcissistic version
of playing dress-up has appeal indeed. But when you're short on
time, charming environments or parking, there are alternative
opportunities, such as the Internet, shopping networks and catalogs
such as the new Macy's by Mail.
</P>
<P>
   The 118-page book, offering fashion and home products, was
mailed to 2 million homes last week. Some 10 million will go out
this fall. From the noted New York-based department store chain, it
includes merchandise from the likes of Tommy Hilfiger, Liz
Claiborne and Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically it comes at a time when business is soft for some of
the biggest catalog companies such as Spiegel and J. Crew,
according to trade journal Women's Wear Daily. But Macy's is
projecting $250 million in catalog sales in five years.
</P>
<P>
   To request a catalog or place an order, call 800-431-9644.
</P>
<P>
   Where to go
</P>
<P>
   On West Sunset Boulevard in Los Angeles, you can buy vintage
clothing in a store called Come to Mamma. Vacation in New York and
visit Cheap Jack's on lower Broadway for 15,000 square feet of
apparel dating back to the 1800s. Buy consignment celebrity clothes
at Encore uptown on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the information you'll find in The Ultimate Consignment
and Thrift Store Guide, (Consignment and Thrift Store Publishing,
$16.95), by Carolyn Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a dedicated scavenger of old and recently new, you may
know the best sources in your neighborhood but not in other cities.
The book does not list every store, but it gives you a start in
such places as Honolulu and Nashville, Tenn. It's available in
major bookstores or check into www.consignmentguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Old Spice?
</P>
<P>
   What's sexy? InStyle magazine asked several hundred women
readers between ages 18 to 49, and in the clothes department the
consensus was _ tah-dah! _ simple jeans and a T-shirt on a woman.
Khakis and an untucked oxford shirt took the title for men. And as
for the sexiest fragrance? Ordinary soap.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three percent thought short hair on women sexy. Forty-five
percent felt a tug at long hair on men.
</P>
<P>
   Among the celebrities, Nicole Kidman picked humor as the
ultimate in sexy. And Natasha Richardson's choice was kitchen
tables, a reminder of ``sex and food,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes have it
</P>
<P>
   The high funnel and turtleneck sweaters so fashionable this fall
require some fresh thinking about makeup, says Dick Page, the New
York-based makeup artist whose recent credits include Calvin Klein,
Michael Kors and Narcisco Rodriguez shows. In the August Vogue, he
advises women to play up the eyes and minimize lips so as not to
look constricted (it may also hold down the lipstick on the
collar).
</P>
<P>
   Some other tips:
</P>
<P>
   - Thin brows make people look startled. And brows should have a
little shine.
</P>
<P>
   - Skip Botox injections that freeze the face. ``Don't be afraid
of the way your face moves,'' Page says. Animated faces are more
interesting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
