<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-GM-NYT &LR;      08-22 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-GM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEGIN LONG, HARD SEARCH FOR NEW GM 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the Fox horses and all the Fox men could not make the
Dodgers a contender again, so now they have begun the search for a
general manager who can.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda will not be the man. The interim general manager
since the dismissal of Fred Claire two months ago, Lasorda said the
trades the Dodgers made would gain them a playoff spot. But there
will be no October baseball games in Los Angeles this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not that his failure to make good on his promise is the reason
Lasorda is not a candidate. Interim, in this instance, really meant
interim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're identifying everyone in the industry who I think is
capable of being a general manager and identifying those people who
are available and requesting permission from their clubs to speak
to those people,'' said Dodgers president Bob Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   A Dodgers search for a general manager does not resemble, say, a
Yankees search for a general manager. There is something about the
frequency that is different.
</P>
<P>
   Under George Steinbrenner, the Yankees have had 15 men serve as
general manager, some of them twice. In nearly 30 years, dating to
December 1968, four years before Steinbrenner and partners bought
the Yankees, the Dodgers had only two general managers before the
June move _ Claire and Al Campanis, who lost his job in April 1987
because of unfortunate remarks about the capabilities of blacks in
management positions.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Dodgers jettisoned Campanis as the politically
correct move to make, they did not have to search for a successor
because Claire was already there.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dave Dombrowski, Jim Bowden, Bob Watson, Omar Minaya, Dean
Taylor and Kevin Malone are the names on the Dodgers' list of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski, the Florida Marlins' general manager, would seem to
be the most logical leading choice. He has the most experience in
the job, put together a World Series champion and has a contract
that expires this year. But he will also be coveted by other teams
seeking a new general manager and a new direction, and the word
among executives of other clubs is that Dombrowski would prefer the
Colorado job, assuming it becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski may also be reluctant to go into a situation where
Lasorda will still be lurking. Graziano said that Lasorda would not
conflict with the new general manager but that Lasorda's role had
not been ``clearly defined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll most definitely have a role in the organization,''
Graziano said. ``I think that will develop as we determine whom
we're hiring and the strengths of the person we're hiring and his
experience. Tommy has a lot of strengths, and I hope to use those
strengths in the future. But the person we're hiring will be the
general manager, no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda is nevertheless joining Graziano and Peter O'Malley, the
former owner and still chairman, in interviewing candidates, none
of whom Graziano would discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, the Cincinnati general manager, has a year left on his
contract. Watson, badly in need of a rest and liberation from
Steinbrenner, remains under contract to the Yankees and is not
certain Steinbrenner will give the Dodgers permission to talk to
him.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is the assistant general manager in Baltimore with a
previous term as the general manager in Montreal. Minaya, with the
Mets, and Taylor, with Atlanta, are assistant general managers who
the Dodgers feel could be ready to assume the No. 1 position.
Minaya is the highest-ranking Hispanic official in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same names will surface in the search by other teams
for general managers. Some executives believe as many as nine or 10
teams could make changes after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for someone who can lead the entire baseball
operation,'' Graziano said, ``someone with a background in
scouting, knowledge of the major leagues and minor leagues, and can
really pull all of our baseball operations together and come up
with the right strategic plan for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziano says he has set no deadline for hiring someone, but his
goal is to have a new general manager going into the off season.
For the Dodgers, the off season begins Sept. 28. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
