<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON'S RELENTLESS WINNING A PROBLEM FOR NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Without a doubt, Jeff Gordon is the driver to
beat this season. But whether his weekly dominance is good or bad
for NASCAR has been the subject of some lively debate.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's goal is to have a racing series that does not favor a
particular team, driver or make of car. So if the racing surface is
level, and the series' strict rules are enforced, every car should
have as good a chance to win as any other.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, one team, Gordon's DuPont-backed No. 24
Chevrolet Monte Carlo, has driven away from the competition. And
that has been raising eyebrows in garages and grandstands around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they want someone winning too much,'' Gordon
said Friday before qualifying for Saturday night's Goody 500,
referring to NASCAR's desire for a variety of winners. ``This sport
is about being as equal as they can possibly get the cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has won eight races this year, including the last
four in a row, attributes much of his success to having a good
rapport with his crew chief, Ray Evernham, who has made several
great late-in-the-race calls in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Evernham talk before, during and after races, trying
to get the car just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that they can't put a template on, one thing they
can't control, is the people,'' Gordon said. ``The driver-crew
chief combination, the pit crew combination. NASCAR knows it's
doing everything it can to make sure everything is equal, but they
can't control how well these people work.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR wants to see every possible car out there win every
season, but that's not possible,'' he said. ``I'm sure there's a
point where too much dominance is not good, but a certain amount of
it is not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing majority of fans voice their displeasure with Gordon's
weekly domination, booing him before and after every race. Because
when Gordon wins, 42 other drivers _ many of whom are admired by
these fans _ lose.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, the director of competition for NASCAR, said: ``At
the end of the day, it's more important to us that the second-place
car is close enough to him to put on a good show. Right now, they
are not as close as we would like them to be, but it will take care
of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Planning Return
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Spencer, who sustained a severe concussion in a wreck at
the Brickyard 400 last month, expects to return for next weekend's
race at New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, the driver of the No. 23 Winston car, started the race
three weeks ago at Watkins Glen, but was relieved by the backup
driver, Boris Said, on the 10th lap. Days later, Spencer announced
that he would skip the next two races (Michigan and Bristol)
because the injury was more serious than believed initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks they know more than the doctor,'' Spencer
said. ``I regret ever getting in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was cleared to return for Saturday night's race at
Bristol, but he said there was some concern that he might struggle
with dizziness caused by the sharp banked turns of the half-mile
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I took the time off,'' Spencer said. ``I didn't think
it would have been a wise decision to jeopardize the team or the
other drivers. There's a lot of pressure from sponsors, fans and
your own team, but it was something I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer's best finish in a points race this season was second at
Talladega in the Diehard 500. He is 14th in the Winston Cup
championship points race.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Leading Rookie
</P>
<P>
   One year after taking rookie-of-the-year honors in the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series, Kenny Irwin is again the fastest first-year
driver on the track.
</P>
<P>
   This season, however, Irwin is leading the Winston Cup rookie
points standing, a prestigious award won by many of the sport's
best drivers. Should he hold on to his comfortable lead, Irwin will
join the likes of Richard Petty, Jeff Gordon, Rusty Wallace and
Dale Earnhardt in having captured the award.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who drives the No. 28 Texaco Ford, has one top-five
(fifth at Atlanta) and three top-10 finishes this season.
</P>
<P>
   Unleaded Fuel Test
</P>
<P>
   Even in this day of environmental consciousness, it came as
somewhat of a surprise when the NASCAR Busch Series driver Elton
Sawyer tested a car at Charlotte last week running on unleaded
fuel. Except for opening the carburetor slightly, there were no
modifications made to the engine. Sawyer's crew simply emptied out
the 110 octane leaded gas used now by NASCAR and filled the tank
with a special Unocal unleaded gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went well; we did not experience any problems as
far as torque,'' Sawyer said. ``It drove the same, ran the same.
The only concern Unocal had was to make sure there wasn't any
extensive wear in the engine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first serious test of unleaded fuel to be used for
racing, and there are going to be several more test runs, according
to NASCAR, before a decision will be made on whether it is a viable
option.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
