<P>
   ROCKART _ EL PASO, Texas _ Hueco Tanks State Historical Park is
a desert enclave of rock and caves that was once a haven for Ice
Age hunters and a spiritual meeting place for native tribes from
both sides of the Rio Grande. Now the 860-acre park has become the
flash point for a cultural clash over recreational and spiritual
use and the preservation and protection of priceless cave drawings
and archeological treasures dating back 12,000 years. According to
Kay Sutherland, an anthropology professor: ``It represents a sacred
place that was a crossroads or a confluence of a lot of cultures.
It is the Sistine Chapel of the Pueblo Indians. And Texas Parks and
Wildlife should pay homage to that. We should pay attention to
Native American voices and not disrespect their beliefs about it.''
But rock climbers and graffiti artists are destroying the artwork.
Use of the park will be restricted to guided tours starting Sept.
1. (Legett, Austin American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS and LOCATOR
MAP.
</P>
<P>
   OUT _ Outdoor column: Cowboy action shooter from Yellow Springs.
(Morris, Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
