<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA: JOHNNY BENCH HE ISN'T; THE PACESETTER SPEAKS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mike Piazza wants to be baseball's highest-paid player, he
should probably learn how to execute the fundamentals of his
position. He came to the Mets with a reputation as a
mediocre-at-best catcher, and he has made plays that indicate that
rating may be too kind.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a couple of weeks, Piazza messed up two run-down
plays. In the first instance, he did not run the runner back toward
third base far enough and enabled the trailing runner to reach
third instead of having to hold at second. In the second instance,
perhaps compensating for the first, he ran the runner back to third
so far that he never threw the ball to the third baseman, and the
runner dived back into the base ahead of Piazza's lunging tag.
</P>
<P>
   That six-year, $84 million offer the Dodgers made is looking
better and better.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacesetter Speaks
</P>
<P>
   Because Mark McGwire has been the focal point of the pursuit of
the home run record, and as such, his name and picture have
appeared daily in Maris pace charts, maybe he deserves to be
listened to on the subject of pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pace is a pace,'' he said. ``You can be off the pace and
then with two or three in a day, you're right back on it. So I
don't think it really means much until the last out of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's own experience shows exactly what he means. When he
hit his 45th home run, he was ``on a pace'' to hit 69 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But then he hit only two home runs in the Cardinals' next 18
games, and his pace plummeted to 61 or 62. Then he erupted with a
barrage of four home runs in three games, and the pace shot back up
to 65 or 66.
</P>
<P>
   As McGwire said, pace means nothing until the last out is made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
