<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA'S SLAM PUTS METS OVER 'BACKS, 9-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It must have been an omen. The New York Mets changed
the picture they usually show on the video board in left field when
Mike Piazza is at bat from one that displayed him with a serious
look to one of him grinning.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Saturday's game was over, both Piazza and the rest
of the Mets had plenty to smile about.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who has been sizzling with the bases loaded, turned the
boos to cheers at Shea Stadium with a towering grand slam off Andy
Benes to punctuate a six-run second inning as the Mets overcame a
4-0 deficit and defeated the Arizona Diamondbacks, 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   For an encore, Piazza _ who also had a single and scored a run
in a two-run fifth _ made a sensational catch of a Travis Lee foul
pop in the top of the third, sliding down the steps of the
visitors' dugout to make the out.
</P>
<P>
   And by finishing a brutal five-day stretch with a 6-2 record,
the Mets (72-57) had pulled back into the National League wild-card
lead, a game ahead of the Cubs, who were routed, 8-3, at Wrigley
Field by Randy Johnson and the Houston Astros on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, it was a day of redemption for Piazza, who has done
his best to shrug off the way he has been treated this summer at
Shea. Piazza had heard a smattering of boos when he struck out with
runners on first and third in the first inning. When he came up
again in the second, with a chance to redeem himself, the Mets were
trailing, 4-2. And with one full-count swing, he was back to being
the hero again.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza and his teammates deserved the applause, considering that
the Mets had just erupted for six runs to erase a four-run deficit.
The Diamondbacks had scored all of their runs with two out in the
top of the second off Bobby Jones, who was making a rare start on
three days of rest because the Mets had just completed a stretch of
three doubleheaders in four days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For a moment, Jones looked as if he was going to escape the
second without allowing a run when he intentionally walked Kelly
Stinnett with two outs and runners on second and third to bring up
Benes. But the strategy backfired when Benes belted a two-run
double over third on an 0-1 pitch. Former Yankee Andy Fox followed
with a two-run single on Jones' next pitch, and the Mets were
staring up from a four-run hole.
</P>
<P>
   But Benes was struggling with his control. His first eight
pitches in the bottom of the first had been balls. And even though
he now had a sizable lead, Benes turned right around and walked
Todd Hundley on a full-count pitch to start the second.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Baerga followed by lining a single over short, and
Hundley kept running _ all the way to third with a head-first slide
as he apparently caught his best friend, Bernard Gilkey, napping a
little in left field.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter was Rey Ordonez, who drew a full-count walk. And
now Benes, who threw 74 pitches in the first two innings, was
really in trouble. But he, too, nearly escaped after Jones struck
out and Tony Phillips lined to right for a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   With runners now on first and third, Edgardo Alfonzo beat out a
check-swing grounder up the third-base line to make it 4-2. A wild
pitch and another full-count walk (this time to John Olerud, who
had narrowly missed a three-run homer to right two pitches earlier)
brought up Piazza with the bases full.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza quickly fell behind, 1-2, before working the count full.
The shot Piazza then launched into the left field bleachers on
Benes' next pitch was estimated at 380 feet. And if anyone was
booing at Shea, there was no way to tell.
</P>
<P>
   While it was the Mets' first grand slam of the season, it was
Piazza's fourth this year (he hit three with the Dodgers in April,
one against Arizona) and the ninth of his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
