<HEADLINE>
FOR AMERICA'S BIGGEST HORSE SHOW, TWO HEADS ARE BETTER THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ak) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEHAMPTON, N.Y. _ People get jobs in the strangest ways.
Consider Tony Hitchcock and his wife, Jean Lindgren, who manage the
Hampton Classic, America's most important outdoor horse show and
its largest (1,600 horses), richest ($400,000 in prize money) and
best attended (50,000 spectators).
</P>
<P>
   This year's Hampton Classic, which begins an eight-day run
Sunday, will mark the Hitchcocks' 21st year in charge. They got
into the business through the back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1970s,'' Hitchcock said in a recent interview,
``we both taught at the Hampton Day School. Then I was fired and
Jean quit. We didn't want to teach and we didn't want to move away,
so in 1976 we decided to be caterers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had been an amateur chef. Lindgren was a good cook.
They had staged international dinners for school fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day in 1976,'' Hitchcock said, ``I got this call and I
recognized the deep voice right away. It was George Plimpton. He
said, `Is there any chance you are free to do a party on Bastille
Day?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Let me check our date book and see if we are booked
that day.' Booked? We had never catered anything. That was our
first call. I made believe I checked our date book and then told
him we could do it. He said: `Fine. We have 1,000 guests.'''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that everyone brought food, and Hitchcock and
Lindgren provided desserts. Their main job that day was party
management. The party turned out to be like a gigantic family
picnic with celebrities, including much of the Kennedy clan.
Another guest was Tinka Topping. She was a founder of the one-day
Southampton Horse Show, which was expanding to become the Hampton
Classic. Topping was impressed by Hitchcock and Lindgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1978,'' Hitchcock said, ``they told us: ``You're good at
catering and managing. Why don't you come back as the coordinators
of the show?' We did, and we have been doing it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, the show has leased the McNamara family's 60-acre
potato farm a half-mile north of the Montauk Highway. Seven more
acres have been leased from the town of Southampton. The grass is
thick and rich, and the trees and shrubs look fresh out of a
nursery.
</P>
<P>
   The summertime Hamptons are celebrity heaven. Joan Lunden and
Stefanie Powers have ridden in the show, and the spectators in
recent years have included Alec and Billy Baldwin, Candice Bergen,
Christie Brinkley, Glenn Close, Bianca Jagger, Billy Joel, Quincy
Jones, Donna Karan, Calvin Klein, Ralph Lauren, Paul Newman and
Joanne Woodward, Steven Spielberg, Barbra Streisand and Robert
Wagner.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Through the years, the not-for-profit show has raised $750,000
for charities. Still, Hitchcock and Lindgren are trying to
popularize this white-collar sport by keeping the admission cost to
$5 a person or $15 a carload.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can run a horse show that is not just elitist,'' Hitchcock
said, ``but something that touches everyone in this community, from
the richest to the poorest.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lindgren said: ``I think a lot of people are scared to
come here. They think it's too fancy. They think they won't fit in.
But you look at the people here wearing T-shirts and floppy hats,
and you can't tell who's rich and who's poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Catering has now taken a back seat for the couple. Running the
show is a year-round job, and they also spend eight weeks in the
winter staging six shows in Indio, Calif., near Palm Desert. They
have come a long way for two people with undistinguished careers as
riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 6 to about 10,'' Lindgren said, ``I rode a dappled
gray who hated cars and would kick our neighbor's car. I was no
show rider. I rode him just for fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's equestrian experience is even more limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 12,'' he said, ``this Dr. Loker had a barn with one
swayback horse and five cows. I rode the horse and milked the cows.
At 26, I took five riding lessons. They finally got me to canter,
and it was so terrifying that I haven't ridden since.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
