<HEADLINE>
HOTEL INNOVATOR SEEKS BIGGER CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernard Goldberg thinks that minibars in hotel rooms
are appalling. He contends that free chamber music performances
will pay for themselves in guest satisfaction. And if orange juice
is to be billed as fresh squeezed, he said, those oranges should
stay intact until just minutes before the juice is delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's views on hotel operations command a certain amount of
attention. Over the last 10 years he has taken five rundown but
well-located small hotels in Manhattan and converted them to
attractive properties catering to the city's booming tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   Now he wants to try something different. Last month he sold his
entire portfolio, consisting of the five hotels plus an office
building on West 55th Street, to Credit Suisse First Boston,
reportedly for close to $150 million. ``It's time to do something
different in size and concept,'' said Goldberg, chairman of Gotham
Hospitality Group. He said he hoped to acquire control of one of
the city's older, larger hotels and restore it to an elegance and
style that he said they once had, but have lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are these old dowagers in this city that are tired and
in need of an infusion of light and air,'' he said. Goldberg said
he was looking for a hotel in the 800 to 1,200 room range. He
declined to identify them, but hotel industry analysts said the
group that he is considering probably includes the Pennsylvania and
Roosevelt hotels, both of which are older properties that have
undergone renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitality specialists caution that running a big hotel is
different from managing boutiques. Smaller hotels can afford to
cater to business travelers and tourists, but large hotels must
market themselves to larger groups to fill the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large hotel is a different animal in many ways from a
boutique property,'' said Sean Hennessey, New York director of
PricewaterhouseCoopers' gaming and hospitality practice. ``Small
hotels shun the group market, but big hotels have to concentrate on
the group market to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that, as far as he knew, there had been no examples of
an operator buying a big hotel and grafting boutique hotel concepts
to it. But he did note that large hotels had the advantage of
economies of scale, with management costs being spread over a
larger number of rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone can do it, Bernard can,'' said John A. Fox, a senior
vice president of PKF Consulting, which specializes in hotels. He
said Goldberg's success in taking buildings that were little short
of single-room-occupancy residences and turning them into upscale
hotels demonstrated his ability to add value to properties.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's plans for a big hotel, provided he succeeds in
gaining control of one, consist of style, customer satisfaction and
variable pricing. All three, he said, are important to creating an
experience that will induce travelers to come back to the hotel
when they visit New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stay at a hotel in Paris, you know that it is
Paris,'' he said. ``You need the same thing in New York. The hotel
has to be thematic. It has to have the feeling of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he had looked at hotel properties in Chicago
and Aspen, Colo., he said he was not likely to acquire anything
outside of New York. ``New York is what I know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his smaller hotels, Goldberg chose every piece of art and
made sure that what was on the wall of the corridors was
coordinated with furnishings in the guest rooms. He said that
integrating the public spaces of a hotel with the guest rooms was
important to creating a pleasant experience for guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at an 800-room hotel in the Broadway district where
the owners had spent a lot of money on refurbishing rooms,'' he
said. He said to reposition the hotel, as the owners wanted, would
require throwing out all the newly purchased furniture because it
clashed with the mass-produced hunting scenes decorating the walls.
``They were from different countries and different periods,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Small things count, Goldberg maintains. Like fresh flowers in
public areas and guest rooms. ``I was at one of the most expensive
hotels in the city and they had an array of silk flowers in the
lobby,'' he said. ``Why not spend $100 to $200 a week to have fresh
flowers in the rooms? That's called thinking about the guest.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg is a real estate lawyer who redeveloped distressed
housing before buying his first hotel, the Wales, on Madison Avenue
between 92nd and 93rd streets, in 1988. He contends that a
short-sighted focus on immediate earnings leads some hotel managers
to do things that degrade the guest experience. Many hotels lease
out ground floor space to retailers, because of the high rents
these businesses are willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   But if the result is a tiny lobby, guests are cheated, he said.
``If you have a 200-room hotel and a lobby that only fits 40
people, the guests notice it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said free amenities, such as chamber music concerts,
breakfast and after-theater snacks, add to the guest experience
because the hotel does not appear to be trying to squeeze nickels
and dimes out of them. And he said the cost of these amenities is
more than made up by higher room rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can change the character of a hotel with these
amenities,'' he said. ``You should serve scones and strawberries at
tea time along with chamber music.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had installed machines that made cappuccino from
freshly ground beans in his smaller hotels so that guests could
serve themselves at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he hates minibars. Forcing guests to pay high
prices for a meager bag of chips or a soft drink leaves a bad
taste, he said. Similarly, charging extra to watch a taped movie
adds to the feeling of exploitation, he argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you charge somebody to watch a movie at your home?'' he
asks. ``That's what the guest experience should be, like a visit to
your home.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goldberg said he was planning to price rooms at an average of
$225 a night, which would put prices between the current rates for
first class and luxury hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But the $225 number is only an average. Goldberg said he planned
to use a form of marginal pricing to try to fill his hotel every
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying that it is great that we have 90 percent
occupancy,'' he said. ``But in a 1,000-room hotel, that means that
100 rooms are vacant. That is the equivalent of a small hotel that
is unoccupied.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would follow a pricing model similar to the one used
by airlines, which charge the highest prices to business travelers
with inflexible schedules. The bargain seats are sold at far lower
prices to people with more time than money, to insure that the
airplanes fly as full as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have suites at $350 a night, but we will also have
rooms for $99 a night,'' he said, to keep vacancies at a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can make money running a hotel in New York today,'' he
said. ``But what happens when the downturn comes? If you are the
hotel of choice for a lot of people, the business will take care of
itself.''
</P>
