<HEADLINE>
FORMER MERCHANT MARINE CADETS FACE U.S. MOLESTATION CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ak) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two former cadets at the U.S. Merchant Marine Academy on Long
Island, N.Y., who were accused of sexually assaulting a female
cadet in her room last year are now facing federal charges, after
Nassau County prosecutors dropped state charges on Friday because
the state lacked jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the former cadets, Francis Crowley, 23, of Glendale,
N.Y., and Steven Valjato, 22, of Richmond Hill, N.Y., filed a
motion earlier this month to dismiss the state case because the
Kings Point academy was built on federal land.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the question of jurisdiction arose, we researched it and
we arranged for the federal government to take the case,'' said Ed
J. Grilli, a spokesman for the Nassau County district attorney's
office. ``It's clear that we cannot prosecute a case we have no
jurisdiction over. It just all came together Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The men were arraigned Friday in U.S. District Court in
Uniondale, N.Y. The arraignment was first reported by Newsday
Saturday. It is not known how the new charges will affect
punishment if the men are found guilty of sexual assault on federal
property.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Saturday, Thomas Liotti, Valjato's
lawyer, said state prosecutors had acted vindictively toward his
client by ``zealously'' persuading the federal government to take
over the case.
</P>
<P>
   He also said federal prosecutors had erred in not consulting
with the Justice Department before bringing charges for crimes
committed on federal property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government will come to see they have no case
against my client and the charges will be dropped,'' Liotti said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint charges that Crowley molested a junior
midshipman, a top engineering student, in her bed while Valjato
warned her that if she told anyone ``it would be all over.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men left the school shortly after the incident allegedly
took place on Sept. 28. Liotti said Valjato is now an engineering
student at the State University of New York at Stony Brook and
Crowley is working and thinking about returning to school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
