<SLUG> BC-NY-ROOFGARDEN-REAL(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO FLOURISH, ROOF GARDENS NEED PLANNING, MONEY AND PERSEVERANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (ak) 
By JAY ROMANO   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _Tom Kaminski, a traffic reporter for WCBS News Radio
88, spends most afternoons perched in a helicopter looking for the
unusual. What caught his eye one day as he gazed through his
plastic bubble 1,500 feet above street level was a patch of green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a roof garden on one of the buildings in midtown, and
it was really beautiful,'' Kaminski said. ``That's when I realized
that there are many of these little gardens on roofs all over New
York. Little patches of green sitting high in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   The little patches of lush green gardens perched on the roofs
and terraces of New York City buildings number at least in the
hundreds and probably thousands, making for an intriguing sight
from the air. Many are private gardens, planted by renters or
apartment owners with access to terraces or patios. Others are
communal gardens installed as an amenity for residents.
</P>
<P>
   They are installed at highly varying costs, but what the larger
roof gardens do have in common, according to real estate
specialists, are the planning, money and perseverance required to
build them successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roof gardens can be wonderful or they can be a nightmare,''
said Ronni Lynn Arougheti, president of Heron Ltd., a Manhattan
property management company. ``It all depends on whether they're
properly designed, properly installed, and properly maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilyse Fink, a spokeswoman for the Department of Buildings, said
she could not estimate the number of roof gardens in New York City.
Many have undoubtedly been installed illegally without permits, Ms.
Fink said, and those that do have permits have a general alteration
permit, a type that does not necessarily include roof gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a safety perspective, they should be getting permits,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most large roof gardens are in co-ops and condominiums, because
rental owners usually have little incentive to spend the money to
build them, and managing them effectively may be a larger problem
than they care to undertake, building managers say.
</P>
<P>
   For co-op or condominium boards that decide to develop a garden,
the first problem is often to get residents to support the project
and the expenses it generates. But then other hurdles are likely as
well _ logistical, legal, social, structural and horticultural.
</P>
<P>
   Once a roof garden is finished and operating successfully,
however, the benefits seem to go beyond the enjoyment of buds,
blooms and blossoms. Roof gardens are selling points in older
buildings that lack the health clubs, gyms and swimming pools found
in newer buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we put in our roof garden was to stay
competitive with all the new buildings,'' said Sanford Greenberg, a
Manhattan lawyer and vice president of the co-op at 155 E. 76th
St., which was adorned with a 1,700-square-foot garden over the
last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the new buildings that are going up are stressing
amenities,'' Greenberg said. ``And since we were about to embark on
a new roof-replacement program, putting in a roof garden would
certainly be a way of increasing the value of all the shareholders'
apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   James J. Blum, the structural engineer who was hired by the
board, said that it is usually when a building starts to consider a
new roof installation that the subject of a roof garden comes up.
Older buildings with wooden roof-support beams may require the
installation of additional supports to increase the roof's carrying
capacity, he said, and this is more easily accomplished in
conjunction with a roof replacement.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Blum said, whenever any of his client buildings is
replacing its roof and contemplating a roof garden _ even at some
uncertain point in the future _ his advice is that it is generally
worth the additional investment to install the new roof in such a
way as to maximize the roof's ability to support a garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually makes a very small difference in the cost of a
roof-replacement project to plan for a garden,'' Blum said. ``But
it can mean an enormous savings when the time comes to install the
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   The board members at 155 E. 76th St., known as the Queen Anne,
wanted to install a pergola _ a structure designed to provide shade
for the residents. By knowing about the plan before the roof was
replaced, Blum said, he was able to insure that supports for the
pergola were installed as an integral part of the new roof. That
avoided the additional expense of cutting holes in the new roof
surface and minimized the possibility that retrofitted supports
might cause a leak, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cholst, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that planning could
even avoid legal problems. When planters are placed on the roof
without professional guidance, there is a risk of damaging the roof
and voiding its warranty, he said. ``Basically, you can only use
your roof for the purpose for which it was intended,'' Cholst said.
</P>
<P>
   An early step in the installation of a roof garden should be a
check with the building engineer to make sure that the warranty
will remain in place, Cholst said. At the same time, he said, those
who are replacing a roof and have future plans for a garden should
make sure that the warranty on the new roof will cover the
anticipated use.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that buildings contemplating installing a roof
garden must find out from their insurance carriers whether
additional endorsements will be required.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arougheti, of Heron, the management company, agreed. ``The
carrier is going to be concerned about parapet heights, whether
there are proper walking surfaces, and even if people are going to
be allowed to smoke up there,'' she said. Low parapet walls pose a
risk of falls and some walking surfaces can contribute to slips.
Smokers may flip a cigarette over the wall and onto someone else's
patio furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arougheti said she had seen roof gardens that ranged from
the simple to the sublime _ from a wood deck with a planter or two,
to an extravaganza of trellises and trees with ornate planters,
terra-cotta tiles and even showers for sunbathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my buildings has two separate gardens, one for the kids
and one for the adults,'' Ms. Arougheti said, referring to a co-op
at 222 Park Ave. South. The children's garden has a jungle gym and
high parapet walls, and the garden for adults has expensive patio
furniture, professional landscaping and even an automatic sprinkler
system. The building uses the roof for its annual meetings, Ms.
Arougheti said.
</P>
<P>
   But roof gardens can cause problems, she said, in terms of both
maintenance and community relations.
</P>
<P>
   In buildings without automatic sprinkler systems, she said, the
plants must be watered if there has not been sufficient rainfall.
And a system must be developed to deal with litter that residents
leave for others to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially more difficult problem comes from residents who
are not happy with the garden. ``I was just at a building where the
people who live on the floor under the garden moved out of their
apartment because of the noise,'' Ms. Arougheti said. Upper-floor
tenants and those with private terraces of their own near the roof
are particularly likely to be sensitive to noise. But there are
also concerns about privacy and security, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Queen Anne, a shareholder in a penthouse apartment
objected to the roof garden because of concerns over all three
issues, Greenberg said. The design accordingly took them into
account.
</P>
<P>
   The walls separating the garden from the shareholder's private
terrace were made high enough so people in the garden could not see
into the penthouse, he said. Video cameras were installed for
security, and the board established ``garden rules'' to minimize
noise and try to prevent other problems. Residents using the roof
garden at the Queen Anne are not permitted to drink alcoholic
beverages, smoke or play radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object was to keep the garden a quiet place,'' he said.
``We never intended it as a place for parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur I. Weinstein, a Manhattan lawyer who is also vice
president of the Council of New York Cooperatives, said that in
addition to keeping a roof garden a tranquil place, the drafting of
specific rules prevents it from becoming a source of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to have as much in writing as possible,''
Weinstein said. And he generally recommends specific restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my buildings allow shareholders to have small parties,
provided they sign an indemnification agreement with the co-op and
obey all the rules,'' Weinstein said. Under this agreement the
resident responsible for a party agrees to reimburse the co-op for
any expenses for damages or cleanup after the party.
</P>
<P>
   He generally recommends that co-ops require the shareholder
giving the party to leave a deposit to insure payment of those
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said he also recommends that specific hours of use be
established and strictly enforced, and that children be allowed on
the roof only when accompanied by an adult. Finally, he said, a
policy covering access to the roof by guests and perhaps even
renters should be established and adhered to.
</P>
<P>
   Claims against strangers or rental tenants are much more
difficult to pursue than are those that are against shareholders,
Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Vitelli, a senior vice president at Insignia
Residential Group in Manhattan, said one of the management's
biggest problems is dealing with residents who build gardens on
their private terraces without proper planning or supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Even a small roof garden that has been installed improperly can
cause serious problems, Vitelli said. If planters are not elevated
and properly supported, they can severely damage the roof membrane
and cause leaking into apartments below, he said. And planters that
do not allow for proper drainage can become so heavy from
accumulated water that they can cause structural damage on terraces
not designed to support so much weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get more calls about leaks caused by planters than almost
any other leak-related problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, informal communal gardens that residents
start on some roofs frequently evolve from little green patches to
big green problems for building management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these roof gardens have had plants growing on them for
as long as 20 or 30 years,'' he said. ``Once you have all that
equipment and all that dirt and all those plants and trees in
place, it becomes an enormous expense to haul it all off and go
back and do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Vitelli said, anyone contemplating a private garden
_ as well as well-intentioned residents determined to spruce up the
roof _ should first consult the building's management, which should
then consult the building's engineer, to determine whether a garden
is feasible and to make sure that if it is, it is installed
properly and with the necessary permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some co-op boards don't allow any plantings at all,'' Vitelli
said. ``And if we had it our way, that would be the standard
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in buildings with sturdy roofs, strict rules and happy
shareholders, a roof garden would be of little use without plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``A roof garden can cost anywhere from $5,000 to well over
$100,000, depending on what you want it to look like,'' said Philip
Roche, a landscape designer with Plant Specialists, the Long Island
City company that designed and installed the Queen Anne's roof
garden. The cost for an average-size roof garden is about $50,000
for buildings that want something between unadorned decking and
horticultural extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant factors in designing a roof garden are the
amount of money and space available and the amount of weight the
roof can support. ``Years ago, there really wasn't much control
over rooftop gardens,'' Roche said. ``But now, buildings have to be
strict about conforming to city codes.''
</P>
<P>
   There are requirements relating to entry and egress, he said. As
a result, gardens must be designed not to interfere with required
exit doors. Height requirements for parapet walls must be followed
if people will be using the roof for recreational purposes, he
said, even if such recreation consists solely of sunbathing or
meditating on the beauty of the skyline. Designs are adjusted to
comply with codes, and the plans are presented to the building's
engineer for suggestions for modifications.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he said, offers another example of the utility of
planning a roof garden long before the first potted plant takes
root.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were working with the engineer at the Queen Anne even
before they started working on the roof,'' Roche said, explaining
that such early involvement made it possible to instruct the
roofing contractor to modify the substructure of the roof during
reconstruction so that it could accommodate a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Once that was done, Roche said, the company was able to exercise
broad latitude in deciding what kind of plants and planters to use
and how densely they could be installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that goes on a roof today is usually removable,''
Roche said. A fundamental rule of roof-garden design is that the
soil the plants are put in should never come in contact with the
roof surface itself. Instead, modern roof-garden design employs
industrial-strength yet lightweight planters set on wood decking or
concrete or terra-cotta tiles that are themselves elevated above
the roof surface.
</P>
<P>
   In the Queen Anne, after the new roof was installed, Plant
Specialists laid down concrete paving tiles in the area that was to
be used for the garden. The tiles were set on a plastic pedestal
system that elevated them a few inches above the roof surface and
provided a concealed space through which irrigation pipes and
wiring for lighting were run. Once the tiles were down, Plant
Specialists brought in the planters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use a lot of fiberglass, a lot of wood, a bit of clay, and
rarely we'll use stone,'' Roche said, adding that the planters
themselves were constructed at the company's headquarters. In most
cases, he said, roof planters are designed to spread the planter's
weight over the greatest possible area while keeping the planter
body slightly elevated above the surface. All planters have
drainage material and filter cloths to insure that any water that
seeps out is free of soil or other solid material, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roche said the planters are usually transported to the roof
empty and then filled with soil and plants. In the Queen Anne,
however, the tree-filled planters were hoisted up the side of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the co-op board wanted the garden to be a
parklike place that required as little maintenance as possible,''
Roche said, so 14 trees were installed with ivy growing in the soil
around the trees. Most of the planters, he said, were constructed
of cedar with benches attached. All, he said, have automatic
watering systems and lighting fed from piping and electrical wiring
run up through the pavers and into the bottom of the planters.
</P>
<P>
   The garden was finished with a wisteria-covered pergola, some
teak steamer chairs and other chairs and tables. Total cost:
$80,000.
</P>
<P>
   And why would a board spend so much for 14 trees, some ivy and a
few deck chairs? ``It gives life in the city another dimension,''
Roche said. ``It keeps you sane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
