<SLUG> BC-POISON-IVY-REAL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WET WEATHER MEANS LONGER POISON IVY SEASON THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ky., Mass.)  (ak) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it might seem hard to imagine another problem that can be
attributed to the notorious El Nino, here's one you may not have
heard yet:
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been one very bad year for poison ivy,'' said
Kathlene Cowan, information systems manager for Tec Laboratories,
an Albany, Ore., manufacturer of products designed to alleviate
skin irritations. ``Because of all the rains we've had this year,
we are now seeing the poison ivy season extending into the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cowan said the season for poison ivy generally peaked in the
spring and started to wane by July. This year, however, she said,
individuals sensitive to the plant could still be bumping into it
as they rake leaves and drag them where the plant may still be
growing. ``About three out of four people are allergic to poison
ivy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee McGoodwin, managing director of the Oklahoma Poison Control
Center in Oklahoma City, said the rash that develops after contact
with poison ivy is an allergic reaction to an oily substance _
urushiol _ contained in the leaves and stems.
</P>
<P>
   One thing frequently not taken into consideration, Ms. McGoodwin
said, is that urushiol can remain on clothing, tools and pets _ and
retain its potency _ for up to a year unless it is washed off.
Moreover, she said, those who come in contact with the substance
typically do not exhibit symptoms for up to a week. As a result,
she said, there is a good chance that people who get poison ivy
will not know when or where they came in contact with the oil. And
after urushiol is on the skin, there is only a short period of time
in which to wash off before it is too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's generally impossible to wash it off with ordinary soap
and water after 10 or 15 minutes,'' Ms. McGoodwin said, explaining
that the proteins in the oil bind tightly with proteins in the
skin.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not altogether impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Technu is for,'' said Ms. Cowan of Tec
Laboratories. The product, sold in drugstores, can remove urushiol
from the skin as long as 10 hours after contact with the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly, the easiest way to avoid poison ivy is to recognize
it and stay away from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``While identifying the plants and avoiding them would seem to
be the best way to protect yourself from the rash, it's certainly
not a foolproof approach,'' said Dr. Joseph Fowler, an associate
clinical professor of dermatology at the University of Louisville.
In fact, Fowler said, in a nationwide survey earlier this year,
more than 75 percent of those surveyed said they could identify
poison ivy _ while 66 percent indicated that they or a family
member have had poison ivy, oak or sumac.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said there was hope even for those who would not know a
poison ivy plant if they tripped over one: a product called Ivy
Block, a ``pre-exposure'' lotion that can prevent urushiol from
binding with proteins in the skin, stopping the allergic reaction.
The product can be found in drugstores and sporting goods stores.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For those who want to avoid poison ivy the old-fashioned way
there is always ``The Poison Ivy Card,'' available from the Center
for Poison Ivy Information in South Weymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   John L. Palmer, director of the center, said that the key to
using the card _ which costs $1 and is available from the center's
World Wide Web site (www.woodsweb.com) _ is to ``stick it in your
pocket and carry it around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is to actually look for poison ivy and then compare
what you see on the ground to the pictures on the card,'' Palmer
said. The reason people frequently misidentify poison ivy, he said,
is that it comes in different configurations. The plant can be
found in the Northeast in various forms _ such as a vine, a
ground-hugging shrub or an erect, woody bush, he said. Moreover,
while the leaves are greenish brown during the spring and summer,
they often turn red in fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one consistent characteristic, however,'' Palmer
said. ``There really are always three leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, knowing the plant when one sees it does not help much
if one does not see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they know what poison ivy looks like,'' Palmer
said. ``But they never think they'll find it in their own backyard.
So that's the last place they look for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
