<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-DICKSON-TEX     08-22 1850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DICKSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARALYSIS FROM ACCIDENT FAILS TO SINK SPIRITS OF FORMER TEXAS
CORNERBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The discourse Tyres Dickson had prepared advocating
harsher penalties for driving while intoxicated may have more
impact when he finally delivers it to a speech class at the
University of Texas, almost a year later than planned.
</P>
<P>
   Trust that it also may be well-attended.
</P>
<P>
   For it is likely that the former Longhorns football player will
give the speech from a wheelchair _ he was paralyzed from the chest
down as the result of a spinal-cord injury sustained last spring in
an automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get a chance to give the speech before spring
break,'' Dickson recalled recently from a hospital bed at The
Institute for Rehabilitation and Research in the heart of Houston's
Medical City. ``It's real ironic. The last thing my professor said
to me was, `Tyres, you'll be first when we come back on Monday.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That Monday won't occur before some time in January, when
Dickson hopes to resume his UT classes.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 1 a.m. on March 22 _ the Sunday morning Dickson
was to return to campus from spring break _ the 1994 Saturn
carrying him and three friends was broadsided by a '98 Suburban at
an intersection of an access road and a street that passes under
U.S. 290 in northwest Houston. The blood alcohol of the Suburban's
28-year-old driver, who witnesses reportedly said sped up to go
through a red light, tested at a level of 0.23. A driver is legally
intoxicated in Texas at 0.10.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson sustained a fractured vertebrae. His spleen was ruptured
and he sustained other internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 20-year-old former two-way all-city player at Houston
Scarborough High School maintains the stance he previously outlined
in that yet-to-be delivered speech, he says he bears no ill will
toward the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have accepted what happened as a turn of life,'' Dickson
said. ``Everybody makes mistakes. I just wish he hadn't made his
when he was drunk. He could have been smarter and gotten a friend
to drive. But him as a person? I don't hold any animosity toward
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people were injured in the chain-reaction, five-car
accident. Approximately 1 million people are injured in
alcohol-related crashes every year in the U.S., according to
statistics from the national office of Mothers Against Drunk
Driving in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   As Dickson _ perhaps fortunately _ nodded off to sleep that
night in the back seat, he might have dreamed of starting spring
practice at Texas in less than two weeks. After a freshman redshirt
season, he was expected to win a place in the secondary rotation at
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to showing my stuff,'' Dickson said with
a smile, the Bible he was reading moments ago folded shut next to a
pillow. ``There were open jobs and I was ready to apply. But then
this happened. My regret is that I never did get a chance to show
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither friends nor family are surprised at Dickson's
magnanimous attitude toward the driver of the other car, nor the
way he has accepted the most-personal tragedy and vowed to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``His attitude is the best I've ever seen in anybody considering
what's happened to him,'' said UT junior linebacker Aaron Humphrey,
one of Dickson's closest friends on the team. ``I'd be in a fit if
it was me. I can't believe how high his hopes are. He is an awesome
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyres has shown miraculous courage,'' said his mother Beverly,
who, though legally blind has raised three sons who are pursuing
college degrees and another who recently graduated from the U.S.
Military Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, he's helped me and I'm a pretty strong person. He's
laid there paralyzed from the chest down and encouraged others.
When other people were crying and didn't know how to approach him,
he's helped them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a tough competitor who was punishing on the field. But
he's unusually sweet, a truly nice guy. This has turned our family
inside out, but we're going to survive. It's a struggle, but we're
used to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson was one of the state's most sought-after athletes as a
senior when he graduated from Scarborough in 1997. An honor
student, he was a starting quarterback and defensive back on a
football team that he led to its first district championship in
1996. Besides being a captain on the football team, he served
similar roles on the basketball and track squads.
</P>
<P>
   Tyres Dickson also cooked for and took care of his mother when
she was stricken with arthritis when he was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't walk,'' Mrs. Dickson said. ``He took care of me. I
love all my sons. But this is my youngest. The one who is very
closest to me in a special way.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the congregation at Christ Holy Temple say as a
teen-ager, Tyres was a driving force in the church's youth program.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the youth in the church look up to Tyres,'' said Mary
White, a longtime church member and family friend. ``He has always
been a very special, a very talented child.''
</P>
<P>
   She often talks to Tyres on the phone _ which frequently rings _
by his hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about him holding on and believing that he will walk
again. He has a lot of faith. He was reared to believe that all
things are possible and he has not given up. I told him _ that if
he believes he will walk again _ I believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Used to setting goals as an athlete, Dickson clings to that
belief. He made remarkable progress in his first stay at the
rehabilitation institute in May and early June before incurring a
serious infection this summer from a bedsore. That setback forced
him back into hospitals for two more operations. He may face six
weeks of inactivity before he can again undertake rehabilitation
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a definite setback,'' Dickson said. ``But I just
think if I take one step back I've got to take three steps forward,
because I've got to stay two steps ahead. I'm going to make it
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his drive, Dickson's physical steps in the future may be
limited, said Dr. Kenneth C. Parsons, who is director of
spinal-cord injury and outpatient clinical services at the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen any meaningful recovery of neurological
function in (Dickson's) legs in the time that we have known him,''
Parsons said. ``I don't make long-range predictions about patients.
But the situation is as it is right now and we don't see any signs
of things changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyres is a fantastic person. I'm sorry he has to be my
patient. But I love being his doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon before the accident, Beverly Dickson said she and
Tyres both took naps. Mrs. Dickson awoke from a dream with a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream was very disturbing,'' she said. ``It was like Tyres
was in trouble or something and I was thinking he was in Austin.
But I woke up and thought there couldn't be anything to this dream
because he's here. I got up and went in and looked at him in his
bed, just to convince myself that everything was all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Stevenson has been a friend of Dickson's since they met on
the first day of school in the sixth grade. Fellow survivors of
neighborhood strife and teammates on various athletic teams since,
they had not seen each other in several months.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevenson had called Dickson and driven in that day from
Prairie View, where he was in college. They ate dinner with two
friends at the home of Stevenson's aunt and later visited another
friend. From there, Dickson called his mother about midnight and
told her he was on his way home.
</P>
<P>
   Confident of his whereabouts with a friend she knew and trusted,
Beverly drifted off to sleep. Tired after a long day and pleasantly
full, Tyres did the same on the way home in the backseat of
Stevenson's car.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is a blessing that neither Ray Stevenson nor Tyres
Dickson remember what happened shortly after Stevenson exited 290
and approached the light at the first intersection, just a couple
of exits down from Scarborough High.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light was green for me,'' Stevenson remembers. ``I started
through, but I never saw the (Suburban) before it ran into us. I
was knocked unconscious, so I don't remember anything that happened
after that and I'm thankful for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suburban slammed into the much-smaller Saturn on the
passenger side. Miraculously, neither of the two occupants on that
side incurred lingering physical injury. Stevenson sustained a
concussion, two broken ribs and a punctured lung.
</P>
<P>
   But the scars and suffering are not only physical when such a
trauma occurs. Stevenson, like Dickson, won't return to college
until the spring semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still trying to get myself straight,'' Stevenson said.
``It was a traumatic experience for all of us and especially for me
_ because Tyres is my best friend and now he's paralyzed and that
hurts me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to going down to Texas this fall to see
him play and I'll never get a chance to do that. But it's hard for
me to even think about. Because I know playing football is
something that Tyres loved doing so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson lived with Scarborough High School government and
economics teacher Leslie Taylor and her family during the spring of
his senior year, after the Dicksons were forced to move from their
old neighborhood to escape gang warfare. The Taylors have remained
close to Tyres.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely something real about Tyres that draws
people to him,'' Taylor said. ``We've spent a lot of time
commiserating about what's happened to him and I think he's finally
come to terms that this is probably a permanent state of being.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also know that he's going to continue to think that he's
going to walk and you can't take away that one shred of hope. When
he was first at (the institute), he went after his rehabilitation
like gangbusters just like he did everything else. That's the way
he's always been _ give me a challenge and I'm going to conquer it.
But I think emotionally and mentally, he's going to have a lot of
work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary White, who has known Dickson since he was a baby,
nevertheless expects remarkable things from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He most definitely will accomplish some things someday,'' she
said. ``He has already touched so many lives just in our church.
And I know he will touch others in the future.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONTRIBUTIONS NEEDED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Tyres Dickson did not have a personal insurance policy
and the other driver's car insurance was insignificant, Dickson's
family faces bills that Beverly Dickson estimates at more than
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two funds have been established to help with both the medical
and personal expenses, which have already enabled the purchase of a
special bed. Donations to defray medical costs can be sent to the
University of Texas, c/o assistant athletic director Ed Goble, P.O.
Box 7399, Austin, 78713-7399.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to the non-medical fund can be sent to The Tyres
Dickson Fund, NationsBank, P.O. Box 620020, Dallas, TX, 75262-0020.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
