<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NJ-TECH-REAL-660&AMP;A     08-22 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NJ-TECH-REAL-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. ADDS TWO FINANCING PROGRAMS TO HI-TECH RECRUITMENT EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RACHELLE GARBARINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey's three-year effort to retain and attract emerging
high-technology companies took a step forward recently with the
start of two financing programs by the state's Economic Development
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   They are the $100 million Technology Funding Program, meant for
growing companies to expand, and the $3 million Seed Capital
Program, intended to help businesses bring new products to the
market. Under both programs, which became available in June,
technology companies can get below-market-rate loans to construct
new buildings, renovate existing buildings or to buy equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Construction also has started on the fifth building at the
Technology Center of New Jersey, the state-sponsored research park
taking shape on 50 acres in North Brunswick. The 60,000-square-foot
structure has been designed for multiple tenants who get the space
for a reasonable price and can expand in place as they grow. The
new building, called Tech II, will join four others now at the
park, which ultimately will comprise up to 800,000 square feet of
office, research and production space.
</P>
<P>
   The state has devised ``a special program that takes a
three-pronged approach'' to nurture the growth of high-technology
business, said Caren Franzini, executive director of the
development authority. The approach, she said, involves promoting
New Jersey as a high-technology state, making real estate available
to companies and now providing financing to them. The authority is
administering the financing programs and, using public and private
funds, is developing the technology center in North Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that these companies can become the Microsofts of
tomorrow,'' said Gualberto Medina, commissioner of the state's
Department of Commerce and Economic Development. ``Creating a
favorable environment is good for these businesses and good
business for the state because it will create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Science and technology-related companies are considered a growth
engine for the state, which ranks seventh in the nation in the
number of high-technology jobs. In 1997, about 168,000 people were
employed in technology-related business, ranging from
telecommunications and electronics to biotechnology and
pharmaceutical concerns, with a total payroll of $9.9 billion,
according to the latest figures available from the federal
Department of Commerce. There were also 145,000 research and
development employees working in 700 laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's appeal to emerging firms in those industries is not
surprising. It is home to such communication giants as AT&AMP;T and its
spinoff Lucent Technology, as well as to the David Sarnoff Research
Center, which conducts electronics research. They provide a strong
resource for the over 5,000 electronics, software and information
technology concerns already in the state.
</P>
<P>
   And its large concentration of drug companies _ including
Bristol-Myers Squibb and Merck, which produce at least 43 percent
of the pharmaceuticals sold in the nation _ serve as a magnet for
the 601 biotechnology, biomedical and health-care related firms
that have sprung up here, says the New Jersey Technology Council, a
Princeton-based nonprofit trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The two recently initiated financing programs are expected to
bridge ``the gaps in the lending market'' faced by these companies,
which private lenders have viewed as risky because they lack the
traditional ``bricks and mortar collateral,'' said Ms. Franzini of
the development authority. The programs are the result of
discussions over the last year among state, industry, banking and
academic leaders, she said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end the authority, using its owns funds, which are
derived from loan origination fees or interest income, will either
provide loans itself, participate in or guarantee a portion of the
loans secured from banks or do both. The programs are expected to
assist 75 to 100 companies over the next few years, Ms. Franzini
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first company to take advantage of the Technology Funding
Program is Price Systems, a software development and licensing
business in Mount Laurel. Last year, the Lockheed Martin Co., its
parent, wanted to sell the company and entertained bidders from
other states that would have moved it out of New Jersey, said
Anthony DeMarco, president of Price.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and three other managers, using a $1.6 million state
loan, purchased the assets of the business in July from Lockheed
Martin. DeMarco said he would increase his New Jersey workforce,
now at 26, by five to 10 employees a year for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the management team was to retain as much equity
and control of the company as possible,'' said DeMarco. Without the
state loan, he said, that would have been difficult to do because
while the company had ``intellectual products, it had few of the
tangible assets'' banks traditionally look for when providing
loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Technology Funding Program, a joint effort of the authority
and six commercial banks, is providing $100,000 to $3 million loans
for up to 10 years to growing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program the bank provides 70 to 75 percent of the loan
at a market rate, and the authority gives the rest at a
below-market fixed rate of 5 to 7 percent. If needed, the authority
will also guarantee up to 50 percent of the bank's loan.
</P>
<P>
   The blended interest rate lowers borrowing costs, Ms. Franzini
said, while the shared financing reduces a bank's risk and
leverages the authority's funds. ``This gives banks the backing we
need to get over the collateral issue,'' and makes the lending
process ``more palatable,'' said Christopher Giamo, a vice
president at Commerce Bank, a lender that was involved in the loan
to Price Systems. He said the program will help stimulate more such
loans.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gov. Christie Whitman also signed a package of bills
into law, effective next Jan. 1, that will offer tax credits and
tax incentives to technology-based businesses to help offset the
costs of research and development. Prime among them is the
technology business tax certificate transfer program, considered to
be the first of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``By freeing up more capital these companies, which live
day-to-day, can breathe a sigh of relief,'' said Debbie Hart,
executive director of the Biotechnology Council of New Jersey, a
Trenton-based nonprofit trade group, referring to the financing
programs. No one incentive is the panacea, she said, but added:
``One-by-one the state is adding more tools to the arsenal to make
it easier for companies to do business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
