<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO LAKE IN TEXAS LIKE CADDO, A PLACE OF MYSTERIOUS BEAUTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCERTAIN, Texas _ Some say Caddo Lake was formed by an
earthquake. Others say it was a big logjam on a nearby river that
forced water into what once was only a swamp. Others say the lake
simply came about before history _ before man really looked back at
his past because the present was so peacefully wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   One thing certain about all the uncertainty, however, is that
Caddo Lake and the surrounding rolling hills and pine forests have
attracted people for a multitude of reasons, from the Kadohadacho
Indians centuries ago to French and Spanish explorers, criminals,
steamboaters, fishermen, hunters and naturalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't another lake like it in Texas,'' camp operator
Gary Kempf said recently as he piloted a flat-bottom boat down a
narrow boat lane not far from Crip's Camp, a neat little fishing
camp Kempf and his wife operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people leave here, what they remember most is the cypress
trees, the lily pads and the Spanish moss,'' Kempf said. ``But
there is a lot of history here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians say Caddo Lake was created by either the New Madrid
Earthquake in 1811-1812 or the Great Raft, a gigantic logjam on the
nearby Red River.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Great Raft and the overflow from the Red River into
what is now known as Caddo Lake probably had the biggest influence
on shaping the lake, there is no argument that the swamplike
features of the several small lakes, canals, sloughs and ditches
were there centuries earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Raft theory for joining the various waterways into one
is the most widely accepted of the two, mainly because the logjam
was reported by explorers long before the New Madrid Earthquake and
also because it is a known fact that it caused major flooding on
both sides of the Red River.
</P>
<P>
   That dispute may never be settled, but anyone who has visited
the lake and its surrounding small towns and communities will agree
that the scenic beauty, the abundance of fish and wildlife, and
historical artifacts and pictures make Caddo Lake a popular place
to fish, hunt and vacation.
</P>
<P>
   More than beauty has attracted people to Caddo Lake, historian
Fred Dahmer notes in his book, ``Caddo Was ...'' However, not all
visitors have come for the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1800s, one area of the lake was so noted for its
racetracks, rooster fights, saloons, brothels and criminal activity
that it boasted of averaging at least one violent death per day,
Dahmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Steamboats also made their way into Caddo Lake history. Pictures
of the old woodburners can be found on the walls of shops and
fishing camps around Caddo Lake and surrounding towns such as
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   A government contractor named Henry Shreve completed destroying
most of the 150-mile long Great Raft in 1833, halting the operation
at a place that bears his name _ Shreveport. Steamboaters not only
made their way to Shreveport but around the Great Raft to the Caddo
Lake bayous and on to Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures of some of the life at Caddo Lake in days of long
ago are among the many attractions anglers, bird watchers and other
visitors find so uniquely interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its historical attractions, Kempf said the biggest
attractions Caddo Lake offers is an abundance of fish and aquatic
vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing generally is good year round, though the average depth
is only 10 to 12 feet in the deepest areas. Largemouth bass, hybrid
striped bass, bream, crappie and catfish are the most popular
species sought by anglers, especially around the moss, cypress
trees and yoncopin.
</P>
<P>
   The yoncopin, which today can be found covering large acres of
shallow or muddy flats on both sides of a boat lane leading from
Crip's Camp to the open waters, actually is an American Lotus, a
lilylike plant that is as rich in interesting facts as it is in its
beautiful yellow flowers that blossom above its bluish-green pads.
</P>
<P>
   People come to Caddo Lake not only to see the acres of pads with
creamy yellow flowers but also come to cut the yoncopin's seed
receptacles only to sell them later as flower decorations, Kempf
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lotus' seeds resemble chinquapins, or acorns, and actually
are edible if they are harvested in their prime _ just before
drying out. It has been said the seeds became a favorite snack of
the Kadohadachos, from which Caddo Lake was named by early
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A law finally has been passed to stop people from cutting the
yoncopins,'' Kemp said, ``and that pretty much put an end to that.
But a lot of people still strip the trees of Spanish moss'' for
decorations.
</P>
<P>
   The lotus is especially abundant today because of a three-foot
low water level and warm summer that has spurred its growth, just
as it has juvenile cypress, a tree whose seeds grow in damp soil
and not in deep water or on dry land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those cypress trees are 350 or more years old,'' Kempf
said, ``and many of the smaller ones are 100 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempf said the location of the biggest cypress trees, ones with
trunks several feet in diameter, are interesting because they
indicate where the water level was many years ago. Because the wind
and current carried the seeds to the banks where they settled into
moist soil, the areas where the largest cypress trees stand today
work as markers, indicating what once was the shoreline of the many
small lakes and sloughs that now are part of Caddo Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Time may have changed something as simple as a name and as
complex as a river, but time has not changed the hauntingly
beautiful maze of trees, aquatic vegetation, and wildlife-rich
waterways of Texas' oldest and largest natural lake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
