New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 8/22/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- NY-BIKER-MOVIESTAR, 8-22 -- Chuck
Zito, president of the New York Nomads chapter of the Hell's Angels
motorcycle club. In his 45 years, Zito has been many things: outlaw
biker, convict, bodyguard to the stars and stunt man. Now, Zito is
trying to leap from macho man to movie star. Last winter, Zito won
his best role yet, a part in ``Oz,'' a prison drama series on HBO
in which he plays an enforcer for a group of Italian inmates. ``I
watch a lot of these actors and say to myself, 'I could do it
better,'''he says. ``They're trying to look like what I really
am.'' (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAGAPONACK, N.Y. -- Aug. 22, 1998 -- NY-BADDREAM-HOUSE,
8-22 -- Land being cleared for Ira Rennert's dream house in
Sagaponack, N.Y. The house will be the largest home in America,
dwarfing the White House and Bill Gates' megamansion. It will have
29 bedrooms, 39 bathrooms, a 164-seat theater and a
restaurant-sized kitchen with five refrigerators. The question
being asked by the Sagaponack Homeowners' Association, which is
challenging Rennert's building permits, is can such a complex be
considered a single-family home? (Lois Raimondo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- NY-MARKET-WATCHING-2, 8-22 -- Carlos Rubino,
a cabdriver, using an electronic stock price checker and laptop
computer connected to the Internet to track the market. Rubino, 41,
is among the many Americans who have become entranced with the
market in the last year. While he never trades with money that he
needs, Rubino has invested in his cousin's restaurant chain in
Denver, called Rodizio Grill, and he hopes to take it public in a
stock offering. ``It's the American dream --why not?'' he says.
``In America, anything can happen.'' (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- NY-MARKET-WATCHING-1, 8-22 -- Mark Candella,
27, a deliveryman for United Parcel Service, checking stock prices
on a Quotrek portable stock quotation machine. He is among the many
Americans who have become entranced with the market in the last
year. Some historians suggest that a number of factors are at work
in today's market popularity, including the growing involvement of
many Americans in the market through the 401(k) and stock-purchase
plans offered by their employers. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 22, 1998 -- CLINTON-LEGACY-2, 8-22 --
President and Mrs. Clinton, returning to the White House, after a
memorial service at Andrews Air Force Base, for the Americans
killed in the bombings at the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya. For
some time, Clinton has hoped that foreign policy, which daunted him
early in his first term, could help redeem him in his second. After
the most tumultuous week of his presidency, capped by a strike on
terrorist outposts, the question that now haunts Clinton is how he
will be judged in light of the Monica Lewinsky matter. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 22, 1998 -- CLINTON-LEGACY-1, 8-22 --
President Clinton during a celebration of the budget agreement on
the South Lawn of the White House in 1997. After the most
tumultuous week of his presidency, capped by a dramatic strike on
terrorist outposts abroad, the question that now haunts Clinton is
how he will be judged in light of the Monica Lewinsky matter. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ATLANTA -- Aug. 22, 1998 -- BBN-WOHLERS-PROFILE, 8-22 --
Mark Wohlers, 28, once the Atlanta Braves' top reliever,
celebrating after the last out in Game 6 of the 1995 World Series.
Wohler, who saved 97 games for Atlanta spanning 1995 and 1997, has
suddenly lost his ability to throw strikes, and has twice been
demoted to the minor leagues this season. His struggle to reclaim
his gift, apparently buried beneath a welter of emotional and
psychological problems, has become a discomforting public drama.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
