A7406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-FAMILIES-NYT &LR;      08-22 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAIROBI VICTIM'S FATHER SAYS CLINTON KEPT PROMISE TO RETALIATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   (bl)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The father of one of the Americans killed in
terrorist bombings in Africa said Saturday that President Clinton
had fulfilled a promise to victims' families with Thursday's
retaliatory strikes against sites in Afghanistan and the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he did it, and I wish he'd do more,'' Kenneth Hobson
Sr., of Lamar, Mo., said Saturday in a telephone interview. ``I was
just surprised it happened so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobson's son, Sgt. Kenneth Hobson Jr., 27, of the Army, a
defense attache's aide at the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, was
one of 12 Americans killed in the bombing there Aug. 7.
Simultaneous car bomb attacks in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, in
neighboring Tanzania, killed 263 people and wounded more than
5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson said that when families of the victims met with Clinton
in Washington, he asked the president to promise him that the
United States would take action when the authorities identified
those responsible. ``I said, `Promise me one thing: When you have
evidence and proof of who did it, that something will be done.
Promise me that you won't just let them go hide in another country
and say that we can't get to them.'''
</P>
<P>
   The father, a decorated Army veteran who served in Vietnam, said
the president replied: `` Hobson, I know my obligations and duties,
and we will take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, he kept his word,'' Hobson said of
the cruise missile strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Hobson, widow of the slain Army sergeant, said in a
separate interview that she wished that there were alternatives to
military action to deter terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't fight terrorism with terrorism, but this is our only
recourse since you can't sit down and negotiate with these
terrorists,'' said Mrs. Hobson, a former Army enlistee who left the
service after the birth of her daughter, Meghan, now 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wish there was another way,'' she said. ``If it means
that no other families have to go through what we have to go
through, then military action is a good idea. But I fear it may
cause more problems, more bombings, and more innocent people being
hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
