<SLUG> BC-STRIKE-BIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FREEZES ASSETS OF BIN LADEN, ALLIES
</HEADLINE>
 LADEN-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced Saturday he had frozen
any assets of Osama bin Laden and his terrorist allies held by US
companies, while the administration said new information shows that
US missile strikes Thursday damaged all six suspected terrorist
camps targeted in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our efforts against terrorism cannot and will not end with
this strike,'' the president said in his weekly radio address. ``We
should have realistic expectations about what a single action can
achieve. And we must be prepared for a long battle.''
</P>
<P>
   He announced that he had signed an executive order authorizing
US officials to freeze assets and to block all financial
transactions between bin Laden and any US company or individual.
The order was signed Thursday, the day the United States fired
missiles on the camps in Afghanistan and a suspected chemical
weapons plant in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton unveiled the new move against bin Laden amid reports of
antiterrorist enforcement actions abroad. In Albania, police
arrested 10 alleged terrorists with possible links to bin Laden. In
Kenya, a newspaper said that three jailed men had confessed to a
role in the US Embassy bombing there.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden is the exiled Saudi multimillionaire who is the chief
suspect in the Aug. 7 bombings at US embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, which killed 12 Americans and 245 Africans. His business
interests range from agricultural and construction companies to
banking and investment firms, US officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials said they did not believe that
much of bin Laden's money is held by US firms, but that the
executive order was a first step in determining the extent of his
holdings and choking his financial support. They said the United
States was urging other nations to freeze bin Laden's assets and
block his financial transactions, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes money, lots of it, to build the network bin Laden
has,'' the president said. ``We'll do our best to see that he has
less of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that an earlier executive order
blocks transactions between US companies and Islamic Jihad, a group
they said is affiliated with bin Laden. Officials said the latest
order is part of a pursuit of bin Laden that includes greater
intelligence collection and possibly more military action.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also said it had received ``somewhat better
visual imagery'' that confirmed its previous assessment that damage
was ``moderate to severe'' at the six camps in Afghanistan, where
bin Laden and his allies were reportedly training terrorists. On
Friday, officials said that cloud cover had hindered spy satellites
from collecting images of the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the six camps sustained some level of damage,'' White
House spokesman Michael D. McCurry said Saturday in Edgartown, on
Martha's Vineyard, where the president is vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton was to meet with the national security adviser,
Samuel R. Berger, on the new assessment. ``I think the president
will hear that we have severely damaged the ability of the Osama
bin Laden network to train and operate from these camps that were
attacked,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   The US attacks included cluster bombs that rained shrapnel on
the camps, Cable News Network reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Kenya, a newspaper reported that three jailed suspects had
confessed to helping plot the US Embassy bombing in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswomen for the FBI and State Department in Washington said
those agencies had no comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, police raided several alleged terrorist safe houses
and arrested 10 foreign nationals. The raids Friday night followed
reports that Albanian intelligence agents and the CIA had launched
a nationwide manhunt for suspects involved in terror attacks in
Egypt, including the November 1997 massacre of 62 people in Luxor.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last week, Clinton said that intelligence agencies
suspected bin Laden's organizations in the attack in Luxor.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Republicans further rallied behind President
Clinton's military strike against bin Laden's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president deserves our support for acting swiftly and
decisively,'' said Senator John McCain of Arizona, in the
Republican response to the president's radio address. But McCain
repeated his earlier criticism that Clinton has failed to bring the
same resolve to ``the many other threats to American security that
have festered from this administration's negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Clinton ``is willing to abandon'' the program of UN
inspections that could deprive Iraq of weapons of mass destruction.
And North Korea is constructing a vast, underground complex for
building nuclear weapons, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Park Police placed concrete barriers around the Washington
Monument Saturday because of heightened security concerns.
Spokesman John Love-land said the monument is among the few major
public memorials that a vehicle can park near. Police also began
checking tourists' bags at the monument.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from Globe wire services was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
