<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS EXPECTED TO MAKE FIRST PUBLIC APPEARANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ In what has been a low-profile vacation,
the Clintons are expected to make their first public appearance
since arriving on Martha's Vineyard when they attend church
services Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Clintons were not among the hundreds of islanders
who gathered at the Union Chapel in Oak Bluffs for a memorial
service for Dorothy West.
</P>
<P>
   West died last week at the age of 91. The influential
African-American writer made the island her year-round home
starting in 1943. One of her best known works, ``The Wedding,'' was
edited by Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, and later Oprah Winfrey
produced the movie version.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday White House press secretary Michael McCurry was asked
how the president and his family were faring during such a
tumultuous time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's working at it, and my guess is that they have
still got work to do,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think there is a healing process that needs to occur,
and as far as I can tell, it's under way, but it's not done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president Saturday was finally in ``vacation
mode'' after returning to the island on Friday. The smaller house
on the 80-acre Oyster Pond estate where the Clintons are staying is
serving as a combination exercise room and office for the
president. The Clintons are staying in the main house on the
property, an antique farmhouse, with access to private beaches and
boating.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it appears that Chelsea Clinton is the only member of
the first family whose vacation is following a familiar pattern.
She has spent several evenings with friends, Stanford College
students who are also vacationing on the island, according to White
House aides.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry suggested that Clinton may play golf Sunday. The
president usually plays a lot of golf when on vacation, often with
Vernon E. Jordan Jr., his close friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan family attended the memorial service for West, and
Harvard University Law School professor Charles Ogletree welcomed
the congregation, sharing his favorite memories of the woman known
as ``the first lady of Oak Bluffs.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton's Vineyard trip this year may be low-profile,
security, as always, is a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Massachusetts State Police arrested a Connecticut man
in New Bedford, after Secret Service agents escorted him off the
island after he was reported to have inquired several times as to
how he could locate the president. Robert E. Ross, 50, also
allegedly told the agents that he had some firearms in his car in
New Bedford. State police retrieved two firearms from his car,
which was parked in New Bedford, according to a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He was arraigned Saturday on two counts of possessing a firearm
without a permit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
