<SLUG> BC-CONGO-AFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AFRICAN NATIONS GETTING INVOLVED IN CONGO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: this story incorporates parts of SAFRICA-CONGO, filed
earlier)  
 (bl)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ In another sign that the civil war in Congo is
mushrooming into a regional conflict pitting African nations
against one another, Angola reportedly joined Zimbabwe on Saturday
in sending troops to Congo to assist President Laurent Kabila's
efforts to repel a rebellion that is believed to be backed by
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Uganda immediately threatened to enter the
conflict if the countries did not withdraw their forces from Congo.
The warning was issued on the same day that a conference to
negotiate a peaceful resolution, led by South African President
Nelson Mandela, failed to begin as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel forces seeking to overthrow Kabila have advanced as
close as 30 miles west of the capital here, according to reports
from the area and Western diplomatic officials in Kinshasa. The
rebels could be in a position to march into Kinshasa before any
serious attempts to arrive at a diplomatic solution get under way,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Pretoria, weekend talks organized by Mandela began poorly
Saturday when a meeting of the main countries involved in the
conflict was postponed until Sunday. Kabila did not go to Pretoria,
and neither did Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe. The heads of
Uganda and Rwanda arrived in Pretoria as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Kabila said Saturday night that he would not attend the
Sunday talks, but that two of his Cabinet ministers already in
Pretoria would stay for the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said that Kabila would remain in the southern city of
Lubumbashi, where he has spent almost all of the last week and from
which he directed the second half of his seven-month war to unseat
his predecessor, the longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni declared that if ``unilateral
intervention intensifies'' in Congo, his country ``may be forced,
after due internal consultations, to take its own independent
action in the protection of its own security interest.'' Uganda and
Rwanda, which backed Kabila's rebellion against Mobutu, have cited
Kabila's failure to secure their common borders as one of the
reasons they no longer support him.
</P>
<P>
   The military intervention by foreign countries has centered in
the area southwest of Kinshasa. In the westernmost region, rebels
told Reuters that they were battling troops and tanks that had
arrived from Angola. In the region just west of Kinshasa, Kabila's
forces have already been joined by several hundred troops from
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Kabila refused to disclose details about the help they
were now receiving, but said it was coming from three countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia said clearly that they were going
to help us, and that's what they are doing,'' said Didier Mumengi,
Kabila's information minister. Dominique Sakombi Inongo, a senior
adviser to Kabila, said Namibian planes had been used to transport
Angolan-supplied arms and other equipment to the region near the
Atlantic Ocean. That report could not be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia belong to the 14-nation Southern
African Development Community, of which Congo is also a member. But
the organization is not united in its policy toward the civil war.
The group's most important member, South Africa, has opposed
military involvement, and the disagreement has led to diplomatic
tensions between South Africa and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda, which are not members, chose Kabila to head a
successful revolt against Mobutu less than two years ago. At first,
Kabila counted ethnic Tutsi Congolese and Rwandan Tutsi among his
closest aides. But Kabila eventually cut himself off from the
Tutsi, who are deeply disliked by other Congolese. Kabila's actions
led to the current 20-day-old rebellion, which is led by ethnic
Tutsi Congolese and also includes former military officials from
Mobutu's army.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda have denied any involvement in the rebellion.
But both nations have strongly denounced countries that have come
to the aid of Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
   In Kinshasa on Saturday, the electricity was turned on and off
repeatedly by the rebels, who control a huge hydroelectric dam
southwest of here on the Congo River.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone at his home Saturday night, Mumengi, the
information minister, began a conversation by saying, ``I'm in the
dark.'' As his children could be heard in the background, he added
that he felt confident that the government forces could push back
any rebel attempts to capture Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very calm here with my children,'' said Mumengi, whose
government has tried to use the power cut to to increase local
residents' anger with the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
