<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-NOSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORCH HASN'T BEEN PASSED IN NHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If Mark McGwire breaks Roger Maris's home run mark (), his
number also should carry a caveat, as in: () _ established in the
era of Triple A pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever seen so many groove jobs? Given this kind of
pitching, Dick Stuart could make a run at Maris, and old Dr.
Strangeglove is 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
   That said, however, watching McGwire's prodigious blasts this
summer has reminded us just how badly the NHL needs a New Man,
someone to capture the audience's attention and imagination at a
time when everyone in the Original 27 looks like so many cast
members from ``Mighty Ducks 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, we are now more than 10 years past Wayne Gretzky being
dealt from Edmonton, and 5-6 years beyond the Great One's prime.
When the end came for Bobby Orr in the mid-'70s (OK, officially it
was the '78-79 seaon, but ... ), Gretzky's arrival in '79 came in a
blink. The segue to Greatness was seemingly seamless.
</P>
<P>
   Between Orr and Gretzky (and Mario Lemieux in the sidecar), the
game had a virtual quarter-century of someone with McGwire-like
stature. Who is that guy now?
</P>
<P>
   Stop the head scratching.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   The segue from Greatness has brought us to a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to be Eric Lindros. Well, L'Enfant Terrible will
turn 26 years old this season. Tempus fugit, big fella. Even Philly
management is finally realizing that it just isn't going to happen.
Oh, the Flyers have tried to make it happen, and they continue to
keep up the beat, with their belief that, if you pay him, he will
come. But six seasons have shown Lindros to be a hunk of potential,
with the occasional awesome display of talent, forever to be
something less than everyone expected. Flyers general manager Bob
Clarke said as much going into the latest round of negotiations,
which was one part posturing and one larger part the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The single greatest talent in the game today is Pittsburgh right
winger Jaromir Jagr. He'll turn 27 this season and has the skill to
dominate the league for the next 4-5 years. He can't be the muscle
that Lindros sometimes is (all too infrequently) but he is
electrifying. He makes the games glow, without the need of Fox
implanting a computer chip in his helmet to make him blur across
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The rule changes approved by the NHL Board of Governors in June,
aimed at opening up the game and limiting clutch-and-grab tactics,
could go a long way in elevating Jagr to The Man status. Some of
the things we don't know: Will the refs make the calls? Will Jagr
remain hungry and healthy? Will the lowest common denominator
prevail, causing teams with lesser talent again to devise defensive
schemes to rub out the likes of Jagr?
</P>
<P>
   If the game goes back to Square One again, then no one is going
to shine, and what we'll be left with is a men's senior league that
asks the public to shell out $50 or $60 to see the Lynn Raiders
grunt it up with the Pembroke Patroons. Get your tickets now.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr isn't alone at the top. There are some other sparkling
talents, such as Paul Kariya, Sergei Fedorov, and Pavel Bure. Teemu
Selanne and Peter Forsberg should be mentioned in the same breath,
somewhere on the cusp of inhale and exhale.
</P>
<P>
   So much is going right for the league now. A new
Disney/ESPN-/ABC television deal is about to be inked. In New York,
commissioner Gary Bettman has assembled a real
marketing-merchandising-advertising machine that understands how to
get the product out there.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, whether any sport truly takes off _ and keeps
soaring _ comes down to the talent of one, two, or three
individuals. We give you Jimmy Connors, Bjorn Borg, and John
McEnroe. Tennis swats on today, but virtually in anonymity. It's
bowling, without the Saturday afternoon time slot. Heck, we give
you Babe Ruth, and to a lesser extent Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   It just takes one guy. An Orr. A Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Batter up.
</P>
<P>
   Who will it be?
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Former Bruin  &UR; John Carter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; his wit as quick as his legs when
he played the Garden, will be behind the bench for Nichols College
(Division 3) this winter, calling the shots as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I helped out with the Woburn High team last year, and I
absolutely loved it,'' said the 35-year-old Carter, whose career
came to a close earlier in the '90s after no fewer than eight eye
operations, his left eye injured while he was playing in a Bruins
intrasquad game at UMass. ``I had a bad stretch there for a while,
but getting back in hockey, I can't tell you how good I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   In a span of 18 months, Carter went through a divorce, surgery
to have his eye permanently removed, and endured his mother's
death. He is now employed as a mental-health worker in a lock-down
unit at a psychiatric hospital, a job he'll keep (third shift)
while he starts down another career path in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I went through with my eye, I'll tell you, I wouldn't
wish that on anyone,'' said Carter. ``I went through absolute hell.
For two years, I couldn't work. I was in agony. The pressure would
build up so much, I'd have to have the eye drained two or three
times a week. Turned out, the best thing to do was to take it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nichols job is a starting place. Late last week, Carter was
working on a dry-land program for his new charges, and he'll meet
with his club for the first time soon after classes begin in
September. Come October, he's back on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a great experience,'' said Carter. ``I'll have to
learn recruiting, all the NCAA rules, but I think it will be great.
When I was playing for  &UR; Kevin Constantine  &LR; in Kansas City (IHL), he
treated me like an assistant coach, and when I was there he said I
should think about coaching when I was done playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I've missed it. I loved playing. I did it almost every
day from the time I was 8 years old. People say it all the time,
but it's one of those things, you really don't appreciate it enough
until it's taken away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Let's not allow Fox to fade from the hockey screen without
giving Uncle Rupert TV credit for at least attempting a different
kick at the puck. To be different in the '90s typically means to be
irreverent, often without any knowledge base to back up the
criticism. Fox didn't poke fun at the game or treat it
disrespectfully. On the plus side, it flooded the arena with more
cameras and dramatically boosted the sound at ice level. Its
mistake was that it took what many of us believe to be a beautiful
sport, one that doesn't need much more than arena organ music as a
backdrop, and tried to jazz it up with glowing pucks and animated,
gun-blasting robots. The attempt made the game look and feel
cartoonish. The viewers were slighted, almost insulted, and it
diminished the work of some very fine broadcasters. After a while,
you expected Goofy and Daffy Duck to be handling the mike. Note to
all American broadcasters: It isn't that difficult. Tune in to a
half-dozen Hockey Night in Canada broadcasts and take it from
there. And don't forget to include the look-at-that-guy-sweat
interviews between the periods. It might not be great TV from a
production sense, but people out here like to see what the players
look like, hear what they have to say. There's a lot to be said for
keeping it simple and allowing the game the space, time, and touch
to sell itself. Fox tried too hard. A for effort. D for impact ...
The feeling around Edmonton is that if Boston University defenseman
 &UR; Tom Poti  &LR; can make a splash immediately, the always
budget-conscious Oilers could look to wheel  &UR; Roman Hamrlik &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the
talented blue liner they picked up late last season from the
Lightning. Now that Tampa Bay is back in the bucks _ with new owner
 &UR; Art Willliams &LR;  _ GM  &UR; Phil Esposito  &LR; would like to get Hamrlik back
in the Bay. Doubtful. Hamrlik will make just shy of $2.5 million
this season and assuredly will look for $4 million-plus with his
next pact. If he lands anywhere for longer than a layover, it will
be in one of those five or six cities where cash is considered only
a mathematic exercise ... And look for  &UR; Marty McSorley  &LR; to return
to the Oil, if the price is right (read: around $700,000 plus
incentives). Always good to have a little extra toughness in camp
... Another BU Terrier, Hobey Baker winner  &UR; Chris Drury &LR; , &UR;  &LR; remains
without a contract. His agent,  &UR; Mark Witkin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has been going back
and forth with Colorado management _ Drury was their fifth pick,
72d overall in '94 _ but as of Friday the numbers didn't match up.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   With less than three weeks remaining until training camp,  &UR; Ted
Donato  &LR; remains a Bruin. Will he be there when the bell rings to
start class? That remains up to the front office. The Bruins have
said they'll try to accommodate Donato's wish to go elsewhere, but
the focus this summer on Causeway Street has been arbitration cases
( &UR; Dmitri Khristich &LR; , &UR; Rob Tallas &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; and primo free agents ( &UR; Jason
Allison &LR; , &UR; Kyle McLaren &LR; ). Donato remains designated for assignment,
which could mean he'll log some time in Wilmington, awaiting the
training camp kinks to work out. He's one of those guys who
virtually every team in the league would want, but not to the point
of giving up much value to get him. Unless packaged correctly
(hello, Khristich?) in a deal that would bring back talent, he's
worth more to Boston than anyone else. But his point is this: If
the coach doesn't want to use him, then he's better elsewhere.
Point well taken, and the front office agrees ... Bure wants out of
Vancouver because, among other things, he receives too much
attention in that city. Don't you love it? A guy negotiates a deal
that will bring him upwards of $8 million this year, but doesn't
understand that there are conditions and responsibilites that go
beyond lacing 'em up for 82 games or more each year. Time to invest
in a dark hat and a pair of sunglasses ... It's almost September
and the Leafs have yet to move netminder  &UR; Felix Potvin &LR; . There are
at least four likely suspects: Canadiens, Canucks, Oilers, and
Panthers. In the meantime, it looks as if Potvin and  &UR; Curtis
Joseph &LR; , &UR;  &LR; signed as a free agent, will be sharing shots at training
camp. Potvin and  &UR; Pat Burns  &LR; can shout to each other from their
lakeside homes on the Quebec/Vermont border. If the Bruins had more
to offer in swap, and especially if they weren't still on the hook
for  &UR; Jim Carey's  &LR; pay ($5 million between now and May 2000), Burns
might be able to think about throwing his pal in the back of his
pickup when he makes the drive down here ... The Bay State's  &UR; Jim
Campbell &LR; , &UR;  &LR; once high on the Bruins' dance card (they opted instead
for  &UR; Glen Murray  &LR; at No. 18 in the '91 draft), will pocket a total
of $1.9 million from the Blues, courtesy of arbitration ... The
trickle-down effect from the new $600 million TV deal for every NHL
team will be around $4 million a year. Today that amounts to a No.
2 or No. 3 defenseman. By the end of the deal, it likely will pay
for a No. 10 or 11 winger. If you're wondering where the rest of
the money will come from, consult the 10 digits that are currently
holding your copy of today's Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
