<HEADLINE>
GORDON IS TEAM-DRIVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The car and driver are a given. To win a race on the
ultra-competitive NASCAR Winston Cup circuit, you cannot do without
one or the other, but those elements have to be supported by a
solid team. In Jeff Gordon's case, his victory in last weekend's
Pepsi 400 at Michigan International Speedway was directly related
to the fine work of his supporting cast, The Rainbow Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   When Gordon pulled his No. 24 Dupont Chevrolet Monte Carlo into
Victory Lane, he appeared to be stunned with the result. After
climbing out of his car, Gordon shrugged and shook his head in
disbelief, as if to say, ``I really don't know how I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   But was there any question, really?
</P>
<P>
   It had everything to do with Gordon's team, which put him in
position to win with rapid work in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crew doesn't give up,'' Gordon said. ``We don't ever give
up until the checkered flag drops.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's eighth victory of the season was also his fourth in a
row, tying Mark Martin (1993), Bill Elliott (1992), Harry Gant
(1991), Dale Earnhardt (1987), Darrell Waltrip (1981), and Cale
Yarborough (1976) for most consecutive victories in NASCAR's modern
era.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, in the Goody's Headache Powder 500 at Bristol,
Tenn., Gordon attempted to become the first to win five in a row.
The reason he was in position to do so has been readily apparent to
his competitors and his teammates in the three-car Hendrick
Motorsports stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our teammate is really on a roll right now,'' said Terry
Labonte, driver of the No. 5 Kellogg's Corn Flakes Chevrolet, who
entered last night's race ninth in the Winston Cup standings,
trailing Gordon by 780. ``We've seen that before with Rusty
Wallace, Darrell Waltrip, and now it's Jeff. They've just got
things figured out. They've got the right setups in the car, and
they unload with the right stuff. They're right when they get to
the track until the time they leave.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, in large part, has to do with the organizational
skills of crew chief Ray Evernham, the self-proclaimed ``chief
worrier of the Rainbow Warriors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a tremendous amount of confidence in my people,''
said Evernham. ``Our sport is like no other. In the NFL, if an
equipment guy puts the wrong cleats on a guy's shoes, he can change
them out real fast. Not in racing. There's virtually no room for
error. The best thing I can do is get the right people in the right
job, then stand back and let them go. If they tell me the car is
ready, I know it's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry McReynolds, who switched to crew chief for Mike Skinner's
No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet after starting the season with Earnhardt's
No. 3 Goodwrench Chevy, said, ``People ask me, what's the 24 car
doing? If I knew, we'd be applying it to the 3 and the 31. I think
the thing they're doing, they have put so many people in place who
specialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got one guy and all he does is look after the aero of
those race cars,'' he added. ``They've got three or four guys and
all they look at is the chassis. They've got specialized people
looking in specialized areas and it's just got every `i' dotted and
every `t' crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, Jeff Gordon is driving with a vengeance on
every lap he's on the racetrack. He and Ray Evernham have a great
rapport with each other, but they've just covered every area down
to the pit crew. They've got a guy and all he does is look after
the pit crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you cover all your areas, it equals what they've done
over the past few years.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Lepage &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 36, of Shelburne, Vt., landed a huge break when
he was tabbed by Winston Cup owner  &UR; Jack Roush  &LR; to fill the seat
vacated by  &UR; Ted Musgrave  &LR; in the No. 16 Prime-star Ford. Lepage, a
veteran of the Busch North circuit who had made a jump up to Busch
Grand National, made his debut in the Roush entry last weekend at
Michigan. Next Sunday in the Country Music Television 300, Lepage
will become the first Vermont driver to start a Winston Cup race at
New Hampshire International Speedway. So what are his goals for the
remainder of his rookie Winston Cup season? ``Obviously, our main
goal _ and as a driver that's my goal every week _ is to go and win
a race,'' he said. ``If I don't feel I can win a race, then there's
no use in becoming a Winston Cup driver. What we need to do, I need
to get up in the top 10 and top five on a week-in-and-week-out
basis. If I can do that, then I think the wins will be right around
the corner.'' ... What happened to  &UR; Ricky Craven &LR; ? The native of
Newburgh, Maine, made a triumphant homecoming to NHIS last month by
winning the pole for the Jiffy Lube 300. It was a stirring moment
for Craven, who was back behind the wheel of his No. 50 Budweiser
Chevrolet after a three-month layoff to recover from postconcussion
syndrome. But, in a move that seemed to suggest he was not yet
fully healed, Craven resigned his ride and was replaced last week
by  &UR; Wally Dallenbach &LR; . In an interview before his NHIS return,
Craven said, ``I've worked 16 years to get to Hendrick Motorsports
and I'm not going to blow it like I almost did at Atlanta,''
referring to his 34th-place finish in the Primestar 500 March 8,
which was hampered by his condition. ``Driving a race car is
something I've done all my life. I've always tried to play hurt.
But that time off showed me you can't fake it when you're hurt;
either you're at 100 percent or you're not.'' ... Winston Cup
driver  &UR; Geoff Bodine  &LR; will bring a taste of the nation's
fastest-growing sport to the national pastime when he throws out
the first pitch at Yankee Stadium Tuesday. Bodine's No. 7 Phillips
Ford will be on display outside the park before the Yankees-Angels
game.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League officials penalized  &UR; Team Menard  &LR; Friday for
violations that were discovered in a postrace inspection at last
weekend's Radisson 200 at Pikes Peak (Colo.) International Raceway.
The IRL fined Team Menard $25,000 and deducted 15 points apiece
from drivers  &UR; Robbie Buhl  &LR; and  &UR; Tony Stewart &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who fell out of the
points lead, after inspections revealed the rear wings of their
cars violated technical specifications. Stewart's deduction left
him in third place with 227 points and vaulted  &UR; Scott Sharp  &LR; from a
9-point deficit to a 1-point lead in IRL standings ahead of
Radisson 200 winner  &UR; Kenny Brack &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 233 to 232. ``After such a
great race at Pikes Peak last Sunday, it's very disappointing this
had to happen,'' said  &UR; Brian Barnhart &LR; , &UR;  &LR; IRL director of racing
operations. ... Despite running out of fuel in Turn 4 of the final
lap, Brack held on for his second IRL victory in a row at Pikes
Peak. Brack held off runner-up Buhl by a margin of 7.542 seconds to
pocket a $112,950 payday ...  &UR; Billy Boat &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who suffered a
fractured left leg and pelvis in a crash June 28 at NHIS, returned
to his  &UR; A.J. Foyt &LR; -prepared car at Pikes Peak and finished ninth
after starting on the pole position. ``We didn't have a ninth-place
race car,'' said Boat, who hobbled around the track on crutches.
``We had a top three-car. For the last few laps, I was just trying
to hang on and salvage a top-five. At least we ran all day. We'll
come back and try to get them at Atlanta (in the Atlanta 500
Classic Saturday).'' ...  &UR; Tom Carey &LR; , &UR;  &LR; of Orange, Mass., will try
to extend his lead over  &UR; Mike Stefanik  &LR; for the Busch North Series
title in next Saturday's CMT Twins 100 at NHIS. Carey will make his
fourth and final appearance of the season at NHIS after posting
second-, third-, and 12th-place finishes in his previous visits.
``I'd like to cap my season with a win (at NHIS),'' said Carey.
``That would prove I can go fast as well as steady, and maybe even
edge  &UR; Dale Shaw  &LR; (of Center Conway, N.H.) for the track
championship.'' ... Fun Ford Weekend will wrap up Sunday at New
England Dragway in Epping, N.H. There will be continuous drag
racing featuring classes of Fast Ford, Quick Ford, Street Ford,
Lightning Pickup, and the 5.0 Showdown series ... A titan of
sportswriting was lost a week ago when  &UR; Jim Murray  &LR; of the Los
Angeles Times died. Although baseball and golf were his biggest
loves, the genial columnist came to embrace auto racing as well. It
was at the Indianapolis 500 that he penned the famous line,
``Gentlemen, start your coffins!'' and where I had the great
fortune to know him by sitting across from him at Indy's media
center for the last 10 years. A true gentleman will be missed.
</P>
</TEXT>
