<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-DURAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD TALE UNFOLDS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roberto Duran says World Boxing Association middleweight
champion Willie Joppy will try to run from him next weekend. He had
best hope so.
</P>
<P>
   The aged Duran will drag his 47-year-old body into the ring at
the Las Vegas Hilton Saturday night to fight one last time for a
world title against a kid who hadn't even been born until Duran was
already 20-0 as a prizefighter.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year difference in their ages doesn't mean as much as it
used to. While Duran has fought everyone, Joppy has fought no one
and still managed to lose once. But this fight is not about who
Joppy is. It is about who Duran is not.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the Duran of 1972, when he savagely battered Ken
Buchanan to win the lightweight title with a 13th-round stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the Duran who defended that title so many times that
he is today considered one of the two best lightweights in history.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the Duran who gave Ray Leonard his first defeat in
1980, winning the welterweight title, or even the one who upset
Davey Moore so gloriously when everyone first thought he was
finished back in '83.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, he is not even the one who defeated Iran Barkley to win
the middleweight title in 1989 when he was already just a shadow of
himself but a glorious shadow.
</P>
<P>
   What he is now is a guy who goes the distance with fighters like
Jacque LeBlanc, loses twice to Vinny Pazienza and to Hector Camacho
and to Jorge Castro, and struggles to survive a preliminary kid
from England named Dave Radford, who was knocked out in one round
in his next fight.
</P>
<P>
   That is the Duran who will fight young Joppy, and even with his
102-13 record and five world titles as impressive baggage, it's
unlikely that Duran can catch this kid. And even if he does, he
might not be able to do anything with him anyway. Not because Joppy
is something special but because Duran no longer is.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fighting style resembles Sugar Ray Leonard's,'' Duran said
of Joppy. ``Running. The first couple of rounds he'll run.
Afterwards, he'll fight.''
</P>
<P>
   If Duran is counting on that, he's dreaming. Joppy (25-1-1)
hasn't knocked out anyone in nearly two years and it's unlikely
he's going to start trying with Duran unless he sees what so many
fear _ that this Duran is a paper tiger, a shell of a legend.
</P>
<P>
   That is what so many fight fans fear and why Duran's longtime
booking agent, Mike Acri, refused to agree to this fight when it
was first proposed. At the time, Acri said, ``I'm not getting Duran
beat by some kid who couldn't have carried his gym bag when he was
Duran for chump change.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, with Panamanian and US tax men chasing Duran,
chump change is enough to keep him fighting. When he fought
Camacho, he made nearly a million dollars _ far more than he will
see Saturday night _ and the IRS took nearly all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has tax attorneys waiting for him in Panama and Las
Vegas, so in the truest sense he does not fight for money now _
because he sees little or none of it. So why then does he go on at
all?
</P>
<P>
   ``It could open the door to bigger and better things,'' Duran
said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, boxing has no bigger or better things for
47-year-old former lightweights who now battle just to get to 160
pounds. It has only beatings and embarrassments, such as the sight
of Radford twice buckling the great Duran's knees with punches that
on another night never would have come close to touching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to see what's coming one night,'' Marvin Hagler
said that night in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   We don't want to see it, but it may be coming whether we watch
or not. And the fact is we will.
</P>
<P>
   We will watch Duran when Showtime turns its cameras on him for
probably the last time because the battering of old champions by
new ones is as much a part of this sport as the glorious nights
Duran had so often.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sad part, but it is the part Duran now plays.
</P>
<P>
   The bit part.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, on this stage, it's also the hit part.
</P>
<P>
   __ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Scionti &LR; , &UR;  &LR; executive director of the Florida State
Athletic Commission, is under fire after lawyers for  &UR; Julio Cesar
Chavez  &LR; charged that his support of a commission rule change
beneficial to promoter  &UR; Don King  &LR; was the result of King's $100,000
donation to a nonprofit organization formed by Scionti last year.
Scionti recommended that the commission reverse a Florida
regulation prohibiting a fighter from being tied exclusively to one
promoter. The commission followed Scionti's recommendation last
Thursday, despite the claim by Chavez's attorney that Scionti was
``in the hip pocket of Mr. King.'' The foundation Scionti formed
was supposed to help boxers continue their education, and he
vehemently denied that he had been bought off by King. He said he
resigned from the foundation when King made his donation but
acknowledged that King's son,  &UR; Carl &LR; , &UR;  &LR; was on the foundation board
with him at the time. Chavez is still fighting to break his
promotional contract with King even as he prepares in Breckenridge,
Colo., for his Sept. 18 rematch with  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya  &LR; in Las
Vegas for rival promoter  &UR; Bob Arum &LR; . King contends he has exclusive
promotional rights to Chavez, a deal that up until Thursday would
have been illegal in Florida ... King got a win of a sorts in his
battle to retain control of International Boxing Federation
welterweight champion  &UR; Felix Trinidad &LR; . On Thursday, US District
Court judge  &UR; Lawrence McKenna  &LR; issued a preliminary order denying
the injunction against King that Trinidad sought. Trinidad recently
signed a promotional deal with  &UR; Dino Duva's  &LR; Main Events company,
claiming his exclusive deal with King had expired and that King had
repeatedly breached the contract. King countered, claiming Trinidad
extended the contract when he signed a bout agreement for a fight
with  &UR; Troy Waters &LR; . McKenna has ordered both sides to appear before
him Monday to consider the possibility of an expedited trial or an
evidentiary hearing ... Worcester welterweight  &UR; Jose Rivera  &LR; lost
his shot at some big-time exposure on HBO Boxing After Dark last
night when a torn ligament in his arm forced him to pull out of a
bout with No. 1-rated junior middleweight  &UR; Fernando Vargas &LR; . Rivera
was replaced by light-hitting  &UR; Darren Maciunski  &LR; (16-5, 6
KOs).Vargas (13-0, 13 KOs) is in line for a shot at IBF 154-pound
champion  &UR; Yory Boy Campas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who must defend his title against
Vargas by December. Vargas's promoters believe Campas may vacate
the title if he appears to be in line for a shot at big money
against De La Hoya by the end of the year. If not, Campas-Vargas
could end up as the second half of a Nov. 14 HBO mega-show with
Trinidad in against World Boxing Association titleholder  &UR; Ike
Quartey  &LR; if he can extricate himself from King. For that to happen,
however, it's likely that Quartey would have to either give up the
WBA title or have it stripped from him for refusing to fight his
mandatory challenger,  &UR; Andrei Pastriev &LR; . Their recently scheduled
fight was canceled when Quartey claimed he caught malaria whie
training in Ghana. Fact is, he feared both death threats and the
warning of his former French promoters that they could not
guarantee his safety if he came to France to fight without them.
</P>
</TEXT>
