<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JACK' HAS GOT IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Stadium Envy. That's what I've got.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sitting in the cushy, air-conditioned press box at
one-year-old Jack Kent Cooke Stadium. I'm looking out at the
state-of-the-art football theater. It's got real grass, 80,116
seats with perfect sightlines, Crayola-clear scoreboards, 23,000
parking spaces, 1,100 televisions, a sound system that satisfied
Mick Jagger, and 199 luxury boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad Massachusetts House Speaker Thomas Finneran couldn't be
here to see this. The Jack was privately financed (to the tune of
$175 million) by the late Jack Kent Cooke, but he got help in the
form of $70.5 million from the state of Maryland for infrastructure
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? The inimitable Bob (now Robert, for some strange
reason) Kraft offered to build his own stadium in Foxborough, but
wanted 72 million tax dollars for infrastructure, which included a
$20 million purchase of land for the stadium that the Patriots
would lease back to the state for an annual payment of $2.5
million. Kraft's plan was rejected by the Massachusetts House.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Patriots are condemned to an endless string of
seasons in Foxborough _ the Levittown of American stadia.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots brought their preseason show to Greater Washington
last night. In the wake of new terrorist threats, there was extra
security at National Airport and several Patriots players noticed
the new lines of defense when they took a White House tour Friday
afternoon. There was additional security around Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   New England players, media, and road-tripping fans could only
look at the new facility and drool. The Jack is beautiful. It's the
NFL's largest open-air stadium and the first built with private
funds since Joe Robbie Stadium (now Pro Player Stadium) went up in
1987. The Jack was built in 18 months and designed by HOK Inc., the
same folks who planned Camden Yards, Jacobs Field, and Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Drawbacks? The Jack is not in downtown Washington ($30 by cab),
and is not on a metro line. It's also expensive, with an average
general-admission ticket exceeding $52, but this deters few. The
Redskins have sold out 237 consecutive games and there are 40,000
on the waiting list for season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke was 74 when he started trying to get out of old RFK
Stadium downtown and it took 10 years to find a site and fix the
financing. Like Kraft, he talked with officials from every part of
the region. Kraft works Massachusetts vs. Providence and Hartford.
Cooke at various times signed agreements with Virginia, Maryland,
and the District of Columbia. To his credit, Cooke never threatened
to take the Redskins to another part of the country. Sadly, he died
five months before the new stadium opened.
</P>
<P>
   There are 2,527 plumbing fixtures at the Jack (I didn't count
them myself; it's in the press guide). Something tells me Foxboro
Stadium doesn't have as many toilets and sinks. The Jack's got 12
miles of handrails and 52,000 gallons of new paint. Not content
with last year's sparkling success, the Redskins dumped another $25
million into stadium improvements for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   The Jack was built on 300 acres that used to be called Wilson
Farm. There was resistance from some Landover neighbors, but the
county council favored the economic windfall. Cooke, who had an ego
even bigger than Kraft's, went so far as to get the postal service
to recognize the stadium land as Raljon, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Raljon has no residents. The word is a merge of the names of
Cooke's two sons, Ralph and John. Yeesh. And we think Kraft has an
ego.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, New England had better watch out. If Kraft
ever builds a stadium, maybe he'll be tempted to do what Cooke did
and create his own town _ Jondandavidjosh, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of catchy, don't you think?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
