<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ORIOLES-ONTHEMOVE     08-22 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-ONTHEMOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BIRD-WATCHING SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BALTIMORE _ Close your eyes and picture this. A huge crowd
overflowing Camden Yards. Happy, happy faces. Fans doing the wave
with a passion usually reserved for Baltimore Ravens games a block
away. People having a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Inhale the smells and hear the sounds. Look for little Orioles
everywhere, yelling and singing about their heroes, past and
present: Jim Palmer, Brooks Robinson, Cal Ripken, and now Eric
Davis, who inspires people every time he takes to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Now, open your eyes and see the reality of Birdland. It is no
illusion. There are the Baltimore Orioles, who long ago seemed to
fall out of contention for a playoff spot, in third place in the
American League East and closing. They are a traditional power,
with a $70 million payroll, and their loyal fans believe they can
catch the Red Sox for the AL wild-card spot, even though the
deficit stood at eight games entering Saturday's play.
</P>
<P>
   After an injury-plagued, 38-50 first half, the Orioles have
gotten themselves together, winning 31 of 41 games after the
All-Star break and erasing half of a 15 1/2-game deficit. But there
is still a long way to go; the Orioles close the season with two
games against New York, three in Toronto and four in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is mostly healthy,'' says first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro. ``After the break, everybody decided to leave nothing out
on the field. Don't leave anything in the clubhouse. Have fun and
play the game. Once we did that, things started to happen. We
started saying that during the last Red Sox series. We went all out
and we swept them, and that's what gave us life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really almost like what happened to us in 1996,'' says
left fielder B.J. Surhoff, recalling how the Orioles overcame an
early-season deficit that year to win 98 games and take the
wild-card berth. ``We struggled for a long time after a good start
because of some injuries to our pitching staff. When we started to
get some people back, things started to come around a little bit
and we made the playoffs. That's about what has happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is any doubt that the AL East is the toughest division
in baseball, consider that the Yankees, Red Sox, and Orioles could
finish with the top three records in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Depleted roster
</P>
<P>
   What a season it has been for the Orioles, who lost their Nos.
1, 3, and 4 pitchers for a total of 30 starts. Mike Mussina (six
missed starts), Scott Kamieniecki (12), and Jimmy Key (12) all have
been on the disabled list. Doug Drabek, the fifth starter, is there
now. The Orioles started the season 10-2 but soon came back to the
pack before collapsing with a nine-game losing streak in May as the
Yankees blew past them.
</P>
<P>
   While the sight of Davis, who has recovered from colon cancer,
has been heartwarming, there has been much ugliness associated with
the Orioles' season. On May 14, Mussina nearly lost an eye when he
was hit in the face by a line drive off the bat of Cleveland's
Sandy Alomar. Key has battled shoulder problems and is currently
working out of the bullpen. Reliever Arthur Rhodes strained his
elbow and missed an entire month. Outfielder Brady Anderson banged
up a knee last Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   And of course there was the infamous brawl in Yankee Stadium in
mid May that resulted in suspensions for the 1-2 bullpen punch of
Alan Mills (two games) and Armando Benitez (eight games). Manager
Ray Miller had to go to a bullpen by committee, one that includes
41-year-old Jesse Orosco, and it has worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes relievers and starters,'' said Miller. ``We lost
three starters and without them called upon 7-8 pitchers who might
have had one-inning roles. That meant you didn't have them for a
few days, which takes you out of the pitching sequence for the next
day. If that's what you have to do, that's what you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up going through two months of bringing in the best
available guy, regardless of left or right, instead of putting
people where they can flourish. Since the break, the starting
pitching has been good. We're bringing in people where we were
supposed to and they are doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, whose connections as pitching coach go back to
Baltimore's glory days of the '70s and '80s. He knew he was in a
high-risk position succeeding Dave Johnson, who led Baltimore to 98
victories in 1996 and 1997 and got fired after being named manager
of the year last season. The pressure didn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the job,'' says Miller, ``because I was afraid that
what we had here would be given to somebody else. I know how good
an organization we have. Davey did a good job of getting us back to
thinking the Orioles way _ good baseball fundamentals and getting
away from gimmick stuff. Just plain good baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take away a No. 1, 3, and 4 starter, as well as two
more pitchers, then you're going to get the heck kicked out of you.
It was fun for those two weeks, we had just eight pitchers, only
one of which was a veteran starter (Scott Erickson), playing all
those interleague games with no lefthanders in the bullpen; no
Harold Baines, no Robbie Alomar for 15 days. We worked our tails
off to hang in there. A lot of credit should go to (pitching coach)
Mike Flanagan, who worked harder for two months than I did over the
previous two years.''
</P>
<P>
   In his shuffling of pitchers, Miller thinks he may have saved
his bullpen for the stretch run and along the way found a valuable
starter in Sidney Ponson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stuck with the kids,'' he said. ``As a team, we went back
to the Orioles way of pushing people who have good years, finding
out who can play baseball or who can't, and rewarding those
people.''
</P>
<P>
   How will it end?
</P>
<P>
   The strong second half has silenced the criticism of Miller and
his veteran team. A 30-game hitting streak by Davis restored some
magic to Camden Yards. Another boost was acquiring righthander Juan
Guzman from the Blue Jays. How long can this run last? You never
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, you'd like to set up your team in a 162-game
season,'' says Ripken. ``But because of injuries, our team wasn't
as strong as we'd like it. But we have the nucleus of a very good
team. Now that we've got everybody in their roles, it's good to see
visible signs of us winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came to the Orioles, we were a very good team.
Then we went through a very difficult rebuilding process when we
weren't that good. Now, we've come back to the talent that can give
us a chance to win by the end of the year. That's all that anyone
can ask.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be all right,'' says Miller. ``We have a steep
hill to climb, but we've come a long way. Before I took the job, I
read about a bunch of high-priced egos. That's wrong. We have a
great bunch of guys on this club. Excellent baseball players.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they are a veteran team, says catcher Lenny Webster, the
Orioles are not going to lose their poise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody in this clubhouse let anybody get down
on themselves in the first half,'' says Webster. ``It's just
understanding the game and how nature takes its course when you're
out there battling your butt and trying to win a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like that Murphy's Law thing hit us. Anything that
could go wrong went wrong. We knew that it was a long season and we
had a second half to play. If we play the way that we are capable,
we'd be able to make a run at the wild card.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
