<HEADLINE>
SENIOR'S MELE GRADUATING TO PGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD _ Peter Mele is a child of New England _ of Everett,
Waltham, Weston, and Raynham. He is an alumnus of Wake Forest, in
the same class as Scott Hoch and a year behind Curtis Strange. He
has been tournament director of the BankBoston Senior PGA Tour
event at Nashawtuc CC since 1988, and his involvement began four
years earlier. He approaches this week's tournament, which begins
Friday, with some nostalgia, because he is about to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   Mele will become tournament director for the PGA Tour's Buick
Classic at Westchester Country Club in Rye, N.Y. As he, wife
Barbara, daughter Lori, and son Peter Jr. prepare to move to
Southbury, Conn., Mele has been ensconced in organizing the senior
event, with its three pro-ams Monday, Wednesday, and Thursday
preceding Friday's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely mixed feelings,'' said Mele Thursday. ``It's
tough. I've been trying to figure out how to handle this over the
next 10 days. It's definitely going to be difficult. It's very
emotional. We've made so many friends here. We've got so many
memories. It all happened so suddenly nobody really had time to
think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity was too good. Everything was being held up
because of the GM strike affecting Buick. I'm going to an event
that's been around. Working for the PGA Tour has had an appeal to
me. It's such a great company to work with, and I know so many
people at headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the attraction is the fact that the PGA Tour is in the
midst of a major transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got so many things going on with the world golf
championships,'' said Mele. ``They're really in an expansion mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only part that's been difficult is the whole idea of
moving out of the area. We live in Raynham. The kids love the
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The BankBoston field is just about as good as it can be. It
features defender Hale Irwin, who won the US Senior Open at Riviera
and is golf's leading money-winner this year ($2,101,750 on the
Senior Tour), plus Isao Aoki, Jay Sigel, David Graham, Graham
Marsh, Dave Stockton, Lee Trevino, Bob Murphy, George Archer, and
Dana Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Nashawtuc is in fine shape despite flooding from the
Sudbury River in late June. Course superintendent Paul Miller and
his staff have done a remarkable job in getting the course ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of June and the first week of July, we were still
under water,'' said Miller. ``The middle of 1. The whole eighth
fairway. The landing area on the ninth fairway. The rough all
around 16 was completely dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used bent grass and rye, about 200 pounds an acre of both.
We cut seed in at two or three different angles. We had 15 inches
of rain in the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This damage couldn't have been much more severe.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Great sportswriter  &UR; Jim Murray &LR; , who died a week ago in Los
Angeles, loved golf. One of his columns concerned a relatively
obscure pro named  &UR; Ken Still  &LR; out of Tacoma, who qualified for the
1969 US Ryder Cup team. Murray wrote that the only time Still ever
saw his name in headlines was when San Francisco native  &UR; Ken
Ventura  &LR; led the 1966 US Open for the second straight day at the
Olympic Club and one of the hometown papers said, ``Ken still leads
Open.'' This reporter rode with Murray to this year's Open, which
he was covering for the fourth time at Olympic Club, and we had a
laugh over Mark Twain's remark that the coldest winter he ever
spent was a summer in San Francisco ... The Golf Skills Challenge
is seeking volunteers for its annual event (Aug. 28-30) at
Wedgewood Pines GC in Stow. Volunteers will receive lunch and an
opportunity to participate in the event free. If interested, call
the NEPGA (508) 869-0000 ... The NEPGA Pro-Am Championship that was
washed out in June will be played over 36 holes Tuesday at Andover
and Indian Ridge Country Clubs ... The New England Open at The
Quechee Club (Sept. 15-17) has pro-am openings for amateurs and
professionals not in the NEPGA but working full-time within New
England. The deadline is Aug. 31. Call (802) 295-6245 ... There are
a record number of applications (290) for the Massachusetts Golf
Association's Mid Amateur Championship at Nashawtuc (Sept. 22-23),
with just 200 spots available ... The first half of the MGA's team
for the Tri State matches involving teams from Connecticut and
Rhode Island has been selected. Ouimet winner  &UR; Frank Vana Jr. &LR; , &UR; Jon
Fasick &LR; , &UR; Jim Ruschioni &LR; , &UR; Kevin Quinn &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Ed Fletcher  &LR; will be
part of the Bay State contingent, which has won the past two years
...  &UR; Allen Doyle  &LR; out of Norwood, the oldest player to qualify for
the PGA Tour at 47, recently turned 50 and was granted one of four
sponsor's exemptions to the Senior event at Nashawtuc. The
remaining three spots were given to former Tufts athlete  &UR; Dan
Woods &LR; , &UR; Homero Blancas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Ed Dougherty &LR; . Doyle, who turned 50
July 26 while playing in the CVS Charity Classic at Pleasant Valley
CC, was a Monday qualifier for the Senior event in Coon Rapids,
Minn. He had a 5-1 record in three Walker Cup matches, won the
celebrated Sunnehanna Amateur four times, and decided to go pro.
Now he's 50, and life begins at 50, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
