<HEADLINE>
BONUS PUTS AN ONUS ON KRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Ted Johnson was sweeping a pen across his new $25 million,
five-year contract extension last week during a press conference at
Foxboro Stadium, Patriots owner Bob Kraft was one floor below,
staring almost incredulously at a computer printout that listed his
team's signing-bonus obligations.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of a long list of names _ topped by the $8 million
Kraft committed to Johnson this week _ was a figure in bold type.
</P>
<P>
   That figure was $35,688,000.
</P>
<P>
   It is a big number, even for a guy who spends most of his waking
hours around big numbers. For the long-term future of the Patriots,
it was the kind of number Kraft believes he can't keep writing if
something doesn't change soon with his stalled stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's reasoning is simple economics, the stuff he was taught
years ago at Harvard Business School, the same stuff taught to his
eldest son, Jonathan, a generation later:
</P>
<P>
   You don't spend more than you take in every year, because if you
do, one year they'll be taking you out. In a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   With the signing of Johnson, the Patriots have now committed the
triangle of their defensive front _ Johnson, Chris Slade, and
Willie McGinest _ to long-term deals that give head coach Pete
Carroll people to build around for the future. But with a total of
$35,688,000 in signing-bonus commitments this season and no
commitment from anyone to help him with a new stadium project,
Kraft sees his own future differently, and what he sees is not
good.
</P>
<P>
   The need to continue paying such bonuses is the driving force
behind Kraft's search for a new stadium that will provide him a
revenue stream he believes can keep his team competitive. Without
it, he feels, he will be unable to continue paying the up-front
money needed to sign top free agents, including his own, and his
team will slowly sink into mediocrity. That, not Foxborough, is
what he fears getting stuck in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be in the NFL if I can't be competitive, and
the fact is I can't keep taking capital we can't generate and
spending it to keep the team competitive,'' Kraft said. ``We're
socialists in this league. We share all the revenue the same. The
only way to differentiate is stadium income. The fact of the matter
is simple. I can't keep infusing capital into this business knowing
this gap will get bigger and bigger if things stay the way they
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way the team stays competitive is if you do that, and
it takes cash to sign these guys. I think some people have missed
the point in this. Having a new stadium isn't about me making
money. I already make a lot of money in my real businesses. A new
stadium is about the team remaining competitive in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hugh Culverhouse, when he owned the Buccaneers, made more
money than anybody else because his teams were seldom competitive.
If I wanted to make some money at this, I'd be better off
financially to be 8-8 every year. Frankly, you go to the
championship game or the Super Bowl and you lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd as that may sound, it has been backed up in the past by
people such as Eddie DeBartolo, who experienced it over and over
again in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Even the kind of guy who would use public money to finance a
minor league baseball park in Lowell but deny it for a major league
team in Boston (say, a guy like Tom Finneran) must understand that
NFL owners could make more taking the money they invest in pro
football and putting it into a real business. They could make more
investing in real estate or any other real business that runs like
a real business, one in which you don't hand over 60 percent of the
gross to the employees and pay millions to kids for what they may
do rather than for what they've done.
</P>
<P>
   So the theory that Kraft wants a stadium to get rich is as
specious as saying everything he does is an act of Christian
charity. As Finneran pointed out in his politically incorrect and
rather blunt way, Kraft is already rich. He needs football to eat
off like he needs another community meeting in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's desire for a public/private stadium partnership is as
simple as the economics staring him in the face at the bottom of
that computer printout.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't like to own a loser, his fans don't like to watch a
loser, and the area doesn't like to hear about losers. Nearly
everybody, sports nut or not, is energized by a winning team, but
only one guy _ in this case Kraft _ has to pay for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been willing to commit to this (bonus structure) because
I always felt we could get a stadium here,'' Kraft said. ``I still
hope we can. But you can't keep spending your capital like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you move to a place such as Los Angeles,
where Kraft would make more capital in a week than a new stadium in
New England would net him in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The supposition in these parts is that if Kraft goes, he goes to
Providence or at worst Hartford, although he does not have a deal
from either yet. That's what Finneran is betting on and what most
pundits expect.
</P>
<P>
   But just 5 1/2 hours away by plane lies a gold mine for someone.
Bob Kraft knows that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One week  &UR; Glenn Foley  &LR; is the Jets' starting quarterback. The
next week he's told by his boss,  &UR; Bill Parcells &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``You're the
other guy now.'' He takes that to mean he's  &UR; Neil O'Donnell &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the
guy he replaced last season. But when  &UR; Vinny Testaverde  &LR; got the
next start, he opened his career with the Jets in the way much of
his 11 years in the NFL have gone. He threw an interception and his
team lost, 33-0. Just like that, Parcells was saying last week that
Foley was his guy all along, blaming the New York media for
inventing a quarterback controversy where, of course, none existed
anywhere but in their twisted minds. Regardless of Parcells's
wavering, Foley is now the guy again, after going 14 of 22 for 192
yards and a touchdown against the Giants Thursday night. Prior to
that game, he was a dismal 11 for 28 with two interceptions and had
shown little of the fire he exhibited by completing 14 straight
against the Patriots in a game last season that began O'Donnell's
demise. If that Foley does not reappear this season, the Jets will
go nowhere and Parcells knows it _ with or without  &UR; Curtis Martin
 &LR; running full steam ahead, as he appeared to be doing Thursday
night. That is why Parcells reminded Foley and everyone else last
week, ``They play until I don't want them to play anymore.'' This
led someone to ask Parcells whether the uncertainty was making
Foley ill at ease. Obviously, the questioner didn't know much about
Parcells. ``I'm not worried about being at ease,'' Parcells
snapped. ``I'm not at ease. How the hell can he be at ease? What is
this, a mental health clinic?'' Considering that Testaverde's
winning percentage in 132 career starts is .367, second-lowest
among active quarterbacks, many in New York will be ill at ease if
Foley doesn't prove to be the guy Parcells thought he was ... The
Patriots are one of nine teams facing possible travel problems
because of an impending pilots strike against Northwest Airlines
that could begin next weekend if a deal isn't struck. The Patriots,
who charter their flights from Northwest, are now planning a
contingency in which they would lease the equipment from Northwest
and hire an outside charter service to operate the plane until the
strike is over.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the seven groups seeking the NFL's expansion
franchise in Cleveland made presentations at a brief owners meeting
in Atlanta last week, but none delivered their financial packages.
The bids remained under seal in New York at the investment firm
Goldman Sachs, but all seven had been judged to have made a minimum
bid high enough to allow them to address the owners. An Expansion
Committee of seven owners will work with Goldman Sachs to reduce
the candidates to 2-4 finalists. They will then present to the 30
owners their final bids, which can be submitted as late as Sept. 7,
the night before a scheduled final vote. Kraft is on the Expansion
Committee and said, ``The numbers are pretty important, but it's
possible that the highest bidder won't get it. Regardless, we'll be
selling the franchise for the highest price ever paid in sports.''
Kraft said the decision to bring in Goldman Sachs was one he
supported because of his own experience when he bought the Patriots
in 1994. ``They sold me the team and did a heck of a job,'' he
said. Although one of the bidders,  &UR; Al Lerner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has a close
relationship with top Goldman Sachs executives, Kraft said, ``Five
of the seven guys involved in these proposals know the people
there, so that's not a problem.'' Kraft went on to praise
commissioner  &UR; Paul Tagliabue's  &LR; handling of the situation in
Cleveland saying, ``He took a situation that was horrible because
in the end there was a deadlock between the ownership of the Browns
and the political people there. They had the best fan base in the
league outside our own, and now to come back to Cleveland with a
state-of-the-art stadium he had to pull off a public/private
partnership and he did. It couldn't be done here, I don't think.
Over the next 10 years, the NFL will be bringing a billion in
revenue into Cleveland that wouldn't otherwise be there through
national sponsorships and TV revenue and taxes. If, in the end, we
go 3,000 miles from here, that's where that revenue will go. The
political people in Cleveland understood that.'' Expansion
franchises in Carolina and Jacksonville went for $140 million in
1993, Kraft bought the Patriots for $160 million, and last week
 &UR; Red McCombs's  &LR; $250 million offer to buy the Vikings was accepted.
Numbers from $400 million to $1 billion have been thrown around as
the cost of the Cleveland franchise. McCombs says the whole thing
is a mystery: ``Nobody knows what these things are really worth.''
... Among the seven Cleveland bidders was Bruins owner  &UR; Jeremy
Jacobs &LR; , who said he did not believe cross-ownership is a problem
and stated flatly that he would not sell the Bruins to obtain the
Browns. Jacobs is not the only NHL owner in the hunt.  &UR; Howard
Milstein &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who owns 45 percent of the New York Islanders, heads a
group that includes former NFL stars  &UR; Paul Warfield  &LR; and  &UR; Calvin
Hill &LR; . Another bidder,  &UR; Richard Jacobs &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who owns the Cleveland
Indians, made some points simply by using only 15 of his alloted 30
minutes to make his pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Things are flush in the NFL, as Fox is learning. The television
network is asking for and getting $1.6 million for a 30-second spot
on its Super Bowl broadcast next January. That is a 23 percent
increase on what NBC charged last season and partially the result
of NBC getting $1.7 million a spot for its ads on the final episode
of ``Seinfeld.'' Fox is arguing that ``Seinfeld'' did a 41.3 rating
while last year's Super Bowl did a 44.5 ...  &UR; Ironhead Heyward
 &LR; begged the St. Louis Rams to release him but head coach  &UR; Dick
Vermeil  &LR; has thus far refused and sources say he will stand his
ground at least until Heyward reports to training camp. The bulky
fullback was told to be at 260 pounds this summer but was so far
off that he refused to come into camp and is being fined $5,000 a
day. To date, that totals $145,000 and his continued absence could
jeopardize the four-year, $4.5 million contract he signed just two
years ago. Heyward, who has struggled with his weight throughout
his career, is said to be offended both by Vermeil's harsh
practices and his harsh words. Earlier this summer, Vermeil
suggested Heyward ``cut the teeth off his fork,'' after the
fullback showed up for a mini-camp at nearly 300 pounds. On Friday,
Heyward told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch to tell Vermeil ``let me
go, please. Put the emphasis on the word please.'' Judging by
Vermeil's response, that didn't seem to change his position.
``You've got to sell a lot of Zest to make his kind of money,''
Vermeil said. Heyward has done several television ads for that soap
... On the same day that McCombs's purchase of the Vikings closed,
club president  &UR; Roger Headrick  &LR; quietly resigned. Present club vice
president  &UR; Jeff Diamond &LR;  is believed to be in line to take over the
day-to-day operation. Diamond negotiated most of the big-money
deals the Vikings made this offseason with their top players. When
McCombs's bid was accepted, one of the first things he did was go
into the locker room at training camp and ask wide recevier  &UR; Cris
Carter  &LR; to stand up. ``I want to see what my money looks like,''
McCombs told Carter, whom the Vikings made the highest-paid
receiver ... But Carter won't have the distinction for long. The
Lions are trying to iron out details with the league to get cap
approval for a contract extension that will make  &UR; Herman Moore  &LR; the
highest-paid receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs may be one of the favorites to win the AFC title but
they're looking a little desperate as they pursue troubled running
back  &UR; Lawrence Phillips &LR; . &UR;  &LR; The Chiefs began negotiations with
Phillips's agent last week in large part because of the lackluster
play of  &UR; Donnell Bennett &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whom they shifted from fullback to
replace the retired  &UR; Marcus Allen  &LR; and the departed  &UR; Greg Hill &LR; .
Coach  &UR; Marty Schottenheimer  &LR; wants to meet with Phillips, who has
already been released by the Rams and Dolphins only three years
after St. Louis made him the sixth player taken in the draft ...
With defensive tackle  &UR; Tim Bowens  &LR; accepting the Dolphins' one-year
tender offer of $2.88 million after being tagged as their franchise
player, there are now four franchise players holding out. The
Redskins are trying to land one of them, New Orleans defensive end
 &UR; Joe Johnson &LR; . Washington offered New Orleans a first- and a
third-round pick Wednesday but the Saints rejected the offer.
Washington also has spoken with the Chiefs about another franchise
holdout, defensive end  &UR; Dan Williams &LR; . Washington has a major need
now that  &UR; Dan Owens  &LR; has been lost for the season with a knee
injury ... Johnson, by the way, already rejected both a $3.08
million tender offer for this season and a five-year deal worth
$21.125 million that includes a $6 million signing bonus and a base
salary of $2.6 million this season ... It's not often an offensive
lineman gets noticed for anything but allowing a sack, but that's
not the case with Jacksonville tackle  &UR; Tony Boselli &LR; . &UR;  &LR;  McDonald's
restaurants in northern Florida and southern Georgia are selling a
$1.99 ``Boselli burger'' that contains three patties, American and
Monterey Jack cheese, mayo, lettuce, tomato, and onion.
</P>
</TEXT>
