<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS TAKE PLAYOFF OPENER IN DEFENSE OF WNBA TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDDY LANDRETH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The format for the Women's National Basketball
Association playoffs may have changed, but the defending champion
Houston Comets looked the same Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which won the league's single-elimination tournament
last season, got 27 points from Cynthia Cooper and a strong effort
from its interior defense Saturday to defeat the Charlotte Sting by
85-71 in the opener of a two-of-three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets can eliminate Charlotte with a victory Monday night
in Houston. If a third game is necessary, it will be played Tuesday
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to go back home and close it out in two games,''
said forward Sheryl Swoopes, who had 17 points and 8 rebounds
Saturday. ``That will give us a little more time to rest. I can
heal. Cynthia can heal. Kim can heal. The entire team can heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper and Swoopes had ice bags on sore knees after the game,
while Kim Perrot walked in for the post-game interviews with ice on
a sprained right ankle that had threatened to keep her out of the
game. She injured the ankle in the final regular-season game,
against Los Angeles on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about as bad as you'll ever see on Wednesday night,''
Houston Coach Van Chancellor said. ``I would have bet anything I
had that she wouldn't have played a minute today.''
</P>
<P>
   She actually played 38 minutes, tying Tina Thompson for the most
on the team. Perrot was 5 of 8 from the field, had 6 assists and 3
steals, and directed a Houston offense that started the game from
the perimeter and finished it in fast-break form.
</P>
<P>
   Her performance left Charlotte coach Marynell Meadors wondering
whether Houston had found a miracle cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Perrot is hurt,'' Meadors said. ``If she did
sprain an ankle, I would like to know what kind of medication they
used to get her back. I didn't see any difference in her play.''
</P>
<P>
   Meadors' pain came from watching her team's perimeter game. When
the Sting got to the basket on fast breaks, it could score.
Otherwise, it was a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte shot 15.4 percent (2-13) from 3-point range. Houston
did not sizzle from there, but the Comets shot well enough (6 of
24) to open the court for its running game.
</P>
<P>
   That enabled Houston to shoot 52.5 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Yolanda Moore's defense that made the difference.
Charlotte's Ronda Mapp made 7 of 10 field goals and scored 16
points, but it would have been much more without Moore's efforts,
Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking Yolanda Moore is not big enough to guard Ronda
Mapp,'' Chancellor said. ``But every time we made that switch, she
did a good job of denying her the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's other inside players bothered Charlotte throughout the
game when the Sting tried to power the ball to the basket. And the
Comets' 35-20 rebounding advantage made a big difference late in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the stretch, the Charlotte Sting did not rebound the ball
well enough to stop their runs,'' Meadors said. ``It seemed like we
were in a position all the time of having to fight from behind. Had
we got the lead, we would have played a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Comets have made a strong first step in the search of
their second straight title. Chancellor said he did not change his
approach because of the new format, but he conceded he felt a lot
more pressure having to start this series on Charlotte's home
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go on the road for a first game, there is a lot of
pressure,'' he said. ``But our team has never thought about
defending the championship. We didn't change anything. We just said
let's go to Charlotte. Forget about the playoff format. Forget
about anything. Throw the ball up and let's get after it. That
sounds awfully canned, but it's a fact.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
