<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHRISTIANITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME YANKEES KEEP THE FAITH IN PRAYER GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Scott Brosius is chatting to a reporter about
the fraying of his baseball glove when he sees his teammate Chad
Curtis approaching. ``Fifty-five,'' Curtis says to Brosius, who
nods and glances at a nearby clock before resuming his
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis moves around the clubhouse, dispensing the same
information, to Joe Girardi to Homer Bush to Mike Stanton and Andy
Pettitte and others. At 55 minutes past the hour on this day, or at
whatever time is set, a group of New York Yankees retreat into an
empty room, and for 10 to 15 minutes they might discuss matters of
faith or inspiration, or a reading they have shared, or ask for
prayers. Every day they gather.
</P>
<P>
   The sharing of faith or prayer is not uncommon in baseball or
other sports. But the Yankees' group is unusual in that it meets
every day, and that it seems to exist seamlessly within the fabric
of the team. Players who don't participate appear wholly
comfortable with those who do meet. Those among the group mention
their faith only when asked.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi is a personal and devoted catcher for David Cone, not
part of the group. Tim Raines, who does not participate,
good-naturedly teases those who do, and in turn, he is teased, and
they seem to be at ease with each other, unthreatened and
unbothered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best go-with-the-flow team I've ever been on,'' said
Cone, referring to the players' tolerance of each other, religious
and otherwise. ``It's a very cohesive team, we all respect each
other, and we all respect each other's beliefs. There's no conflict
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone has been on teams, he acknowledged, where this was not the
case. ``Not only with religion issues, but what music is played in
the clubhouse, what's on the television sometimes before the
game,'' Cone said. ``There are different divisive issues that
sometimes enter into a clubhouse. This team almost disallows
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre agreed. ``Everybody's an individual
with their own beliefs, and it's important that is respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis organized the meetings early this year, after noticing
that the Yankees had a number of players with belief in various
denominations of Christianity. Pettitte is Baptist, for example,
while Curtis chooses not to be part of a specific denomination, and
George Rose, Hideki Irabu's interpreter, is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   To bridge the many faiths, Curtis said, they all agreed that
``we're not going to talk about the differences'' in the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to focus on what's central,'' Curtis said, ``that
Jesus is who He says He was.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pettitte: ``In today's world you see so many people argue
about so many different religions, and everybody in our group is
from a different religious background. But we all love the Lord and
that's all that matters. There's no sense in fighting or having
divisions. I don't think that's what the Lord wants us to be
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis is serious and introspective, an intense listener. When
batting, he stares at a pitcher, focusing on the pitcher and only
the pitcher; he engages in conversation the same way, the hard
visual examination. He speaks in a low and assuring voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same core beliefs,'' Curtis said, referring to
those in the group. ``We find that's our strength. Not for
baseball, but for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis says that because of what surrounds him every day _ the
expectations for performance, the stress _ he finds a need for a
counter-balance, a reminder of what should be important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to surround myself with people and bathe my mind
and my soul in what I really want to be evident in my life,'' said
Curtis, ``which is the word of God, and what I've found on this
team is that there are others who have that same desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Religion, says Pettitte, is an important part of his life and he
carries and reads a Bible daily. ``These meetings are just another
way for me to get closer to the Lord,'' said Pettitte. ``We get
together on the road sometimes, maybe like an hour or so, watch a
video and then talk about it. It gives us time for fellowship _
there's so much negative going on in this world, and it gives us
something positive getting together.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte says he would practice his faith regardless of whether
it differed from the beliefs of his teammates. ``This is important
to me,'' said Pettitte. ``We do this privately and it's something
we're going to do. We feel like it helps us. I could see if we were
doing it in the middle of the clubhouse, that might bother other
people. But we are private about this and anybody who wants to come
in is invited.''
</P>
<P>
   Players on this team almost never make religious references when
discussing their own performance or a result on the field. If he
pitches a shutout, Pettitte does not attribute this to an act of
God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most you'll hear me say is to thank God for keeping me
healthy,'' said Pettitte. ``I mean, God doesn't care how many wins
I have. That's not a concern of his. What matters is that I'm being
a good servant to him and I'm helping other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my job and I thank him for letting me do this job and
I've just got to go out and do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said: ``There are definitely people who assume we are
trying to get favor from God on the field. Am I going to take what
I believe, am I going to take this God and turn him into a good
luck charm? Am I going to say this is the God who gives me base
hits? It's not that. That's trivializing God. It's the God who
gives me life.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis used to play with Tony Fernandez in Cleveland and
recalled that last year, Fernandez thanked God after he hit a
game-winning home run in the playoffs _ and then thanked God again
after making a decisive error in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' Curtis said, ``that's honoring and glorifying.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
