<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETTER-TO-KILLER-LADN     08-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTER-TO-KILLER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER'S BULLETS HIT FAMILY'S DREAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News.) 
By DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- So, what was it?
</P>
<P>
   A gang initiation murder? A drive-by? Or were you just ``out
hunting,'' as the cops call it?
</P>
<P>
   Why'd you do it? Why'd you mess up one fine family, end one fine
life?
</P>
<P>
   In case you give a damn, the kid you killed was named Julio
Cano. He was 20, and would have been 21 in a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   He was out jogging in the pre-dawn hours Sunday morning on the
streets of Pacoima because that was the only time he had to stay in
shape.
</P>
<P>
   When you're working two full-time jobs trying to help your
father support your mother and four brothers and sisters, you take
what time you can steal for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Julio's time was 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   He'd get up as quietly as he could, so as not to wake up the
rest of his family living in the cramped, two-bedroom apartment on
Van Nuys Boulevard in Pacoima.
</P>
<P>
   His running clothes were already laid out in the living room.
He'd dress quickly and hit the streets for a five-mile or so run
around Hansen Dam and back.
</P>
<P>
   You saw him on the way back, around 6 a.m. at Glenoaks Boulevard
and Pierce Street, not far from his home.
</P>
<P>
   We know because that's where police found his body crumpled in
the gutter, dead from gunshot wounds. Neighbors say it was around 6
a.m. when they heard the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Guerra, a licensed vocational nurse, says she heard about
Julio at work late Monday. Her knees went weak, and she had to sit
down or she would have hit the floor. She just sat there and cried
for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, Julio's been her helper on Station 2 over at
the Foothill Health and Rehabilitation Center in Sylmar. It's a
mental health facility. She and Julio would spend their shift
together trying to help the people on Station 2 make some sense of
this crazy world.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling eight hours there, Julio went over to the Beverly
Manor Convalescent Hospital in Panorama City for another eight as a
nurse's aide, helping old people live out their lives in some
dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra called Julio an ``angel from Earth.'' Never complained,
always taking on extra duties, always ready to switch work days to
help a co-worker out of a jam.
</P>
<P>
   All the patients loved him.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they and the staff chipped in what they could the
other day when Julio's father, Julio Sr., stopped by to say thanks
and pick up an envelope with some cash in it.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much, Guerra said, but it helped the financially
strapped Cano family bury its main breadwinner the other day at
Forest Lawn, Hollywood Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Angelic &UR;  &LR; Flores, Julio's older sister, had her mother,
Eustaquia, by the arm _ helping her get through the service and
burial.
</P>
<P>
   Your bullets hit her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Right in the heart. Maybe of all the Canos, she's taking Julio's
death the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   He was her baby, her salvation. Angelic says Julio and his
mother would sit for hours talking about the future _ about how he
was going to school to become a nurse just like Susan Guerra.
</P>
<P>
   How someday he would make enough money to hire his mother a maid
so she would never have to scrub another toilet or floor with those
painful, arthritic hands.
</P>
<P>
   How he promised her he would do everything in his power to move
his family to a safe place, away from these violent, gang-ridden
Pacoima projects.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Department Detective Lindy Gligorijevic, who
is handling this homicide, says that in the last nine months in the
Canos' apartment complex there have been three gang-related
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Julio, she says, was a good kid just in the wrong place at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he and his family live in a housing project
that has a rival gang problem, and it looks like in the early
morning hours, while out running, Julio may have been mistaken for
somebody in a rival gang,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or, it may be that it was just somebody out hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody out hunting.
</P>
<P>
   For a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Any human being.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
