<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7451 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTS-ACCUSED-LADN     08-22 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-ACCUSED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE ACCUSED OF STARVING DAUGHTER TO DEATH RELIES ON FAITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file.) 
(EDITORS: Repeating with Web site address, address is
www.ptw.com/(tilde)trig) 
By BHAVNA MISTRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE LOS ANGELES, Calif. _ The crime is unspeakable: a father
and mother starving their severely disabled daughter to death.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Michael and Kathleen ``Katrina'' Gentry stand accused of
just that, of killing 15-year-old Lindsay, an offense so heinous
they are being held in Los Angeles County jails on $1 &UR;  &LR; million bail
each.
</P>
<P>
   To their friends and neighbors in this remote high-desert
community, the idea that the Gentrys _ churchgoing, civic-minded,
generous and devoted _ could do such a thing is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We _ the people who know the truth _ know these people could
never be responsible for any of this,'' said Paul Villandry, a
longtime friend. ``These people give their lives to helping
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Villandry and about 40 others have rallied behind the Gentrys.
They have set up an Internet site, staged a fund-raiser at a
Lancaster JetHawks minor-league baseball game and are selling
T-shirts bearing the Gentrys' likenesses to raise money for their
legal defense. They also wrote testimonials in an effort to
convince a judge to lower the couple's bail.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the supporters also may be at the Gentrys' preliminary
hearing, scheduled for Wednesday in Los Angeles Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Gentry, 44, is being held in the women's section of the
Twin Towers Correctional Facility. She receives medication for pain
caused by a lifelong medical condition, but is otherwise treated as
an ordinary prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gentry _ a former Town Council and Park Association
member, volunteer firefighter and longtime Air Force reservist _ is
locked up in an isolation cell in Men's Central Jail in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in jail, he spoke of his faith in God and
belief that his and his wife's innocence will protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never done anything wrong, so why should I be afraid?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an angel,'' he said, ``but with respect to my
children, I have tried to give my them the best, physically and
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   The second of Michael and Kathleen Gentry's two daughters _ he
has two grown children from a previous marriage _ Lindsay was 10
weeks premature when she was born Jan. 4, 1981. She had water on
the brain, dislocated hips and clubbed feet.
</P>
<P>
   She also suffered from congenital myotonic dystrophy, which is
characterized by the wasting of muscles, the formation of
cataracts, premature baldness and, frequently, mental deficiency.
She inherited the condition from her mother, who has a mild form of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said that the Gentrys tried to give Lindsay a normal
and happy childhood, although the little girl was frequently
hospitalized and always in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gentry built a playground, swimming pool and spa in the
backyard. Kathleen Gentry gave Lindsay massages to alleviate some
of her pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make her as comfortable as we could,'' said Helen
Darrow, Michael Gentry's mother, who lived with the family during
the two years before Lindsay's death.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's parents also enrolled her in special education classes
in the Wilsona School District, where the girl was teased by other
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would take her walking stick and make her fall,'' said
Licecka Brown, Lindsay's classmate at Wilsona Elementary School.
``They called her slow and retarded and barked in her ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months before she died, the Gentrys withdrew Lindsay from
school, choosing to teach her at home. Her condition worsened
around Thanksgiving 1995, and she was admitted in January 1996 to
Kaiser Foundation Hospital in Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   When she died Feb. 6, the 4-foot-8-inch girl weighed less than
50 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's death certificate listed pneumonia and marasmus _
progressive emaciation caused by a lack of food _ as contributing
factors. Because of her complex health problems, authorities didn't
suspect wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, detectives received a tip from someone close to the family
that Lindsay had been mistreated. They opened an investigation that
spanned two years and included numerous medical specialists before
deciding to arrest the Gentrys.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide detectives and prosecutors declined to comment for this
story, although they previously have said they believe Lindsay
could have survived given proper care and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In jail, Michael Gentry is labeled a ``high-power inmate'' _ he
is an accused child killer and has an excessively high bail _ so is
isolated from other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   He is allowed out of his 6-by-9-foot cell for 30 minutes every
other day to shower, shave and use the phone. One day a week, he
gets to spend three hours in a 10-by-10-foot room equipped with
weightlifting gear.
</P>
<P>
   While other inmates are allowed four visits a week, Michael
Gentry may have visitors for 20 minutes on Fridays and Sundays. He
is separated from his visitors by a thick glass window and must use
a phone to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Clean shaven, calm and mild-mannered, Gentry says he doesn't
mind being in prison but is concerned about his wife because of her
medical condition. He offered to stay in jail as security if his
wife is released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about my wife,'' he said. ``I'll be the insurance for
my wife's freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
