<SLUG> BC-NY-GARBAGE-TRUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBE DELAYS NYC PLANS TO BUY GARBAGE TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city has postponed plans to buy scores of garbage
trucks while it investigates its contracts with an Oklahoma company
that has supplied most of the current fleet. Arranging for a new
supplier could take more than a year, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Saturday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the
Department of Investigation was looking into the propriety of the
city's contracts with the company, Crane Carrier Co. of Tulsa,
Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Crane was the only bidder on many New York City contracts for
garbage trucks in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, tiny cracks were found in the steel frames of more than
20 trucks, then a few years old, made by Crane. Crane fixed the
cracks, but the city has stopped buying trucks from Crane until the
investigation is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said investigators would look into the wisdom of
depending on one company to provide the majority of the city's
2,000 garbage trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always better if we don't have to do that,'' he said. ``I
don't know if that was a mistake in this case. When the Department
of Investigation finishes its investigation, I'll be able to tell
you whether that was a reasonable judgment in advance and it turned
out wrong, or it was not a reasonable judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   In a March letter to Crane, the Department of Citywide
Administrative Services, which buys city supplies, said the company
had been ruled ineligible to bid on a contract for new trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said Crane had been ``determined not to be a
responsible vendor.'' It asserted that Crane had ``failed to
perform adequately on previously awarded contracts,'' ``provided
trucks which did not conform to the specifications in significant
respects,'' and manufactured trucks ``with poor internal testing
and quality controls.''
</P>
<P>
   James Wade, who was the company's vice president of sales when
the cracks were discovered, said Crane had thought that the
Department of Sanitation was ``completely satisfied.'' He said New
York was by far the company's largest customer, and municipal
contracts were an important part of its business.
</P>
<P>
   ``To avoid any possibility of a future problem, the company at
its own cost went through and repaired all of the frames that were
suspicious, and reinforced all the other trucks that were in that
whole series,'' said Wade, who retired in April.
</P>
<P>
   Crane president Reg Wallace did not respond to a message left at
his home Saturday. A security guard at Crane said no spokesman was
available, and said he was not allowed to take messages.
</P>
<P>
   Crane Carrier's Web site says the company was founded in 1953
and specializes in heavy-duty custom vehicles, including
waste-collection trucks, cement mixers and airport ground-support
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The company supplied all but 53 of the 1,987 garbage trucks in
the Department of Sanitation's fleet, and all but 16 of the
department's 121 front-end loaders, a city spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said officials were not concerned that any defect in
the trucks might hamper service. ``The vast majority of trucks
aren't affected by this, so there isn't a broad-based concern about
the safety of trucks or the viability of trucks,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-GALAXY     08-22 0730
