<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-GALAXY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION DECIMATED BY GALAXY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Revolution could have used Walter Zenga on the
field instead of as an honored guest during Saturday's game against
the Los Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   But even Zenga would have struggled against the Galaxy, which
controlled the game from the opening kickoff, in taking a 5-1
victory to keep the Revolution in last place.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, owners of the best record in Major League Soccer
with 58 points in 26 matches, should have been expected to defeat
the Revolution, who have the league's worst mark with 20 points.
But the margin of the rout indicates the Revolution have lost their
way and have little hope of qualifying for the playoffs, though
they could salvage hope at Miami Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution played conservatively at the start, creating few
scoring chances, even after surrendering an 11th-minute headed goal
to Cobi Jones. They rallied beginning the second half, but soon
after Carlos Hermosillo headed in a Martin Machon cross 11 minutes
into the half, the Revolution collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Jones scored three goals but missed a 70th-minute penalty kick,
after which Revolution captain Mike Burns was ejected. And
Hermosillo scored twice, the second just seconds after the penalty
kick.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the Revolution to keep the score close before a
crowd of 24,143 raised questions about coach Thomas Rongen, who was
asked if he would resign after the match. ``Absolutely not,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't evade responsibility for the dismal showing. ``It
starts at the top, and I take responsibility,'' said the coach.
``If you look at the team, I'm not satisfied with the team's and my
own performance. I feel the Kraft family, the fans, and the
organization deserve a better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've proven in the past that I can put a winning product on
the field. I'm disappointed in my own performance, but that doesn't
necessarily lead to my resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's central defense again faltered; the team has
allowed a league-worst 60 goals. The opening goal was headed in by
Jones, at 5 feet 5 inches among the shortest players on the field,
who was free because of miscommunication between the Revolution
central defenders and 6-6 goalkeeper Ian Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   Rongen hoped to play compactly, to parry the Galaxy's attacks,
then take the offensive in the second half. But the Revolution
virtually surrendered the midfield and were outflanked by the speed
of Jones and Welton.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution rallied late, sparked by 18-year-old Jamar
Beasley, who drew a penalty from Paul Caligiuri on his first touch.
Raul Diaz Arce hit the top of the crossbar with the penalty in the
76th minute, then headed in a Beasley cross with the Revolution
trailing, 5-0, in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against a team as good as LA, you can't play catchup,'' Rongen
said. ``It's that simple. The game was won and lost in the first
half with that goal. We knew we couldn't play come-from-behind. At
halftime we were still in the game, but after the second goal, that
was all she wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, among the most powerful strikers in Mexico before
joining the Galaxy this season, leaped over Manny Motajo for the
second goal. But the play was set up by a counterattack, with Jones
penetrating into the heart of the Revolution defense, then laying
off to Machon, who drew out Feuer and crossed to the far post.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question they are disappointed in themselves,''
Rongen said of his team. ``We are in this together. We all make
mistakes. Collectively, we are not doing the job we are supposed to
do. As a team, we played poorly defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's best chance to recover was at the outset of the
second half, when David Nakhid moved into attacking positions.
Then, Joe-Max Moore headed wide in the eighth minute. The Galaxy
countered seconds later for Hermosillo's first goal and a 2-0 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Revolution began gambling and left themselves
embarrassingly exposed on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any easy games when there are 12 teams
still with a chance to achieve something,'' Galaxy coach Octavio
Zambrano said. ``Technically, nobody is out of it. We played like
we know how to, kicked the ball around, and waited for an
opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
