<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-COBIJONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES IS GALAXY'S MVP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Can there be any doubt that Los Angeles Galaxy
midfielder Cobi Jones is this season's Most Valuable Player of
Major League Soccer?
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's 5-1 victory over the Revolution, Jones punched in
three goals and had an assist, for his third hat trick of the
season and the fourth in his career. It gave Jones 16 goals and 10
assists for the 20-6 Galaxy, tying him for the team and league lead
in points with Welton, formerly of the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   By reaching double figures in both goals and assists, Jones
joined only five players in the league to do so this season. He
leads the league in hat tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy about it,'' said Jones. ``I've got to look at
that as a positive, but I have to study the negatives. I think,
personally, I should have had two more in this game. I've got to
look at that and try to better myself. I'm very happy with what I
have, but I've got to study a bit and to think about the
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy are 17-0 in the last 17 games in which Jones has
scored. He's played in only 18 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   In seven career games against the Revolution, Jones has five
goals and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   His first goal Saturday came in the 11th minute when he had a
header at the top of the box, getting to the ball quicker than
Revolution defender Manny Motajo and crossing up goalkeeper Ian
Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   His two others were on breakaways, in the 79th minute and the
85th minute, both on touches.
</P>
<P>
   As for the misses, Jones failed on a penalty kick in the 78th
minute, trying to tuck the ball into the upper-right corner. ``I
hit it and I thought for sure it was going in, but (Feuer) has got
a wing span like no tomorrow,'' Jones said. ``He got it and knocked
it against the post.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other miss, Jones took a pass from Clint Mathis and shot,
but the ball never reached the goal. ``At the time I thought I
should shoot it,'' Jones said, ``but when (Feuer) came out and I
shot it and it went through his legs. It bounced and through his
legs, but one of their guys cleared it out. Hindsight is 100
percent, but I probably should have dribbled around (Feuer).''
</P>
<P>
   Said Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano, ``That's the challenge that
he puts on himself. It's always about playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones isn't spending his time thinking about being the league's
MVP. ``Personally, I'm just going out and trying to do what I have
to do,'' he said. ``I'm supposed to be one of the scorers and
people give me the ball so I'm just doing my job out there. The
rest of the guys are helping me out and getting me to where I am
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Zambrano, ``His overall competitiveness is what makes him
the player that he is. He takes it personally to perform at 100
percent in every match. I've never seen Cobi go through a match
without giving it his all. And he exposes his body when he does
that. He doesn't back off. At 28 years old, you peak in the game
and Jones still is. He's definitely one of the strongest candidates
to be the MVP.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
