<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS' PITCHER HEARTENED BY LETTER FROM DAUGHTER IN CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Orlando Hernandez, the defector from Cuba who
will make his 15th start for the New York Yankees here Sunday
against the Texas Rangers, has been heartened by a letter he
received from his eldest daughter. With a broad smile, the pitcher
said Yahumara Hernandez, 8, wrote in a letter received three days
ago that she understands why her father left Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Yahumara and her sister Steffi, 3, remained in Cuba with
Hernandez's former wife, while their father left Cuba for
liberation and an opportunity to pursue his baseball career. The
letter, Hernandez said through an interpreter, ``took away some
worry.'' He added, ``You always worry that when kids grow up, they
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahumara also included a catalog of Barbie dolls, with the
request that Hernandez send one of each that she checked off. ``She
checked off all but two,'' Hernandez said, laughing. ``She's very
smart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
