<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7483 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-HACKETT-LADN     08-22 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-HACKETT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN HACKETT HACK IT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Talk to Paul Hackett's friends, and you will hear
tales about a perfectionist with a burning intensity to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Hackett, and you'll get a couple more personality traits
rarely heard about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the one you haven't added was impatience,''
Hackett said. ``I had a bull-in-a-china-shop attitude. That gets
you into trouble, particularly with authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambition was always one issue. I was seen as a guy who doesn't
have a lot of tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett described himself as ``a guy going 1,000 miles per hour,
regardless of what's in his way,'' during his younger years.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett the coach, like Hackett the person, has undergone
changes. The ambition and intolerance are no longer issues, Hackett
said. He's 51 years old and doing things differently than his
previous college and NFL stops.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back at USC, Hackett is trying to make the most of perhaps
his last chance to prove he can be a successful head coach, with a
kinder, gentler approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm older and wiser,'' Hackett said. ``You can't keep making
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest occurred in Berkeley in 1975, when Hackett
was an assistant at California. He coached outstanding quarterbacks
Steve Bartkowski and Joe Roth and began building his reputation as
a quarterback guru. However, Hackett got fined and reprimanded by
Cal athletic director Dave Maggard for violating NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   The school's faculty athletic representative, the late Bob
Steidel, wanted to fire Hackett. It's an episode few know about,
but Hackett looks back at it with amusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never liked me (at Cal),'' Hackett said. ``I was too
ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was found to have violated the rules by working with his
quarterbacks during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overzealous,'' he said. ``One of the days I was on the
sideline yelling at the quarterbacks . . . my typical attitude. I
was right next to (Maggard's office).
</P>
<P>
   ``He decided to make an example of it. I reacted to him and got
upset. Dave Maggard and I never saw eye to eye on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Maggard, who now lives in Atlanta: ``There were NCAA and
Pac-10 Conference rules violations and we took care of them. Paul
was very ambitious and temperamental.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cal coach Mike White, who is an assistant with the St.
Louis Rams, said Hackett would have eventually been the head coach
at Cal if not for clashes between the football staff and
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, Paul was trying to do one thing, help build the
image of Cal football,'' White said. ``To be questioned for his
integrity, I could see how that could stick in his craw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he got reprimanded for taking a player to lunch. He was
trying to build a rapport. Maybe somebody said he saw Paul and a
player throwing a ball from a window. Paul's motive was never more
than to help a student do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   White and Hackett and other Cal assistants probably dodged
another bullet when NCAA violations were discovered regarding the
eligibility of running back Chuck Muncie during their tenure. By
the time the violations were unearthed in 1980, however, the NCAA's
four-year statute of limitations had lapsed and no one was
punished.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he wasn't worried that being disciplined at Cal
would derail his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew I was a good football coach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he proved it at USC, where as the offensive coordinator he
helped lead the Trojans to a national championship in 1978.
Although his initial tenure as a USC assistant under John Robinson
is frequently portrayed as a warm, fuzzy ``mentor-prodigy''
relationship, those who worked at USC in the late '70s remember a
far different atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett's pass-first mentality often clashed against Robinson's
power-running philosophy, and arguments stretched from Heritage
Hall to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be going to the game and have a battle,'' Hackett
said. ``We were always going at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Things became so heated, some former assistants thought Hackett
might quit during several games.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I was more aggressive than I should have been,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett eventually got fed up at USC, but it wasn't his
relationship with Robinson that caused him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I (thought about quitting) was when it got to be
that winning wasn't enough, and that happened in the fourth year,''
Hackett said. ``We would win and be coming up the tunnel and people
would be upset because we didn't win by enough points.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nine more years before Hackett got his first chance
to be a head coach, when Pitt hired him to replace Mike Gottfried,
who was 26-17-2 in four seasons. It turned out to be an emotionally
scarring experience as Hackett tried to win and build the academic
program simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked him to get rid of all the questionable-character
kids,'' said Kansas State assistant coach Ron Hudson, who grew up
with Hackett in the Bay Area and remains a close friend. ``He told
the kids you had to go to class.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett's record at Pitt was 13-20-1, and he was fired after
three seasons, but he still feels bitter that the school's
president and athletic director left shortly after he was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``My support group got knocked out from under me,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   His experience at Pitt has probably had the most profound impact
on Hackett's approach to coaching at USC. He has delegated
authority to his assistant coaches and _ unlike at Pitt _ is not
trying to coach the quarterbacks, run the offense and be the head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, I had to do it all. I had to do it all and it
almost killed me,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett loves to tutor the USC quarterbacks during training camp
at UC Irvine, but he has not been overbearing or obsessed with
running the offense, a main critique from his time at Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very serious but in a good way,'' quarterback Mike Van
Raaphorst said. ``He has a lot that he can teach us.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also been extremely patient with the players.
</P>
<P>
   White said Rams quarterback Steve Bono recently messed up a
drill during practice, so he asked Bono how Hackett would have
reacted when the pair worked in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have thrown a fit,'' Bono told White.
</P>
<P>
   There's been little of that so far at USC. At practices, it's
far more likely to hear him encourage a quarterback. ``Great pass,
Carson'' has not been an unlikely comment while observing freshman
quarterback Carson Palmer. Hackett has earned the respect of
players, notably by suspending temperamental wide receiver R. Jay
Soward for the season-opener for poor academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats us all equally,'' wide receiver Billy Miller. ``He
said he doesn't want stars, he wants a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett has learned to make the subtle changes for a chance to
succeed at USC. He wants to bring USC back to prominence, but this
is also Hackett's chance to prove that the brilliant assistant can
finally make it as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   He is confident in his methods but isn't as likely to lose his
temper. His intensity remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn from every experience,'' Hackett said.
``When you get your (butt) beat, which we did at Kansas City, you
rethink it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett certainly has a game plan. He has already overhauled
USC's football office. Sixteen employees connected to the football
program have either left, been reassigned or fired since January.
</P>
<P>
   It's Hackett's operation now, win or lose. And he's willing to
take responsibility, if he gets a chance to rebuild the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a process of trying to build a great tradition at
this university,'' he said. ``It's going to take time. It's a
long-term process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
