<HEADLINE>
COACHES WORK ON PLAN FOR PURDUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC football coach Paul Hackett gave the Trojans
the day off, but Saturday was just another work day for his staff.
Hackett began putting together a game plan for next Sunday's game
against Purdue at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no day off for coaches,'' Hackett said. ``There's
always one more tape to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it's the season-opener, USC's impression of Purdue will be
largely based on last year's game tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're assuming they'll be somewhat similar,'' Hackett said.
``All we have to go on is last year. About all they know about us
is we'll line up in the `I' (formation).''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett will be bucking history when he tries to win the
season-opener. Six straight USC coaches have failed to win in their
debut games, including John Robinson twice (1976, 1993). Ted
Tollner tied Florida 19-19 in his debut in 1983. The last USC coach
to win his first game was Jess Hill in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Fast walk-on: USC sprinter Marcus Holiwell is trying to join the
team as a walk-on at wide receiver. Holiwell is one of the track
team's top sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   He will joined in the spring on track by fellow sprinters Sultan
McCullough and Miguel Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-on wide receiver Dylan Weiss has left the team to
concentrate on academics.
</P>
<P>
   Will Palmer play? Hackett doesn't seem to be in hurry to get
freshman quarterback Carson Palmer into a game. Asked if Palmer
might see some action against Purdue, Hackett said, ``I don't know.
I'm not much of a rotate-quarterbacks kind of guy. Let's see what
Mike (Van Raaphorst) can do. (But) there's no question Carson's got
a great future.''
</P>
<P>
   Training costs: USC will spend about $50,000 extra by staying in
Irvine for three weeks. The primary cost was moving equipment from
Los Angeles to Irvine. USC moved its weights and created a weight
room adjacent to the practice field. Food and dormitory costs are
about the same as if the team had stayed at USC.
</P>
<P>
   New look: For the first time in at least 20 years, USC players
are wearing cardinal blazers for road trips. Players usually wore
warm-up suits when they traveled in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980822.0209 </DOCNO>
