<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHAB STINT IS THREE INNINGS FOR VALDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Right-hander Ismael Valdes made his first minor-league
rehabilitation start since injuring his left side July 27 but
lasted just three scoreless innings and 44 pitches in a game for
the the Dodgers' Single-A affiliate in Port St. Lucie, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The club was hoping he would throw at least 75 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes spent the night in Orlando and flew back this morning to
Los Angeles, where he will be examined by orthopedist Frank Jobe.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers figured Valdes would make one minor-league start and
be ready to pitch Thursday against the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a little hard to read those things from here,'' said
Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman, the former field coordinator for the
Dodgers' minor-league operation. ``We probably won't know until
tomorrow how he came out of this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes recovered slowly after injuring his side in a game
against the Arizona Diamondbacks. He did not throw a ball for two
weeks, but he reported great improvement during the past 10 days.
He threw a simulated game in Pittsburgh and reported no discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Still looking: The Dodgers' general manager search continues.
Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden and Atlanta assistant Dean Taylor have
both interviewed with club president Bob Graziano in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor returned to Atlanta on Friday and spoke with interim GM
Tom Lasorda on Saturday. ``I really hope he gets this chance,''
Braves GM John Schuerholz said. ``He has been with me for 18 years,
back to the days in Kansas City. I don't know of anyone with his
grasp of all facets of the game _ minor leagues, contracts,
scouting, everything. I don't want to lose him, but this is a great
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to say about the interview is that it is an honor
to be considered for one of the most prestigious jobs in the
game,'' said Taylor, who started working for Schuerholz in 1980 at
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Dave Dombrowski will be interviewed this week. Gary
Hughes, the Marlins' highly regarded director of player personnel,
also will speak to Graziano this week. Dombrowski and Hughes joined
the expansion Marlins in 1993 after several years together in
Montreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
