A7651 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     08-22 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLY PUT, YANKEES REIGN SUPREME. PERIOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Yankees, go home.
</P>
<P>
   Don't come back until October.
</P>
<P>
   In the autumn, by the light of an always-dicey, best-of-five
postseason series, the New York Yankees might look a smidgen more
beatable.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, they are lapping the American League field. The
pundits are running out of adjectives. They are inviting
comparisons to some of the most formidable aggregations of all time
_ the '27 Yankees, the '75 Reds, the phone company before
deregulation, the Rolling Stones when Keith Richards had his
original factory color.
</P>
<P>
   This is embarrassing. New York has the league's best batting
average. The best earned-run average. The best caps. The best
muggers. The best $34.95 breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers come back and win the AL West with their current
percentage, the ``reward'' will be a first-round series against Joe
Torre's Yankees. It's a best-of-five series, but I like the New
Yorkers in two games. Then I figure the Yankees will beat the
Cleveland Indians in the ALCS by, oh, six or seven touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any need to play the World Series because, by the
day postseason rosters are due, the Yankees will have bought up all
of the good players.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson _ left-handed setup man.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. _ late-inning defensive specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan _ shooting guard on off-season Yankee hoops team.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Springer _ coordinator of bench-clearing brawls.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are so good, they've almost become trite. New York
headline writers have had to hang on to every visiting team's
remark, in hopes of an original angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canseco declares stadium dogs `tasty'
</P>
<P>
   Ripken misses early bus
</P>
<P>
   What kind of name is Nomar?''
</P>
<P>
   And last week's gem, ``Oates rips Yanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the story didn't exactly say that _ and though Rangers
manager Johnny Oates didn't, either _ the headline in the ``New
York Daily News'' suggested someone thought the emperor really had
no pinstriped clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth, of course. Oates didn't
say it. Oates doesn't even want to talk about it, as I learned by
innocently inquiring about ``this misquoting thing in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Duhh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's dead!'' Oates abruptly answered, waving me away. ``I
have nothing whatsoever to say about it. It's a waste of time
trying to defend myself. Let's move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Earwitnesses support Oates' story. He didn't ``rip Yanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would he?
</P>
<P>
   Heading into last night, the Yankees were 61 games over .500,
which I think is the same record the Globetrotters have against the
Washington Generals. This time, however, we are all the straight
men in the Yankees' act. We think there's a pennant race going on.
</P>
<P>
   (Throw fake bucket of water on us here.)
</P>
<P>
   Against the Yankees this season, the Rangers are something like
2-and-89. They have lost to Yankees that speak three different
languages. They have lost, despite actually, truthfully, kind of,
more or less, playing the Yankees tough.
</P>
<P>
   Before last night, Oates didn't want to hear that, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they add a column other than `wins' and `losses,' I
don't care about that,'' the manager said. ``Every paper I've ever
looked at doesn't have a column for `close games.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not like the Rangers have been outclassed by the
Yankees. There was that memorable 15-13 New York victory at The
Ballpark back in early May. There was a 13-inning Rangers victory a
week later at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When a foe is 61 games over .500, you have to be willing to read
between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, once burned in print, doesn't want to compare (yawn) the
New Yorkers with the greatest teams of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't there in 1906, so I don't know what kind of
competition the Cubs had,'' he said. ``And I wasn't there in 1927,
so I don't know what the Yankees' competition was like.''
</P>
<P>
   But these Yankees are pretty good. A Cadillac, perhaps, with a
Rolls Royce of a record.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend series at The Ballpark has done nothing to alter the
'98 Yanks' steamroller image. They are amazing. They are
relentless. They are re-lapping the field.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of name is Nomar, anyway?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
