<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-22 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Alou-HNS &LR;      08-22 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Alou-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Alou's throws his bat into MVP race
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ St. Louis' Mark McGwire and Chicago's Sammy Sosa are
chasing baseball history. Pretty soon, they could be chasing one of
the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the home-run race but in the quest to be the National
League's Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou's campaign unofficially took off Saturday afternoon
in front of 39,886 at Wrigley Field. The fans saw an MVP-type
performance from a Dominican outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   One not named Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   What once looked like a two-party race for the league's top
honor has a third candidate after Alou tied a career high with four
hits, including his 37th home run, in the Astros' 8-3 victory over
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to hear stuff like that,'' Alou said of being
mentioned as an MVP candidate. ``There are a lot of guys on this
team that have done a great job. It's not like it's my show every
day. Every day is a different guy. I'm happy to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``MVP is something out of my reach. I have no control over that.
Actually, I hadn't even thought about it until a year and a half
ago, when people started talking.''
</P>
<P>
   The whispers are getting louder. Ballots aren't due until late
September, and the race is heating up:
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is the odds-on favorite to break baseball's most
hallowed record _ Roger Maris' single-season home-run record of 61.
McGwire has 52 with five weeks left.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who went 0-for-5 on Saturday and has 49 home runs, paces
the National League with 124 RBIs and has led Chicago into the
thick of the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's homer total (37) is modest in comparison to his
competitors' numbers. But he in the RBI hunt, with 112, while
hitting .310. Perhaps most important, the Astros are first in the
Central Division and are 30 games above .500.
</P>
<P>
   After going 4-for-5 with two RBIs and three runs scored
Saturday, Alou picked up a big endorsement from teammate Jeff
Bagwell, the NL 1994 MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moises has been a rock in our lineup,'' said Bagwell, who
batted .368 with 39 homers and 116 RBIs in the strike-shortened
1994 season. ``Day after day after day he comes up with big hits
for us. He just doesn't get meaningless hits, he gets big hits, big
RBIs. There is no question in my mind he's the MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the balloting isn't that simple. Most believe the
award will go to the player _ McGwire or Sosa _ who breaks Maris'
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, 32, doesn't consider himself a serious candidate just yet,
but he thinks the award should not be based on individual merit
alone. Despite McGwire's power heroics the Cardinals are under
.500. Sosa, on the other hand, has been the main reason the Cubs
have gone from last place in 1997 to playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Few would argue the Astros' acquisition of Alou has been the
difference in this team being 30 games over .500, where last year's
finished just six games over in winning the division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about this game is winning,'' Alou said. ``Whoever
is on a winning team should get an edge for the award. The thing is
one of those guys (McGwire and Sosa) has a shot at breaking the
record. They'll probably get it because of the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe whoever is on a winning team should get
consideration. It could be a guy from the Padres it could be a guy
from the Braves a guy from the Mets or Cubs, if they make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a guy from the Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou singled three times and hit a solo home run in the fourth
Saturday for the 11th four-hit game of his career. He has 17 homers
since the All-Star break. In the past 16 games he is batting .400
with nine homers and 17 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year with the Astros, Alou has been named an
All-Star and seems headed for club records for home runs (43) and
RBIs (135). Bagwell holds both.
</P>
<P>
   Which team does Alou consider better, the 1998 Astros or last
year's World Series champion Florida Marlins?
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the Astros) are pretty much ahead because we are in first
place, we're the team to beat,'' Alou said. ``We (the Marlins) had
a great team last year, a great bunch of guys and a great manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were the wild-card team. We didn't win our division.
Winning the wild card didn't mean we had no shot. We knew we had a
shot against Atlanta because we played them well throughout the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing I'm really looking forward about playing
tough teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The next 32 games will help decide who wins the MVP honor.
Speaking from experience, Bagwell won't rule out his teammate.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities are there, and Bagwell has a good idea of what
it takes to win the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my MVP year, it seemed like I always came up in a big
situation and always got a big hit,'' Bagwell said. ``I see the
same thing in Moises this year. Somehow, some way, he will hit a
big home run, a double, single, whatever it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
