r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CAMPS-ASU-UA-AZR &LR;      08-22 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CAMPS-ASU-UA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL IN THE BOONDOCKS  
 ISOLATION OF CAMPS HELPS UA, ASU DEVELOP UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The football schedules of Arizona and Arizona State say their
seasons officially begin in early September, when stadiums are
filled with fans and Saturday afternoon television is dominated by
games instead of infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   But ASU Coach Bruce Snyder and Arizona Coach Dick Tomey will
tell you something different. Ask Tomey where a winning season
starts and he'll tell you Camp Cochise, near Douglas in the
southeast corner of the state. Ask Snyder and he'll tell you it
starts at Camp Tontozona, 17 miles east of Payson.
</P>
<P>
   It is in training camp, Tomey said, that a team starts to
develop a personality that either will carry it through difficult
times or will collapse under the burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is a journey, not a destination,'' said Tomey, who's
picked up a slogan or two from every motivational book he's read.
``And the damn journey is not a four-lane highway. It's not I-10.
It's the back road to Sonoita. It's full of potholes and hairpin
turns.''
</P>
<P>
   While the work at the two camps is nearly identical _ 100 or so
college men hitting, sweating and bonding _ their locations could
not be more different.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Tontozona is carved out of a forest of pine trees (yes,
they are cool and tall), with a creek (yes, it's a babbling one)
that cuts around the edge of the field.
</P>
<P>
   In their spare time, which is as precious as sleep at camp,
players can soak their legs in a cold spring, bait a hook, or take
a short hike to a waterfall. Or they can sit on their cabin porch
and gaze at the beauty of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it's surreal,'' said center Grey Ruegamer. ``You're
out in the middle of the woods and you walk out of your cabin porch
and there is a football field. It's like, `Oh, hell, that's what
I'm here for.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Cochise, players never forget what they are they for. To
get there, you take I-10 east from Tucson, past the exit for the
back road to Sonoita, until you get to Benson. There, you take
Arizona 80, past Bisbee, to Cochise College, a junior college about
eight miles west of Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   The school is in the middle of desert, with cattle ranchers and
flies serving as the only close neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to joke that the Wildcats spent a year there
last week when they went through preseason drills.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be unfair, Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the best facility I've ever seen, including all
the ones the NFL teams use,'' he said of his team's training
accommodations. ``The people are so nice and everything is so well
tied together, the dorms, the meeting facilities, the practice
facilities, the dining hall.''
</P>
<P>
   To Tomey and the players, the isolation of Camp Cochise is
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Douglas is eight miles away, but it might as well be 108 or it
might as well be two,'' Tomey said. ``We're not going anyplace,
anyway. We don't have any time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomey, who coached Hawaii for 10 seasons, raves about the area.
High temperatures usually stay in the 90s. Afternoon storms
routinely roll in, casting exquisitely eerie shadows over the
desert and cooling the sweating players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's breathtaking,'' Tomey said of the scenery. ``There's a
man in charge up there who every night is trying to figure what the
tapestry will look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapestry is not a word that Tomey's players would use to
describe Camp Cochise. When he first saw his home for 10 days each
August, junior quarterback Keith Smith wondered what he had gotten
himself into.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing around except this little airport,'' he
said. ``I was thinking, where do you go if you have a serious
emergency?''
</P>
<P>
   When Jeremy McDaniel, a senior receiver, saw Camp Cochise for
the first time he vowed to never set foot off campus after dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it would be a scary place at night,'' he said. ``It's
real dark and the nearest house is about 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from a team perspective, coming down here brings us
closer. You block out all the bad _ the flies on you every five
seconds _ and pull together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   To further that goal, Tomey holds what he calls team-building
events that are every bit as important as practice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on the final day of camp last Wednesday, he called
off a practice and ordered his team to report to the pool next
door.
</P>
<P>
   There, they held relay races and finished by jumping together in
the water, barking some unintelligible chant.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will help them win Sept. 3 at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cement pond at Camp Tontozona. No comfortable beds.
No privacy. Even the showers are outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've grown to love it,'' said Snyder, whose team concluded
training camp Saturday and plays its first game Sept. 5 against
Washington. ``I like going up there and I don't like leaving it. Up
there, there are no freeways, no elevators, no phones. I can kick
back and coach. When I leave, I'm saddened.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of his players don't feel that way. Sleeping in barracks,
practicing twice daily and endless meetings take a toll. They crave
a return to normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his first visit to Camp Tontozona, senior quarterback Steve
Campbell thought it was paradise. The bus arrived on Wednesday
evening. There was a nice supper. The weather was wonderful.
Putting a football field amid the pines was ingenious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think, `this is great. I'm going to love this,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he found out his bed sagged in the middle. The fan he
brought was taken over by a fullback and two offensive linemen. The
upperclassmen left their stinking pads in his trailer.
</P>
<P>
   So what if there were pine trees and creeks nearby?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But like Camp Cochise, this is where coaches want players to
bond. Misery brings the freshmen closer together. Nostalgic
evenings work for the upperclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night, we go out on the porch of our cabin and just talk
for hours,'' Campbell said. And for now, their thoughts aren't on
their traditional rival and their game scheduled for Nov. 27. But
Jackson does have one question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know too much about Douglas. Is it somewhere near
Tucson?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
