r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS-AZR &LR;      08-22 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-METS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS LOOK LIKE WEARY TEAM IN LOSS TO METS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Which was the team that had played three
doubleheaders in four days, and which was the team that, by
comparison, was as fresh as a daisy?
</P>
<P>
   By the result of Saturday's game at Shea Stadium, it was
difficult to tell.
</P>
<P>
   It was the New York Mets, whose tanks were supposed to be empty
after the three doubleheaders, who came through when it counted,
pinning a 9-4 setback on the listless Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets used a gutty, seven-inning effort from right-hander
Bobby Jones, pitching on only three days' rest, and a grand slam
from Mike Piazza, his second against Arizona this season and fourth
overall, to delight the crowd of 42,654.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets (72-57) moving a game ahead of the Chicago Cubs
(71-58) in the National League wild-card race, New Yorkers have
visions of a subway World Series against the cross-town big-shot
Yankees dancing in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, meanwhile, dropped their second game in a row
and fifth in their past six. They are 48-82, dashing some team
officials' hopes of reaching the .500 level in their inaugural
season. The primary goal now is to avoid losing 100 games, and
Arizona will have to finish 15-17 to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona jumped to a 4-0 lead in the second inning against Jones
when starting pitcher Andy Benes stroked a two-run double down the
left-field line with the bases loaded and Andy Fox rapped a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   Benes, however, bidding for a chance to climb above the .500
mark with his fifth straight win, couldn't hold the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The big right-hander walked three batters in the inning _ all of
whom scored _ gave up a sacrifice fly to Tony Phillips, a
run-scoring infield hit to Edgard Alfonzo and the grand slam to
Piazza on a 3-2 pitch. Piazza's previous grand slam came off the
Diamondbacks' Jeff Suppan in Los Angeles on April 9 when Piazza was
with still with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My control obviously wasn't very good, but as bad as it was, I
still had the opportunity to get out of it, and I didn't,'' said
Benes, who fell to 11-12. ``There were a lot of borderline
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Those last words were a veiled reference to plate umpire Angel
Hernandez, with whom Benes had a difference of opinion early in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of pitches I thought were strikes that he
said were low, and I said OK,'' Benes said. ``I wasn't trying to
show him up or anything. I think it's fair if you ask a legitimate
question about where the pitch was.''
</P>
<P>
   On one occasion, Hernandez removed his mask and took a few steps
in front of the plate. Manager Buck Showalter came out to talk to
Benes, then, on his return to the dugout, had a few words with the
umpire, although they did not appear to be heated.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' six-run second inning gave new life to Jones, who
scattered eight hits, walked two and struck out five to raise his
record to 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   He got help in the eighth and ninth innings from left-hander
Dennis Cook, a one-time pitcher for the Triple-A Phoenix Firebirds.
Cook, who was a key ingredient for the World Series champion
Florida Marlins as a middle reliever in 1997, held Arizona hitless
while walking one and striking out four.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said Jones had four pitches working _ fastball, change-up,
slider and curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't leave many over the plate, so we weren't able to get
real good wood on them,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his teammates knew that Jones was working on three days'
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you're in that situation, you don't have the
same zip on your fastball as you normally do, but you can overcome
that by pitching better, pitching smarter, trying to mix things up.
That's what he did today,'' Fox said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
