<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PUT WAITE ON THEIR LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes shored up questions concerning their
goaltending situation, apparently striking a deal with Jimmy Waite
to return for a second season as the primary backup to starter
Nicolai Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   The signing will be announced within the next few days,
according to a team official, who promised there will be other
moves made during a ``very busy week'' by the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected those announcements will include the re-signing
of some of the team's three remaining Group II free agents _
defenseman Keith Carney, right wing Shane Doan and goalie Scott
Langkow.
</P>
<P>
   There also is speculation the team might have landed a free
agent from another team.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements, however, are not expected include star left
wing Keith Tkachuk and the captain's ongoing negotiations regarding
a hefty contract extension, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Waite, who appeared in 17 games for the Coyotes
last season, became a Group V unrestricted free agent after Phoenix
declined to tender him an offer. At that time, it appeared unlikely
he would be brought back, especially after management made repeated
statements that Langkow would be given every chance at the backup
job behind Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   But Waite, a 10-year NHL veteran from Sherbrooke, Quebec,
apparently received little interest from other clubs and thought
his best scenario was to return to Phoenix, where he went 5-6-1
with a team-best 2.12 goals-against average and .913 save
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   He also started two playoff games against the Detroit Red Wings
after Khabibulin sustained a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not available. Waite and his
Philadephia-based agent, Steve Mountain, were unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The signing, however, eases speculation about the strength of
the team's goaltending situation. For the past two seasons, the
club has had depth problems because of the ongoing knee problems
that ultimately led to the retirement of Darcy Wakaluk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
