<SLUG> BC-FBO-RATTLERS-ARENA-MVP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATTLERS STAR EARNS MVP  
 SCHEXNAYDER'S OFFENSE IMPRESSES ARENA LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calvin Schexnayder would have preferred to be in Tampa today to
play in the first nationally network-televised ArenaBowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers star, however, gladly accepted the next-best thing:
the Offensive Most Valuable Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   Schexnayder, who put up record receiving numbers, won the honor
on the eve of the Arena Football League championship game that is
being played by Orlando and Tampa Bay and shown by ABC (Channel 15
at 10 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a productive year for me,'' he said. ``It's
been one of my best seasons. Of course, it can't top last year,
when we won the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight year, the Rattlers won the Commissioner's
Award for top organization. They shared it with the Orlando
Predators, who beat the Rattlers in last week's semifinals under
first-year Coach Jay Gruden.
</P>
<P>
   Schexnayder, a 6-foot, 195-pound offensive specialist, set
league records for receiving yards (1,982) and receptions (136) and
tied the league mark for touchdown catches (44).
</P>
<P>
   He said he still fell short of his goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to score five touchdowns a game,'' Schexnayder said.
``I also wanted to surpass 2,000 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 42-40 loss to Orlando, Schexnayder was held to 77 receiving
yards. In a rout of Grand Rapids, he had 58 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the man known as ``Shakes'' was brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Five times he was selected game MVP. He had one of his greatest
efforts in a 59-55 victory over Nashville in the regular-season
finale, a win that clinched home field in the first round of the
playoffs. Schexnayder had 10 catches for 177 yards and five
touchdowns in that game.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, in a first-round victory over Houston, he had
nine catches for 143 yards and four touchdowns and returned three
kickoffs for 70 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Schexnayder was the mainstay on a team that had 14 players go
down because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the main criteria on voting for the MVP is how
valuable he was to the team, I can't imagine anyone more valuable
in the light of the injuries,'' Coach Danny White said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
