<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOWING DOWN NOT AN OPTION  
 AT 39, SPEEDY HENDERSON UP FOR STEALS TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quietly, almost too quietly,  &UR; Rickey Henderson is doing what he
set out to during spring training. Henderson, arguably the best
leadoff hitter in the history of the game and a sure-fire Hall of
Famer, wanted to lead the American League in stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   With just five weeks remaining in the season, Henderson not only
leads the AL in that category but the entire major leagues. If
Henderson, 39, holds on, he will become the oldest player ever to
lead the majors in stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eddie Collins of the Chicago White Sox was 37 when he led the
majors with 42 stolen bases in 1924. Henderson entered the weekend
leading Cleveland's  &UR; Kenny Lofton by 13 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``These old bones still have some life in them,'' Henderson said
during spring training. Now I don't want this out until at least
the All-Star Game, but I plan to lead the league in steals again.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who leads the AL in walks, has won 11 stolen-base
titles since his rookie season with Oakland in 1979. Interestingly,
Henderson, baseball's all-time stolen base king, has not led the
league in stolen bases since 1991, when he had 58.
</P>
<P>
   This is a player who has often made it difficult to be
understood. His actions throughout his 20 years in the majors have
often made him an easy target of numerous detractors. But, believe
it or not, Henderson is not the demon he's been made out to be.
</P>
<P>
   There were times in his career when Henderson's actions were
inappropriate and selfish. But when it came time for the playoffs
or making a playoff run, there were few players on the same level
as Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 10-year window there, from about 1981-90, when
Henderson was probably the best overall player in the game. There
was little he could not do, and even someone of  &UR; Don Mattingly's
stature realized Henderson was the best player in the game, an
answer he gave when asked back in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will always talk about me,'' Henderson said. ``I can't
change what anyone thinks about me. But I think people who follow
the game know I have given everything to the game.'' &QL; 
Dodger Stadium II? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The good folks at FOX have learned that it will cost upwards of
$200 million to upgrade Dodger Stadium the way they envision, with
all those money-making luxury boxes they want to build.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if they're going to pony up $200 million, well, an
additional $200 million could build a brand new ballpark, a
consideration the FOX brass is tinkering with. The hope among
Dodgers fans and baseball fans who have ever been to what is still
considered one of the most picturesque ballparks in the game, is
that the current Dodger Stadium will remain.
</P>
<P>
   Club President  &UR; Bob Graziano insists the front office is
committed to renovating the 36-year-old park that still looks new
and will simply add the 60-75 luxury suites in the near future.
However, he does not rule out the other option, which would be a
sad statement for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a chance the costs can be such that when you look at
the risk and the incremental increase in revenue that you stop and
think, `Boy, this doesn't make much sense,' '' Graziano said.
``There is a chance of that happening, which is what we're trying
to decide now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not started evaluating (a new stadium) yet. We're
trying to show how we can make sense out of a renovation. ... But
when you look at renovation costs, it can get close to being as
high as building a brand-new stadium. That's a concern.'' &QL; 
Very rare air &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr.,  &UR; Juan Gonzalez,  &UR; Albert Belle and
 &UR; Andres
 &UR; Galarraga have in common? All could join a select club of players
who have driven in 400 runs over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, Gonzalez needed four, Griffey eight,
Galarraga nine and Belle 27 to join a list of 48 players who have
accomplished the rare feat, last done by  &UR; Vern Stephens from
1948-50. The three-year record is help by the immortal  &UR; Lou Gehrig,
who had 509 RBI from 1930-32. &QL; 
Cone of silence &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees pitcher  &UR; David Cone, attempting this season to
win his second Cy Young Award, needed to pitch 37 more innings
entering Saturday's start before a contractual clause that will
allow him to become a free agent kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   If Cone reaches 200 innings he can walk away from his 1999
contract. While Cone won't say for certain what he will do, he made
it known that he was impressed with  &UR; Paul O'Neill's new contract
extension, which will pay him far less than if the right-fielder
had gone on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Cone will probably try to pry a pay raise out
of
 &UR; George Steinbrenner for next season. &QL; 
AZ bad as he wants to be &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Montreal Manager  &UR; Felipe Alou, one of the most respected
managers in the game, had a strong position to take when asked his
thoughts on Bank One Ballpark last week, his first trip to Phoenix
for a big-league game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another building to make money _ a factory,'' Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   Alou was also amused that the Diamondbacks were so jacked after
winning the first game of the series last Monday, moving Arizona
within 1{ games of the Expos overall this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a stadium that costs that much, a payroll of $30
million, and they put catching us as a goal?'' Alou asked. ``That's
ridiculous.'' &QL; 
Captain Jack speaks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon's quotes of the week:
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to church the other day to pray for our pitchers, but
there weren't enough candles.''
</P>
<P>
   After learning his Reds are 51-45 against every club other than
Atlanta, Houston and San Diego: ``If we didn't have to play the
division leaders, we'd be fighting for the wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Where's Pookie?: The New York Mets first- and third-base coaches
are  &UR; Mookie Wilson and  &UR; Cookie Rojas, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If only those games didn't have to count: Seattle was 4-20 in
games decided by one run, entering the weekend. The Mariners are on
pace for the fewest one-run wins in a 162-game season, a record
held by the Texas Rangers. They managed 11 such wins in 1985. The
overall big-league record is nine by Cleveland in 1948 and 1953 New
York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Reggie Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; This guy's pitching better than ever and here's
 &UR; proof: Atlanta's  &UR; Greg Maddux can become the second pitcher since
1920 to win the ERA crown with an ERA of less than 2.00 in three
different years. Only Hall of Famer  &UR; Sandy Koufax has accomplished
the feat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; We'll throw in this Bob Feller  &UR; guy; great fastball,
 &UR; he's just a little old: The three pitchers Cleveland sent
Cincinnati on July 31, 1997 _  &UR; Scott Winchester,  &UR; Danny Graves and
 &UR; Jim Crowell _ have all undergone rotator cuff surgery. &QL; EXTRA
BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maddux won his 200th game last week, making three active
pitchers with at least 200 victories. Coincidentally, one of the
others has a locker just a few feet away _ Atlanta Braves teammate
 &UR; Dennis Martinez has 244 wins. Next on the list is Toronto's  &UR; Roger
Clemens, who has 228.
</P>
<P>
   For San Francisco to overtake San Diego for first place in the
National League West, the Padres would have to finish 17-17 while
the Giants would need to go 33-3. Of course, the Padres' real
battle is chasing the Braves for the home-field advantage in the NL
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Ageless reliever  &UR; Jesse Orosco pitched in his 55th game of the
season for Baltimore last Tuesday. Big deal? Well, for Orosco it
was. His 1999 contract automatically kicked in at that point.
Orosco, 41, is the Orioles oldest player, but he had the lowest ERA
at 2.70 entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Curtis Leskanic set the six-year-old Colorado Rockies record
for consecutive scoreless innings last week when he reached 19
innings, since upped to 21.  &UR; Willie Banks has the on-going
Diamondbacks record, also at 19 innings, for the five-month-old
club.
</P>
<P>
   Embattled Braves reliever  &UR; Mark Wohlers has sent signals that he
will agree to be sent on another rehabilitation assignment Aug. 31,
a move that will allow the club to bring up someone else to be
eligible for the post-season roster. Players brought up after Sept.
1 are not eligible for the playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's 5-4 victory over Baltimore last weekend prevented
the Indians from being swept by the Orioles in a series of at least
three games since 1971. Back then,  &UR; Mike Cuellar,  &UR; Pat Dobson and
 &UR; Jim Palmer threw three complete games in a four-game sweep at
Municipal Stadium. &QL; THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland wouldn't necessarily mind trading  &UR; David Justice
during the off-season. The problem is that Justice, who hasn't
complained once about being moved from outfield to designated
hitter, is owed $28 million over the next four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shawn Estes, a 19-game winner for San Francisco last season, is
looking at making a rehabilitation assignment next week. If all
goes well, Estes, who has begun throwing batting practice, could
return by the end of the month. Of course, that's a big maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners may be trying to change the player to be
named in the trade that sent  &UR; Randy Johnson to Houston in exchange
for four players. Initially, the Mariners agreed to receive pitcher
 &UR; John Halama. Now they apparently want an upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that keeping outfielder  &UR; Dante Bichette in a Rockies
uniform will take a four-year commitment from Colorado. Early word,
though, has the team worried about Bichette being 38 in the final
year of the contract. Colorado seems more intent on offering a
two-year deal with an option year.
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees General Manager  &UR; Brian Cashman is attempting to
pry pitcher  &UR; Brian Boehringer from San Diego. Boehringer used to
pitch for the Yankees. The Padres, who seem willing participants,
are seeking  &UR; Shea Morenz, a Double-A outfielder. The Yankees are
seeking insurance for injured reliever  &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Nelson. &QL; Includes information from other media sources. Pedro
Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
