<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS EXTEND FORD'S STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not so fast,  &UR; Ben Ford. &UR; You're not going anywhere,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed pitcher, who thought he was on his way back to
Triple-A Tucson on Friday after one day in the big leagues,
remained with the Diamondbacks instead, as right-hander  &UR; Bobby
Chouinard was placed on the 15-day disabled list because of a
strained posterior muscle in his throwing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, Ford would have to remain with
Tucson for 10 days before being recalled, but since this involves a
player going on the DL, he will be allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard had been experiencing some discomfort for a brief
period and thought it would go away, but it did not. Chouinard, who
pitched the ninth inning of Friday night's 1-0 loss in
Philadelphia, will return to Phoenix with the club after Monday's
game here against the Mets and begin a rehabilitation assignment in
Tucson. &QL; 
Bernard's back &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey returned to Shea Stadium on
Saturday for the first time since being traded from the Mets on
July 31. He responded with a pair of hits and was thrown out by
catcher
 &UR; Mike Piazza while trying to steal second in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on both sides of the fence here,'' said Gilkey, who
began his career with the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed playing here. The fans are pretty good in general.
They get on you when you're the home team, and they get on you when
you're the visiting team. They get on everybody. It's what they
do.'' &QL; 
White out again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder  &UR; Devon White sat out the game because of the same
tight hamstring that caused him to miss four games earlier in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting a game-winning homer in the 11th inning of the
second game of a doubleheader in Philadelphia on Thursday night,
White nearly sat out Friday night's game against the Phillies but
decided to play. He went 0 for 2 with a pair of walks.
</P>
<P>
   As he was when he was previously sidelined, White will be
evaluated daily. &QL; 
Worth the wait &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Michalak said it was the moment he had been working for all
his life _ a chance to pitch in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The dream came true Saturday, when he pitched two innings,
struck out two and gave up a run on one hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in from the bullpen (to begin the seventh
inning), the mound seemed like about three miles away,'' said
Michalak, called up from Triple-A Tucson late Thursday night.
``When I got there,  &UR; Jay ( &UR; Bell, &UR; shortstop) and  &UR; Kelly
( &UR; Stinnett, &UR; catcher) were waiting. I took a look around for a
second to take it all in, then concentrated and went to work.''
</P>
<P>
   After striking out the first two batters he faced in the seventh
inning,  &UR; Brian McRae and  &UR; Todd Hundley, &UR; Michalak got  &UR; Carlos
 &UR; Baerga on a pop-up to right for the third out. In the eighth, he
gave up a bloop double to leadoff man  &UR; Rey Ordonez, &UR; who later
scored on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Of the double that fell into shallow left-center, Michalak said,
``He (Ordonez) did a good piece of hitting. That's part of the
game. I was pleased with how I pitched.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
