<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATS' CALLEN SHOWS HIS STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ For a year, he tried to outrun anonymity. Friday night,
there was a sign he might do it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Leon Callen outran the Arizona defense.
</P>
<P>
   On one play, he bounced off a would-be tackler at Arizona
Stadium and raced for 50 of his scrimmage-high 71 yards.
</P>
<P>
   For one moment, Callen, who had six carries, looked like the
``Parade'' ``Magazine'' All-America prized prospect he was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in between? A serious knee injury in 1997 and
grade problems sidelined Callen, also a sprinter with world-class
speed in the 100 meters (1.5) and 200 meters (21.3).
</P>
<P>
   Then, there other prized recruits  &UR; Trung Canidate and  &UR; Leo
 &UR; Mills. But Canidate, the designated starter from Phoenix, is
recovering from an injury. Mills, a freshman and another ``Parade''
All-American, also was impressive during the scrimmage with six
carries for 29 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a book. Chapter 1: Leon doesn't know if he's going
to make it,'' Callen said before the Wildcats opened their
preseason camp. ``Chapter 2: Leon is back in school. Chapter 3: Leo
Mills. Chapter 4: Trung Canidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final chapter is going to be: How are they going to
co-exist?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Callen gives the Wildcats some critical depth.
It's not known when Canidate will return. He is trying to
strengthen his right leg, which was in a cast for five weeks
because of a stress fracture. Mills' academic eligibility is still
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the battle for the starting job appears to be between
Callen and reliable senior &UR; Kelvin Eafon, who rushed seven times for
25 yards and a touchdown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats won't practice Monday, the start of classes. Coach
 &UR; Dick
 &UR; Tomey said his team will scrimmage again on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback &UR; Ortege Jenkins appeared to have an edge over rival
 &UR; Keith Smith with his scrimmage performance. Jenkins completed 8 of
18 attempts for 133 yards. Smith was 1 for 6 for 5 yards and an
interception. But Jenkins wasn't happy. ``I wasn't in an OJ mood,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest adjustment starts this week, Tomey said at the
conclusion Wednesday of camp at Cochise College near Douglas. ``The
guys have been able to handle tough conditions and tough
discipline,'' he said. ``The next week's adjustment in Tucson _
with academic details, books to buy, players' friends around, our
guys living all over town _ will be much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Possible third-string quarterback &UR; Peter Hansen, a freshman from
Palo Alto, Calif., is 6 feet 7. His size has earned a nickname from
Smith and Jenkins. ``Baby Leaf,'' referring to former Washington
State quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf, a 6-foot-5 San Diego Chargers
rookie. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
