</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SCRIMMAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS SHOW WHY THEY HAVE HIGH HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP TONTOZONA _ Just minutes after his team closed camp with a
public scrimmage, Arizona State Coach Bruce Snyder called his
players together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can sense it, but people expect you to be
something special,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A record 5,000 fans congregated outside Payson for a sneak
preview of the much-hyped Sun Devils. What they saw was a defense
that will be better than expected, new players with big-play
capabilities and a kicking game that still needs work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A national championship, that's our goal,'' quarterback Ryan
Kealy said. ``We expect nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the hits and misses:
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tenuous state of Marlon's Farlow's future, ASU is
deep at running back.
</P>
<P>
   With Heisman Trophy candidate J.R. Redmond playing sparingly _
Snyder knows what he can do _ the coach got a closer look at
Daveron Hightower, Gerald Green and Larry Montgomery, the Nos. 2, 3
and 4 tailbacks, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower, who was slowed by a blood clot in his right big toe,
carried 10 times for 47 yards and two touchdowns. Green, who
quickly is becoming a crowd favorite, rushed for 49 yards and one
touchdown, and Montgomery carried five times for 42 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't really plant and cut like I want to,'' Hightower
said. ``That wasn't my best.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils unveiled their new secret weapon: Steve Campbell,
special teams player extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder had talked about using the 6-foot-8 quarterback to block
field goals, but he hadn't practiced it during camp. Campbell was
sent out during the scrimmage to do exactly that and he blocked
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go. I'm a quarterback and everybody wants to talk
about blocking field goals,'' Campbell said smiling. ``Actually, it
feels really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who is battling for the No. 2 spot with redshirt
freshman Chad Elliott, has had the best spring of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure this will probably be the last year I go out and play
quarterback,'' he said. ``I might as well go out and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The kicking game is still shaky.
</P>
<P>
   With efforts of 45, 55 and 55 yards, redshirt freshman Stephen
Baker showed he may blossom into a solid punter. But neither Baker
nor Mike Gauthier made a convincing argument for the starting
place-kicking job.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Nycz was so consistent last season, it was easy to forget
just how valuable he was. Snyder didn't seem overly concerned, and
believes both players have the potential to be like Nycz.
</P>
<P>
   The team has plenty of big-play potential.
</P>
<P>
   Senior wide receiver Lenzie Jackson worked on improving his
speed this season and he seemed almost a step faster. He connected
with Kealy for a 75-yard pass play.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Alfred Williams, who has been lost in the hype
surrounding ASU's other newcomers, showed why Snyder has talked him
up recently and had the scrimmage's only interception.
</P>
<P>
   What defensive concerns?
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' front held its own and didn't seem to lose a
step when the second team came in. Returning starting tackle Albrey
Battle was joined by tackle Ryan Reilly and ends Quincy Yancy and
Derrick Ford on the first team.
</P>
<P>
   Junior college transfer Junior Ioane, a defensive tackle, made
one of the plays of the game when he stuffed running back Green and
tossed him aside.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers Adam Archuleta, Joe Cesta and Stephen Trejo, who are
expected to start the season, as well as Eric Fields, who may very
well see as many minutes, played well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-22-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
