<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WADSWORTH DEAL ON HORIZON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No longer are Cardinals officials optimistic they will get
first-round draft pick  &UR; Andre Wadsworth signed before the start of
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides remain almost $20 million apart and negotiations
appear at a standstill because both sides have dug in their heels.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth is demanding a four- or five-year deal that voids
after as early as three seasons while the Cardinals remain adamant
they won't give him any contract that includes voidable years.
</P>
<P>
   The only possible solution, unless the Cardinals can convince
Wadsworth their word is gold and they will positively, absolutely
tear up the contract after three seasons, is for a short deal _ one
to three years _ but the team is unable to give Wadsworth the $10
million signing bonus he is seeking unless the contract is spread
out over six years.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, the Cardinals didn't take Wadsworth
seriously when he said he would go back to school and re-enter the
draft next year. They figured he had a target date when he would
report and that he would make sure he was in camp before the Sept.
6 season opener at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals now know Wadsworth isn't bluffing. He is serious
about sitting out the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   He's not desperate for money. He isn't from poverty. In fact,
his father owns a successful business on the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   To Wadsworth it's a matter of principle, but it also should be a
matter of interest, the interest he won't get on the $10 million
bonus the Cardinals are offering.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans can't understand how Wadsworth can pass up $10
million. But he is convinced he can get a similar bonus in next
year's draft even if he isn't picked as high as third overall
again.
</P>
<P>
   But if he sits out, he and the Cardinals lose, and nobody
suffers as much as his agent,  &UR; Eugene
 &UR; Parker, who will have to find a way to explain to prospective
clients why he turned down the third-biggest signing bonus in NFL
rookie history.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals lose because they will take the field without the
best defensive lineman prospect to enter the NFL in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Their image, the image they've worked so hard to change, also
will take a beating. They will be reminded over and over again that
the last first-round pick to sit out an entire season also was
drafted by the Cardinals _ Colorado State quarterback  &UR; Kelly
Stouffer in 1987, a year before the team moved to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   So far, public opinion has been on the Cardinals side during the
Wadsworth holdout. But that will change if they begin the regular
season without him, and, especially, if they don't win.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will accuse them of being cheap, just of being inflexible
and showing no creativity in trying to get the deal done.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth will survive. He'll just play for another team in
1999, one that gives voidable contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will take a bigger hit as they try to get a new
multipurpose, domed stadium. &QL; 
Back to future &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So now Oakland Raiders owner  &UR; Al Davis wants to move back to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the dynamic football team that sells out stadiums and
wears silver and black,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   His team has sold little more than 30,000 season tickets this
year, fewer than the Cardinals, who play the Raiders next Saturday
in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders moved back to Oakland in 1995 after Davis was
guaranteed by the Oakland Marketing Association that 175 luxury
suites would be sold. Many haven't even been built yet. &QL; 
Rough ride &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers punter  &UR; Josh Miller, an Arizona product, and
kicker  &UR; Norm Johnson missed the team's bus back to Pittsburgh from
training camp in Latrobe, Pa. So they climbed inside the equipment
truck and rode 60 miles.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a comfortable ride. Around one turn, some equipment
moved and buried Johnson, who could have taken a cab for $70. &QL; 
Short shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Chiefs linebacker  &UR; Terry Wooden, a resident of
Scottsdale, still is furious that the team wouldn't release him in
the off-season. ``My feelings haven't changed at all,'' he said.
``If anything, every day they just grow, and I want to be here less
and less, and my resentment grows more and more. Terry Wooden is
not a backup. It's tough to get up every day, and it's tough to
come out on the field, and it's tough to find enthusiasm. Every day
is a living hell.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals sign Wadsworth, they will have three rookies
who were defensive players of the year in their conferences _
Wadsworth, a Florida State product, in the Atlantic Coast
Conference, Arizona State linebacker  &UR; Pat Tillman in the Pac-10 and
Southern Mississippi linebacker  &UR; Marchant Kenney in Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell wants it known that his
wife,  &UR; Tanya, and son,  &UR; Tylan, do not have sickle cell anemia but
carry the trait.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay guard  &UR; Jorge Diaz, on the rising Buccaneers: ``Last
season, we were raw and hungry, and we ate the appetizer. This
season, we want the whole meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
