<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BIG-GAME PERMIT SYSTEM WORKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRT BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There may be nothing more controversial among hunters
than the computer drawing for big-game permits.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is one of the fastest growing states in terms of human
population. Its big-game populations aren't growing that fast. In
fact, recent drought years have drastically reduced the number of
mule deer permits. Even elk, which are extremely adaptable, took a
hit.
</P>
<P>
   The number of big-game permits fell as the number of hunters
wanting them rose.
</P>
<P>
   I once was drawn for elk three years in a row. I haven't been
drawn since. When I was getting the permits, friends (I guess they
were) gave me a full ration of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game and Fish is setting it up so you'll get drawn,'' they
said with a snarl. Since I've gone several years without being
drawn, they've ignored the situation. Perhaps they think Game and
Fish has determined that I shouldn't get drawn anymore. Whatever,
they're liking it.
</P>
<P>
   The computer draw isn't a setup. I know two high-ranking Game
and Fish officials who messed up their elk applications this year.
They were rejected. One was making application for two friends at
the same time. Of course, they were rejected, too. You think this
guy hasn't faced the needle? It's brutal out there.
</P>
<P>
   The computer draw is impersonal. For a long time, it made its
random decisions with no mitigation. If you applied for a trophy
bull elk permit, it meant the odds were overwhelming against you
getting it. There were so many more applications than permits that
those who were drawn should have been dancing in the streets. Some
of them probably were.
</P>
<P>
   But, there always was this problem of applicants who had a black
cloud over their heads. They'd go year after year submitting an
application and never get drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seemed, had a solution, except Game and Fish. I've
seen some of the darndest proposals from hunters to correct the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   The old guys thought they deserved to bypass the younger ones
for a permit, figuring they might be dead before they got drawn
again. Who said so? I'm getting to be pretty ancient myself, and I
never figured I had more rights to a permit than anyone else. There
were some applicants who said they hadn't been drawn for seven
years. That black cloud over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Then, believe it or not, a couple of Valley residents, Larry
Knipp and Dan Westfall, came up with a plan that even got the
attention of Game and Fish. They came to a public meeting of the
Arizona Game and Fish Commission in Flagstaff with more than a
``pity me'' syndrome. They laid out the mathematics in a brochure,
showing how a more equitable system could be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Every year a hunter wasn't drawn for, say, elk, a bonus point
would be recorded on the file. If the hunter was willing to take
Game and Fish's hunter education course, there would be a another,
one-time bonus point. The latter was Game and Fish's idea.
</P>
<P>
   For any given hunt number, 10 percent of the permits would be
reserved for those with the highest number of bonus points. If
hunters with the highest numbers weren't drawn, they'd also be
eligible for the regular computer drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish bean counters checked out the mathematics, found
them to be valid, and the plan was implemented.
</P>
<P>
   This year's drawing was the second that the bonus point system
has been in effect. And it's working.
</P>
<P>
   The current system is applied to elk, antelope, bighorn sheep
and bison. Deer will be included next year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the maximum bonus points a hunter could accrue was
eight. We'll give you some figures first, then explain them with
the help of Ray Lee, big game supervisor for Game and Fish.
</P>
<P>
   Let's use elk as an example. Seventy-one of 225 applicants with
eight bonus points were drawn for an elk permit for a success ratio
of 31.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There were 616 with seven bonus points, and 346 were drawn for a
56.17 percent success rate. The 1,296 persons with six bonus points
drew 617 permits, a 47.61 percent ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're going to ask why those with eight bonus points drew a
smaller percentage of permits than those with seven or six.
</P>
<P>
   Lee can explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people with eight points went after an early bull
(trophy) rifle hunt,'' he said. ``The chances of getting that
permit normally are 100 to 1 against. The people with all the
points seemed to put in for hunts that are harder to get. The odds
are against them, even with bonus points.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd gone after an archery cow permit, their chances
would have been more than 90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried for a November bull hunt in Unit 7. I didn't get it.
Someone with eight bonus points would have had a good chance
because the computer favors those points. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
