<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Aug. 23. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPICE (Phoenix) _ They're here. The Spice Girls grabbed a stage in
the dessert Saturday amid reports that two of the teenie-bopper
sensations are pregnant and a swirl of British tabloid reporters
wanting to report on the upcoming love children. Meanwhile, young
girls are still agog over the singers. By DAVID PROFITT. Move in
`A` category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DRUGWAR _ America's drug czar will soon propose sweeping remedies
to try to patch gaping holes in the Southwest border, where tons of
cocaine and marijuana continue to slip through undetected. The
proposals, the result of two years of study, will be announced this
week and will include putting a federal official in charge of each
of the 24 entry points and naming a coordinator to oversee the
entire 2,000-mile border. By JEFFBARKER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HILLARY (Undated) _ Women's rights advocates around the nation seem
to be worried that Hillary Rodham Clinton's continuing gracious
attitude toward her husband's infidelity reflects submission and
repression, the opposite of what a feminist role model should be.
By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONICA (Undated) _ Perhaps never has a tale of a sexual encounter
offered such potential for profit: Monica Lewinsky's financial
future looks very promising. By MARTIN VAN DER WERF. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLINICS (undated) _ Imagine a medical clinic where your surgeon
isn't really a surgeon; he's a dermatologist who took extra
classes. The staffer who reads your X-rays is learning as he goes;
other clinic employees are so untrained they don't even know know
cardiopulmonary resuscitation. If a crisis erupts during your
postsurgical recovery, your best bet is to call the Fire
Department. Many outpatient procedures are not regulated by the
state, by medical associations, by the federal government or anyone
else. By JODIE SNYDER and SUSIE STECKNER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MARRIAGE (Phoenix) _ They have already promised God to love, honor
and cherish. But about 75 married couples wanted to find out
Saturday how to get the state of Arizona involved. ``Before God,
we're vowed. We've already made the commitment that divorce is not
an option,'' said 35-year-old Kim Schmidt, standing next to her
34-year-old husband, Marc. The Schmidts, who've been married 15
years, were among the information seekers who attended a seminar at
the downtown Hyatt in Phoenix on Arizona's new covenant marriage
law. By RICHARD RUELAS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COL (Phoenix) _ Sooner or later, you'll catch on. You'll be
downtown, looking west toward the Washington Monument, and see only
a saguaro. Or you'll be on the eastside, where the Capitol dome
should dominate the skyline, watching instead as the dome of a
thundercloud boils over an unbroken horizon. And you'll know _ in
spite of this newspaper's distortions and deceptions _ that you DO
NOT live in Washington, D.C. You live in Phoenix. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
