<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS WITHDRAWS APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MEICH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ After Friday night's defeat to the Toronto Blue Jays,
Angels manager Terry Collins said he had about a ``zero percent''
chance of winning an appeal of a controversial ruling in the second
inning by home-plate umpire and crew chief Larry Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Collins withdrew his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 1-1 in the bottom of the second inning on Friday,
the Angels had the bases loaded, with Edmonds on third, when Gary
DiSarcina lined a single to right field. The Blue Jays then threw
Garret Anderson, who had hardly moved off second base, out at
third.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck touched second, saw Anderson and retreated toward
first when the Jays threw to second for the inning-ending double
play. Edmonds had long since scored. But because of the forceout,
Edmonds' run didn't count and DiSarcina didn't get the hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were too many screwy things going on out there at the
same time,'' Collins said. ``Larry Bennett has seen more games than
I have, and he'd never seen that. And I didn't tell him I thought
he was wrong. But I thought (Jimmy Edmonds should have scored), so
I appealed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday afternoon, Collins invited writers to visit his
clubhouse office, where he had a copy of the game's rules,
including 7.08 (j), in ``The Runner'' section.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Collins entered his office and studied the
passage further. He must have acknowledged the futility of fighting
the call then, because an Angels official announced the withdrawal
in the press box in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds sits: Angels center fielder Jim Edmonds, who strained
back muscles while running into the wall in the ninth inning on
Friday night, was replaced in the lineup on Saturday by Reggie
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, with his back to home plate, got a glove on the ball,
hit by Toronto right fielder Shawn Green. But in an instant the
ball popped loose, Edmonds looked down for it and momentum carried
him into the wall. Green wound up with a triple. Collins said he
hopes Edmonds returns by Monday, when the Angels begin their
five-game series against the Yankees in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Martin gets a start: Collins said he will play Paco Martin in
place of DiSarcina at shortstop this afternoon against the Blue
Jays. Martin, who has four hits in his last 34 at-bats, was
activated off the disabled list (strained neck) on Friday. Collins
said he wants DiSarcina, 30, fresh for the team's 10-game trip to
New York, Boston and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching matchups: Steve Sparks, Saturday night's starter, will
start the second game of Wednesday's doubleheader against the
Yankees, according to Collins. Jack McDowell (Monday), Omar
Olivares (Tuesday), Jeff Juden (Wednesday's first game) and Chuck
Finley (Thursday) had already been penciled in for their starts
against the Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells, who tossed a perfect game earlier this season, is
slated to start Wednesday's second for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (9-6) starts for the Angels today (1:05 p.m.) against
Woody Williams (9-8). Finley is 7-6 with a 4.40 earned-run average
in more than 143 innings lifetime against the Jays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
